    'from' => 'alvin plummer plummer@hubble.sheridanc.o',
    'body' => '--0-488322767-776636668:#21768
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; CHARSET=US-ASCII


     First off: I attached two files concerning the nobility, from a
recent discussion on Usenet.  If you already saw them, consider it \'for
the record\'.  Of course, further comment is appreciated.
     From my point of view, the noble rankings in Traveller are only
the bare-bones of the Imperial nobility.  Aside from non-human/human,
rank/blood, and high/young divisions within the nobility, there is also
  -- traditionalist vs. modern (i.e. are clones legal heirs?  How about
\'geneticly perfected\' nobles, more attractive and smarter than the
commoners?) 
  -- imperial vs. regional vs. pan-racial/pan-religious nobles
  -- merchantile vs. military nobles 
  (I\'d bet good money that these issues have been discussed before, but
the old archives are still inaccessible and these questions are too
interesting)

     Secondly: I don\'t have a copy of the old MegaTraveller rules: could
someone fill me in concerning which sectors are in which domains? 

     Thirdly: There was once a game called Invasion: Earth, where the
Third Imperium faced off against the Solomani of Terra.  What I want to
know is: 1) What are the main strategic considerations of invading a
            high-tech, heavily-defended world without just nuking it?
            Should you go for the do-or-die assault on the \'hardpoints\'
            of system defence?  Or start at the poles - or the oceans - 
            and work your way in?
         2) What are the advantages/disadvantages of the invaders carrying
            fighter aircraft, rather than just using the warships for 
            orbital fire?  I understand that the fighters can carry
            a lot of very useful payload, but couldn\'t you just launch the 
            payload from near orbit, without risking the pilots on the AA
            fire (I believe it was Peurelle (spell-check) who got rid of 
            future fighters, since high-tech AA becomes just too (beep)
            accurate).
         3) How would High-population woulds configure their system defences?
            At TL 15?  At TL 12?  At TL 10? As an example, how
            is Capital/Core defended?  How would this defence contrast
            with a \'troubled, strategic\' world, like Terra/Solomani Rim?
            With the defence of a Depot?  With the defence of a minor,
            backwater world?
         4) The Third Imperium chose to create hardpoints throughout their 
            their empire; information/communication nodes called scout
            bases, military ones called naval bases, and fortress-systems
            called Depots.  Why did the Imperium choose this method -
            basically, thinly spreading warships thorughout the Imperium - to
            protect itself?  If they had chosen a \'multiple hard-shell
            route\' (i.e. the Roman frontier, the Great Wall of China), 
            there would be few assets available for regionalists to launch a
            rebellion.  Moreover, the only reason I can think of for
            spreading ships like this is A) the military is a militia (good
            enough for the colonial navies, but not so good at accounting
            for serious Imperial warships in Massillia, say) or B) Imperial
            suppression of dissidents within the Empire (rather likely,
            now that I think about it.  Of course, no hint of major
            anti-Imperial hostility is given in Classic Traveller, but GDW
            never worry\'s about continuity, do they :->)
         5) Apparently, the defense of mains (long, jump-1 routes) is
            crucial to the Imperium.  I suspect that the top/end points
            of these mains would be closely watched.  What\'s the best way
            to do so? (Incidentally, Norris successfully defended his
            Domain from Virus by massing his fleets at these chokepoints)
            I suspect that it is exactly for this purpose - and
            for defending High-pop worlds - why capital ships are built at
            all.  Why ships, and not static installations a la the Death
Star?
            After all, you can run a static hardpoint a good bit
            more cheaply than you can a mobile one.  (why dies \'bitzberg\'
            and \'Magnot Line\' keeps coming into my head? ;-) 
         4) The \'High Guard\' of the book of the same title refers to the
            convoy\'s watch over refuelling merchantmen (I never read the
            book - it\'s a guess). This principle is extendable to cover a
            host of circumstances, of course.  Am I missing anything about
            the High Guard\'s function? 

Again, I feel that these questions have been hit upon 10 times already,
but... I\'d love to know.

Alvn Plummer
(Who really, REALLY needs those old TML bundles...)
