David P. Summers (DPSummers@Ames.arc.nasa.gov) wrote:
> [concerns original Traveller]
> The Imperium has a hereditary fuedal structure, rom the Emperor down to
> the Dukes who rule the subsectors.  There are also lower levels of
> nobility (Barons and Knight).  My question is how this relates to 
> to rule of individual worlds.  Do they all have their own governements
> or does the Imperium rule any directly?  If so, how many and who rules
> them?  Barons?


   It depends. :)  Most nobles don\'t rule, and most worlds have thier own
governments (but all have some sort of noble representation between them
and the Imperium).  The more important worlds will normally have Dukes and
Counts associated with them, the with most senior of the subsector\'s Dukes
being in charge of the subsector.  If my memory is accurate, the Duke of
Regina does not rule Regina (but was in charge of the subsector\'s (and
sector\'s?)) Imperial government; the Marquis Aramis, however, does rule
Aramis directly.

   There is a distinction made between honour, rank, and high nobles.
Honour nobles have gained for performing some service (military, science,
etc.); rank nobles are the less important local Imperial representatives and
administrators; high nobles are the oldest and most powerful nobles.


