Hmmm, big question.  It depends on what worlds.  The Third Imperium is
a "feudal confederation".  Member worlds pay fairly minimal taxes to 
support the Imperial government and interstellar military, accepts the
jusrisdiction of the Imperial Ministry of Justice over certain "High
Laws" that the empire requires all sophonts to adhere to, and in return
get protection of trade, diplomatic arbitration with Imperial and extra-
Imperial worlds, but are otherwise allowed to control their own affairs
in-system.  Some (Archduke Dulinor comes to mind) think that the Imperium
should require world governments to behave in a democratic manner, but
in general the Moot doesn\'t agree.  

Many worlds are not ruled directly by the Imperial nobility, but have
locally chosen leaders.  Some worlds are ruled directly by the Office
of the Emperor, like Terra/Sol or Capital/Core, for various political
reasons.  Before the Rim War and martial law on Terra, it had a 
Secretary-General.  However, many other worlds are run either by 
"rank nobles" who hold positions in the Imperial bureaucracy, or by 
"high nobles" who directly oversee Imperial territories.  Some worlds 
are also ruled directly because they are Reserves, or Depots, and some
are placed under interdict and left totally alone.  But the vast majority 
of worlds are run locally.

There are far more honor nobles ("celebrities" of any stripe from a
Sir Alec Guinness to a Sir Isaac Newton to a Viscount Montgomery of 
Alamein) and rank nobles than high nobles, but no exact figures exist.

Let\'s see if I can figure out about how many high nobles we have:

Archduke (SocSt G): They run the seven multi-sector Domains.  Not 
                    counting Sylea (the emperor\'s domain), but counting
                    Norris in Deneb after 1116, there are six.
Duke     (SocSt F): Twenty senior subsector dukes are recognized as 
                    sector dukes.  There are about another 200-300 
                    subsector dukes.  (The Imperium has territory in
                    more than twenty sectors, but they don\'t all rate
                    sector dukes.)
Count    (SocSt E): At two to three worlds each, there are probably
                    four thousand Imperial counties.
Marquis  (SocSt D): At one world a piece (roughly), figure about nine
                    thousand or so.

Figure about 13200, and you have a fair guess for the *high* nobles 
above SocSt-C.  However, some will be overlap (the same person has 
*two* or more titles), some will be vacant, and some positions will 
be filled by lesser nobles that usually expected, especially on the 
frontier.  In places these nobles will be in charge locally -- in 
others, they will merely be the local Imperial authority (which isn\'t 
exactly small peanuts itself), especially in the case of rank nobles.  
In most cases, you get to choose what works for you.

If you want to find more information, your best bets are:

--> GDW
MT _Imperial Encyclopedia_   good general info, best bet
CT _Library Data N-Z_        older, but ok if you can find it
TNE _Survival Margin_        useful background info, Rebellion era

--> Digest Group
_Travellers\' Digest_ #9      Capital/Core issue
_Travellers\' Digest_ #18     "Concise History of the Imperium" article

CT == Traveller; MT == MegaTraveller; TNE == Traveller: The New Era

I\'d also recommend the Traveller Mailing List, but it\'s undergoing a 
change of moderation right now, so it\'s off-line.

Happy Travelling!

Steve Bonneville
