    'topic' => 'Boring Review: Look-over of Classic Rules',
    'body' => '
Last night, I was looking over the Classic books 0 to 3, and the Intro
adventure "The Imperial Fringe", just to re-familiarize myself with the
heritage of Traveller.  (I typically play using TNE rules)

Brief observations below...
  1) "The Imperial Fringe"
      As was previously mentioned, the first mission - to survey all 440
worlds in the Spinward Marches - is a whopper!  If you spend two weeks at
each system, you\'d finish just in time for the Rebellion at 1116!
      However, it\'s a great way to earn a living ... that\'s 50,000 Credits
per system, and an extra 10,000 credits after all systems have been
surveyed ... a grand total of 26,400,000 Credits.  Almost enough to buy
the Aurora, at 29.43 MCr.  

      Looking at the library data, I note that the First Imperium was
founded at 476 AD ... just as Rome fell.  And that the Vilani invented
jump drives at 4715 BC.   Also, the First and Third Imperiums both lasted
about 1100 - 1200 years.

   2) Book 0: An Introduction to Traveller
      The dullest book in the lot ... if your already familiar with
role-playing.  Still, it should be read once a year, just to remind
yourself of the basic tools of role-playing.

   3) Book 1: Characters and Combat
      Does anyone know who "Mary Beth" is? (The book is dedicated to her)
      
      Hey! Everyone is assummed to be in the military services! (Or a
scout).  I like the 8+ basic throw for combat.  Then again, I feel that the
loose, free-flowing nature of Classic Traveller is it\'s greatest strength.  A
short selections of useful tools and vechiles and off you go!

      However, that\'s _not_ why I like Traveller today.  I hardly ever
play the game as role-play.  Instead, I just build things...and more
things...and more things.  I like Traveller (TNE) due to the tools it
gives me as a designer, not as a role-playing enviroment.  I suspect that
this change of viewpoint is prevalent in GDW, too.  

   4) Book 2: Starships

      "The Low Lottery: It is customary for the captain to contribute Cr10
out of each low passage towards a lottery.  Each low passenger randomly
guesses the number of low passengers who will survive the trip. If the
winner does not himself survive, the captain recieves the money.  The
ship\'s steward administers the lottery."  NO COMMENT.

      Hey, I actually LIKE the old \'Jump drive A, Manuver Drive A, Power
Plant A\' format.  This reminds me of a \'soapbox opinion\' I have: Traveller
should have two levels of complexity, the \'Quick and Dirty\' and the \'Slow
and Accurate\'.  Okay, off the soapbox.

      An interesting stress on \'computer programs\', and _the volume they
take up_ (Hard disk space?)  I know that this factor of Classic traveller
was not followed up, but it has potential still...

      I like the education rule..."you can increase your education rank up
to your intelligence level".  _This_ is going into my campaign, and
perhaps a limit that "education may not be higher than intelligence" in
caracter generation.

      In the Trade section, I\'ll only note that the base price of grain is
Cr 300, and for radioactives it\'s 1,000,000.   Compare this with Mega of
TNE formats, where they are equal. ( I spent Friday night designing a sane
trade pricing table for myself).
      
   5) Book 3: Worlds and Adventures
     
      Basic world design.  Standard equipment profile, but...what\'s this? 
Food and Overhead?  Bloody awsome! (Reminds me of the lack of washrooms on
the Enterprise, for some reason...)  More things to be directly copied
into my campaign...  Also, I\'d like to note the steamships, motor boats,
and a submersible (Why aren\'t these things in TNE?)

      And, of course, pisonics.  (Ugh.)

 
Summary: Classic Traveller is a good set of rules for role-playing, rather
         than world building/equuipment designing.

Alvin Plummer
(Who really, really Should Be Studying)   

