    'topic' => 'METEOR! and Invasions',
    'body' => 'Alvin Plummer (plummer@hubble.sheridanc.on.ca) writes:

>      1) What are the main strategic considerations of invading a
>         high-tech, heavily-defended world without just nuking it?

Erwin Fritz (erwin@fritz.cuug.ab.ca) replies:

> Actually, why nuke it?  It\'s cheaper and more effective to just nudge a
> few asteroids into a carefully calculated course intersecting with the
> world (and with the ocean, if you can manage).

[pragmatic, but valid, reasons why neither, deleted]

Or, worse still, put a ship which is primarily a large mass of rock
on a very high relative vector to the world but *in another system*,
and then jump it in at the 100-diameter limit of the target.  Even
small ships can pack a gigaton-class punch at impact, and the world
would only have a turn or less to react.  Precision may not be very
terrific, but it doesn\'t need to be if you\'re using this tactic.
There are even methods you could use to give the thing some guidance
and possibly even eject and save the expensive jump drive.

However, this sort of tactic doesn\'t look that common in Imperial
warfare unti the Rebellion-era, when the gloves came off because
the emperor at Capital didn\'t quite get why this was so *stupid*.
Among other reasons, with the technology the Imperial worlds had,
this sort of attack may kill a lot of people, and still leave the
defensive systems in place unless you are willing to scourge the
entire planet.  "Destroying the enemy is not the acme of skill;
capturing the enemy is the acme of skill."  And at Terra, the 
Imperials had to be *very* careful not to damage the planet too
much, for political reasons.  (Luckily, the Solomani Confederation
felt the same way.)  Of course, this is a game.  In RL, I shudder
to think of the carnage possible.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonnevil@mermaid.micro.umn.edu>



