    'topic' => 'Asteroids and planetbusters...',
    'body' => 'Sorry for jumping in here late, if this has laready been brought up, but
I\'ve been out of town...

Erwin:

> Actually, why nuke it?  It\'s cheaper and more effective to just nudge
> a few asteroids into a carefully calculated course intersecting with
> the world (and with the ocean, if you can manage).  Lucifer\'s Hammer,
> by Larry Niven, does a good job of describing this, although he talks
> about a large comet.   The advantage of this is that you still have a
> habitable world after it\'s all over.

 Well, if Lucifer\'s Hammer (and other works) and that comet that
slammed Jupiter recently were any guide, I doubt very seriously that you
would still have "a habitable world after it\'s all over".  Unless "it\'s
all over" refers to several hundred to several thousand years after the
impact.

 I also would suggest that (depending on the Rules Set under
consideration) it would be relatively easy for the defenders to
obliterate your incoming asteroid.  This, of course, depends on the
correlation of forces in the system...
 And, it might do to keep in mind that if you can do unto HIS world,
he can do unto YOUR world...


> Your point about fighters being obsolete due to the accuracy of AA
> doesn\'t work though.  Assume that there are two types of AA:  solid
> projectiles (missiles, mostly) and energy beams (lasers, mostly).  The
> solid projectiles need time to travel from launch point to the
> fighter.  No matter how accurate the projectile, the fighter will see
> it coming and be able to do something about it.  Energy beams, though,
> are a different matter. The fighter will not have warning about a
> targeted beam.  Unfortunately, the cost of these weapons favours the
> use of missiles.  Thus, the effectiveness of fighters has been reduced
> because of AA but not eliminated.

 A silly point.  If missiles are not especially effective as
anti-fighter weapons, then they will not be used.  After all ONE really
good AA weapon is much better than twelve nearly useless AA weapons...
 Again, the Rules Set in question has a lot to do with the usefulness
of any given weapon against any given target...


>>         3) How would High-population woulds configure their system
>>            defences?  At TL 15?  At TL 12?  At TL 10? As an example,
>>            how is Capital/Core defended?  How would this defence
>>            contrast with a \'troubled, strategic\' world, like
>>            Terra/Solomani Rim?  With the defence of a Depot?  With
>>            the defence of a minor, backwater world?

> High pop worlds at TL 13+ should consider placing a few spinal
> mount-type guns on their surface and on their satellites.  A system
> navy would help  as well but having large particle accelerator cannon
> and meson guns sure would help against the asteroid-bombing scheme.

 <snicker>  Why bother with "a few spinal mount-type guns"?  Let\'s
put several hundred of them.  Or perhaps several thousand.  Plus a few
hundred thousand sensor arrays scattered over the surface.  Plus around
50,000 bay-mount missile launchers.  Plus anywhere from several dozen
BIG SDBs to several thousand medium size SDBs to several tens of
thousands of fighters (50-90T range)...Or some combination.

 Capital/Core has eight or ten deep meson guns inside the Imperial
Palace alone.  Probably several thousand scattered throughout the
planet, plus similar numbers deployed in every gas giant in the
system...

 Terra has no planetary defenses to speak of, of course.  Primarily
to make it vulnerable to the Imperial Fleet.  Sure that means that the
Solomani can take it away from the Impies easily, but it also means that
the Impies can take it back easily when the time comes...

 And "minor, backwater worlds" have no significant planetary
defenses, and no way to stop even "chicken thieves" like most Vargr
Corsair bands from doing/taking whatever they want to...



Steve Bonneville:

> Or, worse still, put a ship which is primarily a large mass of rock
> on a very high relative vector to the world but *in another system*,
> and then jump it in at the 100-diameter limit of the target.  Even
> small ships can pack a gigaton-class punch at impact, and the world
> would only have a turn or less to react.  Precision may not be very
> terrific, but it doesn\'t need to be if you\'re using this tactic.
> There are even methods you could use to give the thing some guidance
> and possibly even eject and save the expensive jump drive.

 Pretty clever idea really, if you like destroying worlds.  ONe minor
problem with it, though.   Ships DO misjump now and then.  It might be
intensely embarrassing if such a weapon misjumped to one of YOUR major
worlds, wouldn\'t it?  Is the effect (impressive, but remember that the
other guy may do unto you also) worth the (admittedly minor) risk that
you might blow up your own world (and make yourself look like one of the
Galaxy\'s biggest fools at the same time)? ;-)


    ----Steve Higginbotham (back again....)


