    'month' => '08',
    'index' => 'aa024',
    'body' => 'Alvin Plummer asks about Invasion: Earth and, more generally, about
invading a high-tech high-pop world and, even more broadly, about Imperial
defense strategy.  I don\'t really have answers, just more questions, but I
hope that they\'ll be helpful ones.  I won\'t address all of Mr. Plummer\'s
issues here, but they\'re all important and worth discussing.  I, too, need
to pay a visit to the ftp site.

1) Main strategic considerations in attacking a hi-t hi-p world:
I suppose that the _strategic_ considerations are "why is this world
important to my plans for expansion, defense, or whatever?"  "what
advantages inure to invading this world? what costs?" "do I need to take
over this world\'s production and divert it to my own empire (or whatever you
call your state)? or is it better (cost-effective, maybe) to bomb it into
environmental collapse?"

_Tactical_ considerations would then be driven by strategy and available
technology (and culture, I suppose, but culture is also a factor driving
strategy).  If nuking them \'til they glow (or throwing rocks at them, a la
Moon is a Harsh Mistress or Lucifer\'s Hammer) is all you need to do, maybe
you don\'t have to worry about troops at all (except commandos to knock out
deep meson gun sites).

Invasion: Earth\'s premise was that the Earth should be occupied.  I always
tried to minimize destruction, but I\'m not sure that that\'s a game effect
(yes, I could just pull it off the shelf, I suppose).  The tactics that I
used as an invader were to bombard any troop and SDB concentrations, which
leads to scattering of defense forces.  I would land troops to surround
isolated units and destroy them, then extract my troops.  I never tried to
take anything except, after sufficient attrition, urban hexes which gave
victory points.  Terrain effects are virtually nil:  The only restriction is
that you can\'t end a movement phase on ocean.  At least that\'s the only one
that made any difference.  So there was no taking the poles or whatever and
working in.  The invader just hits and runs, and the defender eventually
runs out of resources to resupply and rebuild units.  I think that there was
a time limit operating against the Imperium in the game, which is necessary
for balance.  If the besieging force has the time and is strong enough to
defeat the space defense forces, it will always wear the ground-based forces
down eventually.

I\'d like very much to hear the stories of other veterans of this campaign of
the Solomani Rim War.

4) Why did the Third Imperium choose a hard-point based defense?
I think Mr. Plummer\'s ideas are right on.

     A) The Imperium relies on a militia.  This is implicit in the game
Fifth Frontier War, with its multitudes of colonial ground and naval forces.
(See also the discussion in Fighting Ships of the Shattered Imperium at
5-7.)

    B) Imperial suppression of internal dissidents required significant
naval and military forces to be distributed throughout the Imperium.  This
seems to be implicit in much published material (I disagree with Mr.
Plummer\'s comment that there is "no hint of major anti-Imperial hostility
.. given in Classic Traveller").  For example, who were the Ine Givar?  How
numerous were they?  They took over much of one of the continents on Efate,
and the Imperium sent a huge military force to deal with it.  This happened
just before the 5FW.  There is at least one AZ dealing with Ine Givar
activity in the Spinward Marches (Rule of Man Commemorative, I think).  Were
the Tanoosians anti-Imperial?  To the extent that the Imperium supported teh
the status quo and allowed Vilis to occupy Tanoose (and call it
Garda-Vilis), they probably were.  MT Imperial Encyclopedia describes the
Zid Rachele Society as a secret Vilani supremacist group, that led a series
of revolts in 1010-1011.  The Psionics Suppressions must have left a lot of
people disaffected (like the surviving relatives of psionic researchers and
psi-talented people who were purged or blacklisted).  

I haven\'t even touched on class divisions that could have caused festering
discontent.  The Imperium is ruled by a small noble class that also controls
the megacorporations and the Navy.  To what extent did the employees and
farmers and sailors feel exploited and trapped?  That\'s not explicit in any
GDW (or other, as far as I know) publication, but it could be a source of
dissent and insurrection.  

The Imperium is a Solomani graft on a Vilani stem, and the Vilani stem
itself includes conquered and subjugated societies.  I think there\'s plenty
of room for an Imperium full of wild-eyed revolutionaries suddenly
developing enormous public support and being suppressed and discredited by
tight-lipped bureaucrats and self-righteous noble-ranking naval officers.
That\'s what you\'ll find if you\'re adventuring in my Imperium, anyway.

One more point on this issue:  The Rebellion Sourcebook seems to take the
line that A Few Great Men and Women completely disrupted a stable and
harmonious eleven hundred year old eleven thousand system wide state
virtually overnight.  I don\'t think so.  The Imperium was ready to be
disrupted, and Dulinor was in the right place at the right time (not that
I support his rash action).

6) "High Guard" refers to the practice of some ships remaining in a gas
giant\'s higher orbits while others refuel in the atmosphere.  It\'s not
necessarily a convoying force in the high position.  The High Guard can
defend the refuelling ships from attacks from outer space -- like ships
hidden on the gas giant\'s satellites.  High Guard doesn\'t protect the
refuelling ships from the SDBs hiding in the gas giant\'s atmosphere, so they
have to take care of themselves.  I think that the natural ECM effects of
the atmosphere would probably help a lot here.  

--Glenn Goffin

