    'index' => 'aa025',
    'topic' => 'Has anyone tried the Trade Rules?',
    'body' => 'Don\'t confuse the speculative trade and common carrier rules.  When you\'re
carrying cargo for a fixed Cr1000/ton, no matter whether it\'s computers to
Glisten or wine to Zila, the rate is a fixed Imperial tariff.  In 20th
Century eartUSA, common carriers carry all manner of stuff, and charge rates
based on a tariff schedule. It appears that the Imperial tariff schedule is
easy to remember:  everything is Cr1000/ton.

On the other hand, when you\'re engaging in speculative trading, you\'re
buying the cargo yourself for resale.  As a common carrier you\'re only the
agent of the person shipping the cargo (or receiving it, depending on your
contract; the rules imply that the shipper is normally your principal).

