    'topic' => 'World Invasion: the role of the Imperial Army',
    'month' => '08',
    'index' => 'aa030',
    'body' => '
 First, I\'d like to thank 
      Edwin Fritz, 
      Edward Swatshenck, 
      Steven M Bonneville ("The walking Traveller databank")
      Steve Higginbothan (Good to see you again! And say hi to Cynthia!)
      Glenn Goffin
      and Emilio Desalvo 
 for helping to sort out my humongous question.  Thanks!
 
 Also, now that my education in asteroid artillery is nearly _COMPLETE_
 (Darth Vader voiceover), I\'d like to stretch out my question a bit.
 
 First: the Path of Tears sourcebook implies that the preferred military
 goal - if you don\'t want to exterminate the population - is decapitation.
 For example, a typical Star Viking hit would capture the headman, or smash
 his main force via bombardment or airborne assault. 
 
 This is excellent as an offensive goal: but what about from the defensive
 angle?  I suspect that the answer would center around 1) set up a BIG
 sensor umbrella (a system-wide version of the DEW line, say) 2) do NOT
 advertise the location of your major resources and 3) pour 90% of your
 money and sweat into the local space fleet & deep-site meson guns,
 because If They Go, It\'s All Over.  Do I have it right?
 
 
 Second: The existance of the Imperial Army has always annoyed me... except
 as long-term occupation & garrison troops, they seem only to mark time.  If
 the Threat Force has successfully taken the high ground (be it space or the
 air), the ground force is meat.
 
 (I shouldn\'t really speak against them: in my pocket universe, My Boys
 have a massive occupation army spread out across a ton of worlds.  "You can\'t
 hold land with jets - or even starships")
 
 Even so... with all those grav tanks and artillery, I can\'t precieve the
 Imperial Army as helpless, for some reason.  Even if the Threat Force has
 captured the main cities, the Army should still be able to fight back,
 from prepared undersea sites or polar ice caps, say.  The primary goals
 would focus on 
    1) cutting off the Threat garrison from their orbiting friends.  This
 would make the starports Serious targets.  Can grav tanks intercept
 landing starships?  If not, I\'m sure that the 57th century\'s equivalent of
 the hand-held Stinger missile can.
    2) drawing the Threat garrison into an Unfortunate Incident.  A
 drastically weakened Threat garrison would weaken the Threat\'s control of
 the population and the world\'s resources.  If the Threat garrison falls, they
 cannot use the down starport\'s resources to repair ships or transport
 resources.  Moreover, a strictly nominal conquest of a world - even if no 
 Imperial Navy ships can help out our battalion yet - can become a \'safe 
 site\' for merchantile raiders or intelligence vessels, as well as a great
 morale builder.  (Many times in British Imperial history, British opinion
 was strongly motivated to \'breaking the siege of Kimberley\' or \'rescue the
 garrison at Bombay\') 
    3) Harrassment.  I\'m thinking of the \'Blowing up the railways\' type of
 thing.  Imagine the French Resistance, spread out across a subsector or
 two.  Here, the Imperial Liberation Front would have to be radically 
 reorganised into a semi-covert or covert force, and take a crash course in
 intelligence operations.  The very nature of the Army would be altered, if
 the Occupation continues for, say, longer than a generation.
 
 (Note: as far as I know, no Imperial territory has been held long enough
 to cause an Imperial Liberation Front to arise, pre-rebellion.  Of course,
 you could imagine what would happen if the Zhodani successfully took the
 Spinward Marches in the Fifth Frontier War.  
    However, I believe that hundreds of Imperial systems fell under Aslan or
 Vargr rule during the Rebellion, many within the Domain of Deneb.  Also,
 there are the fractions...)
  
 With these notes, I hope that I have expanded the Imperial Army\' s mission
 into something more suitable of the name \'Imperial\'.  
 
 
 Alvin Plummer
 (Who is happy to see so many respond to his question)
