    'from' => 'Erwin Fritz',
    'body' => '>Alvin Plummer (plummer@hubble.sheridanc.on.ca) writes:
>>      1) What are the main strategic considerations of invading a
>>         high-tech, heavily-defended world without just nuking it?

>Erwin Fritz (erwin@fritz.cuug.ab.ca) replies:

>> Actually, why nuke it?  It\'s cheaper and more effective to just nudge a
>> few asteroids into a carefully calculated course intersecting with the
>> world (and with the ocean, if you can manage).  Lucifer\'s Hammer, by
>> Larry Niven, does a good job of describing this, although he talks about
>> a large comet.  The advantage of this is that you still have a habitable
>> world after it\'s all over.

Edward Swatschek then said:
>   Nukes are more precise, though easier to defend against.  They don\'t
>make a world any more uninhabitable than an asteroid strike or two (the
>mess an asteroid would make of weather patterns, and the sheer number of
>dead laying about, would leave the world less habitable in the short term).
>The main effect, however, of using such weapons is to piss off your
>opponent.  It won\'t make attacking the planet a lot easier in the short
>term - it\'s mostly civilians dying, in the billions.  After a while of
>this, there won\'t be a lot of opposition left.  If your opponent was
>limited to just that planet, that will probably be the end of it; if it was
>an interstellar state, you\'ve just taken the gloves off.

Well, I think asteroids do leave the world more habitable (at least by
Traveller terms) because you don\'t have all that messy radiation lasting
tens of thousands of years.  Calling a weather pattern messy is relative;
there\'re probably lots of worlds with naturally occurring weather far 
messier than the one resulting from a couple of dropped asteroids.

Your point about pissing off your enemy is good but only if the enemy is
the interstellar state you mentioned.  If your enemy is confined to the
planet in question, then fear is probably a better resultant emotion than
anger.

-- 
erwin@fritz.cuug.ab.ca
