    'month' => '08',
    'body' => '> Also, now that my education in asteroid artillery is nearly _COMPLETE_
> (Darth Vader voiceover), I\'d like to stretch out my question a bit.

 This was _COMPLETE_? <g>

 
> First: the Path of Tears sourcebook implies that the preferred
> military goal - if you don\'t want to exterminate the population - is
> decapitation.  For example, a typical Star Viking hit would capture
> the headman, or smash his main force via bombardment or airborne
> assault. 
 
> This is excellent as an offensive goal

 Well, no.  How effective would destruction of Washington DC be in
conquering the USA?  Admittedly, we\'d lose Congress, the President, and
the Pentagon, but would that be such a bad thing (in terms of conquest
of the US, anyway)?
 It seems to me that a decapitation strike would work well only in
places where the general populace is ready to come over to your side as
soon as the "Great Leader\'s" boot is off your neck.  It wasn\'t even
_that_ easy in Nazi Germany...


> but what about from the defensive angle?  I suspect that the answer
> would center around 1) set up a BIG sensor umbrella (a system-wide
> version of the DEW line, say) 2) do NOT advertise the location of your
> major resources and 3) pour 90% of your money and sweat into the local
> space fleet & deep-site meson guns, because If They Go, It\'s All
> Over.  Do I have it right?

 Probably.  I\'ve always been in favour of MASSIVE, MIND-NUMBINGLY
thorough sensor networks.  Mind you, the network doesn\'t really need to
be system wide, since the only parts of the system you need to concern
yourself with is the part you live in (gas giant refueling is a stupid
waste in TNE rules, and not especially useful in either of the other
rules sets - I\'d rather take along a huge pile of drop tanks, myself).
 As to deep-meson sites - I\'ve become skeptical about them recently. 
The TOUGH worlds in my TCS game had anywhere from 12,000 to 30,000
missile batteries as planetary defenses.  None of them had meson tech
until near the end of the game, BUT in previous games, the number of
deep meson sites never exceeded a few hundred (due primarily to the cost
of the supporting power plants).  And the deep meson sites were quite
vulnerable to attacks on the required power plants (which were quite
detectable via neutrino sensors).
 Admittedly, the missile batteries were also vulnerable to attack,
but you can afford a LOT more of them, which makes it a LOT harder to
neutralize them...
 But the Fleet is probably your single best defense against an attack
intended to conquer you.  A Fleet can\'t really protect you against an
attempt to destroy you (as several people found out to their dismay (New
Home and Neubayern and Serendip Belt come to mind)), but it can make a
conquest far more expensive and difficult than any other single factor.
 Note that a Fleet won\'t make your world unconquerable.  Even if it
is the biggest Fleet around.  But it WILL make it MUCH harder to do, and
stretch out the conquest for quite a long time...

 
> Second: The existance of the Imperial Army has always annoyed me...
> except as long-term occupation & garrison troops, they seem only to
> mark time.  If the Threat Force has successfully taken the high ground
> (be it space or the air), the ground force is meat.

 This sounds like the standard line I\'ve been hearing all my life (I
grew up around the Army).  And from what I\'ve read, it has been the
standard line ever since the end of WW2 (with variations going back to
last century).  Every time a new weapon comes along, you hear about the
death-knell of the Army as a factor in future wars.  Hasn\'t worked out
that way yet, and I have this (admittedly religious) feeling that it
won\'t be gone in 5600+AD either.
 Admittedly, the way the Army does things changes as technology
changes.  But so far, in the last 5000 years of technological advance
(and advance in the military art), the basic job of the Army hasn\'t
changed very much really - just the way they DO their basic job (take
control of things that the owners don\'t want to give up).  I expect that
by the time of the Imperium, the Army will fight in ways that are not
easily predictable (I haven\'t done enough Striker/MT mass combat/TNE
mass combat to make a good guess as to what will work), but I will
venture to make a few (not very educated) guesses:

 1)  the fraction of soldiers on the "front lines" will continue to
decrease, while at the same time, a larger fraction of soldiers will
find themselves fighting more often.
 2)  artillery will continue to increase in importance (and the
defense with it).  Note that I don\'t define the _form_ that the
"artillery" will take - I doubt seriously it will still be cannon,
either conventional, ETC, or mass driver.  I wouldn\'t bet too much on
artillery rockets, either.
 3)  the degree to which the Army and Navy function as a team will
continue to increase, probably even faster than at present.  This
depends a lot on rules set in question - the reaction drives in TNE will
produce significantly different interactions with the Army than the
reactionless drives in MT...

 (Gee, it was easy to make those guesses.  Now my guess as to how
many of them will actually be accurate - zero...;-) )

 
> Even so... with all those grav tanks and artillery, I can\'t precieve
> the Imperial Army as helpless, for some reason.  Even if the Threat
> Force has captured the main cities, the Army should still be able to
> fight back, from prepared undersea sites or polar ice caps, say.

 Why do you assume that the Threat Force will take the main cities? 
Historically, cities have always been among the hardest things to take
(without destroying them).  Admittedly, the Threat Force could threaten
to obliterate the cities if they don\'t surrender.  But unless they are
prepared to carry through on the threat, they\'ll be out of luck if
anyone calls their bluff.  And if they ARE prepared to carry through on
the threat, then they don\'t NEED the real estate, and shouldn\'t be
wasting their time trying to conquer this place.
 It is more likely the initial landings will be well away from the
major cities (if only to avoid destroying the industries you are trying
to capture)...


> The primary goals would focus on 
>    1) cutting off the Threat garrison from their orbiting friends. 
> This would make the starports Serious targets.  Can grav tanks
> intercept landing starships?

 Depends on technology.  In the earlier versions of Trav, they
definitely can.  In TNE I don\'t know, but probably.


> If not, I\'m sure that the 57th century\'s equivalent of the hand-held
> Stinger missile can.

 Also a good guess.  If only because the lads in the battledress can
carry a pretty big "hand-held missile"...


>    3) Harrassment.  I\'m thinking of the \'Blowing up the railways\' type
> of thing.  Imagine the French Resistance, spread out across a
> subsector or two.  Here, the Imperial Liberation Front would have to
> be radically reorganised into a semi-covert or covert force, and take
> a crash course in intelligence operations.  The very nature of the
> Army would be altered, if the Occupation continues for, say, longer
> than a generation.

 If the Occupation continues that long, then there won\'t be a
Resistance anymore.  As to "crash courses", it is quite likely that what
we now consider "covert ops" will be a standard part of military
training then - note that the history of Infantry operations includes a
trend toward smaller maneuver units, and less obvious operations...

 
> (Note: as far as I know, no Imperial territory has been held long
> enough to cause an Imperial Liberation Front to arise, pre-rebellion. 
> Of course, you could imagine what would happen if the Zhodani
> successfully took the Spinward Marches in the Fifth Frontier War.  

 Incorrect.  The Zhos have pushed the Imperium out of the sectors
spinward of the Marches.  Once upon a time, the Impies even owned all
the "Zhodani worlds" in the Spinward Marches...


> With these notes, I hope that I have expanded the Imperial Army\' s
> mission into something more suitable of the name \'Imperial\'.  

 Actually, we (Cynthia and I) don\'t even believe that there IS an
"Imperial Army" per se.  We think that the "Imperial Army" is actually a
number of HQ formations for Army and Army Corps level units.  No combat
units at all.  When the "Imperial Army" is needed, the formations are
filled out with individual units seconded from member worlds
militaries.  Which would tend to explain why the Army units in FFW have
widely variable TLs, as opposed to the Marines, which are all TL15...

    ----Steve
