In TNE, meson-gun artillery can easily hit orbiting ships, and
ground-based PD batteries can theoretically hit ships all the way
out to the jump point (4.3 light-seconds from a size-8 world).  
In 1977 CT, ranges were minimal, and in MT extreme range starts 
at about five-sixths of a light-second.

For instance, at 1.2 light-seconds, Luna is at extreme range for
all Earth-based weapons in MT, while in TNE it is at medium range 
for the standard tech-15 150 MJ laser turret.

In TCS, massive missile/repulsor/damper batteries can make more
sense than the same money on meson-guns, since even the little
mesons are fairly expensive (I don\'t know about Striker).  Of
course, that assumes you aren\'t using the standard planetary
capture rules, but I know few TCS players satisfied with them.
In TNE, you can build little ones, but heavy-duty meson screens 
are fairly cheap and don\'t need much power.  Then again, you
can up the discharge energy on a short gun.  Whether or not 
missiles need maneuver fuel can affect the energy weapon/missile
balance.  The big advantage of a deep-site is that it can hurt
a big ship coming in, has a tremendous armor value, and even
can be meson-screened.  But MT neutrino sensors can ruin your
day.  (Ask the inventors of the "meson-gun-submarine".)  So
in a sense, it depends on which rules you plan to use. 

  Steve Bonneville
