    'topic' => 'HG designs: Krait fighters',
    'body' => 'Here are some High Guard fighters. The Krait series is the Rift Alliance\'s
primary fighter from 5631 AD through 5650 AD.

                      The Krait Series of Fighters

FA-5A Krait  FH-0606G81-000000-00004-0 MCr175.25 90 tons
bearing                            1   Crew=1.
batteries                          1   TL=13(14).
Cargo=.41. Fuel=7.49. EP=14.4. Agility=6.

Notes: Has bridge, stateroom. Uses NH3 fuel system and multi-turret system.

Although the FA-5A needs only one pilot, it can (and often did) carry an ER
missile gunner to direct long range fire from other ships.

The FA-5A version, generally known as the Krait-A, was built as a stopgap
measure. The NFN needed a heavy fighter to replace the FA-2B Asp, so they
initiated development of the 90-ton Krait. During development, St. Hilaire
announced the afterburning powerplant, which immediately became a requirement
for the NFN\'s new fighter. Unfortunately, the new powerplant couldn\'t be used
for a fighter until it went into mass production, and in addition Neubayern
had to finish development on the acceleration tanks that would let crews
function under very high G-loads.

The NFN\'s Fighter Design Bureau decided to go ahead and construct 1,250
Kraits of the pre-afterburner design, which would then be refited with
afterburners and acceleration tanks when they became available. These
fighters all saw action in the Serendip War, and were split up among the safe
worlds at the beginning of the Imperial Occupation. As new Krait versions
entered service, the original fighters were upgraded, and most of the
original Krait-A airframes are still in service in 5650.

FA-5B Streak Krait  FH-0606(C)N81-000000-00004-0 MCr185.45 90 tons
bearing                                      1   Crew=1.
batteries                                    1   TL=12(15).
Fuel=19.96. EP=19.8. Agility=6(12).

Notes: Has bridge, stateroom, NH3 fuel system, enhanced output maneuver
drive, afterburning power plant, multi-turret system. When using afterburners
it can accelerate up to 12G and has an agility of 12, although in practice
10G/agility 10 is enough to avoid damage. It has a 9.66 ton fuel supply for
the afterburners. Like the Krait-A, an ER missile gunner was sometimes
carried.

The Krait-B is what the Fighter Design Bureau had in mind for the Krait
program when they learned of the new drive systems. Several thousand
Krait-B\'s were built on the safe worlds during early years of the Occupation,
and they saw some action in skirmishes with the Imperial Navy ships besieging
their bases. During these skirmishes, the Krait-B\'s avoided using their
afterburners to keep the technology\'s existence secret. Despite this
restriction, the Krait-B performed admirably.

By 5634, production of TL15 computers had increased to the point where they
could be used in fighters. Neubayern\'s Fighter Design Bureau, which was
sitting out the Occupation at Station Omega, was called upon to design a new
Krait version incorporating the new technology.

FA-5C Super Krait  FH-0606(C)R91-000000-00004-0 MCr223.14 90 tons
bearing                                     1   Crew=2.
batteries                                   1   TL=12(15).
Fuel=14.96. EP=22.8. Agility=6(12). 50 XO racks.

Notes: Has bridge, stateroom, NH3 fuel system, enhanced output maneuver
drive, afterburning power plant, multi-turret system, anti-missile fire
control. Afterburner performance is the same as the Krait-B, but with only
3.1 tons of fuel. An ER missile gunner is now a standard crew member.

The Fighter Design Bureau decided that in addition to the new computer, they
would rework the basic Krait to include all the new technology. They outdid
themselves.

In the past fighters had been limited by their small armament to engaging
escorts and civilian shipping, but could not take on cruisers or larger
unless thousands attacked a single cruiser. The Krait-C\'s XO racks changed
that forever. Now, only one or two hundred fighters could attack a cruiser,
and expect to cripple it with one salvo (which is, of course, all the
fighters had).

In addition, the anti-missile fire control dramatically increased the
effectiveness of fighters as point defense weapons, an idea that the NFN had
experimented with before the Occupation. Krait-C\'s carried by escort carriers
and _Tisiphone_ class destroyers proved very effective in defending Alliance
fleets from incoming missile fire.

Krait-C\'s saw extensive use throughout the Cluster Liberation War. Although
their sterling performance in the major battles was overshadowed in the media
by the exploits of "super ships" like the _Sol Bianca_, they actually did
more damage to the Imperial Navy. In particular, the Krait-C squadrons (and
the carriers and destroyers that transported them) bore much of the burden of
the clean-up campaign.

Following the defeat of the last organized Imperial force in the Islands at
the Battle of New Colchis, the Alliance Navy\'s heavy ships were all withdrawn
to Amondiage and sent off on the campaign that led to the Battle of
Pamraeltan. With the big ships gone, it was left to the few _Tisiphone_
squadrons and escort carriers to chase down the hundred or so Imperial
warships still in the Cluster. These stragglers ranged in size from escorts
up to heavy cruisers, and represented a real threat to civilian shipping.

FAdm Olson, the officer left in charge of the Cluster, spread her force out
with a destroyer squadron or an escort carrier to each system. These small
forces managed to destroy or cripple many of the stragglers, and the
survivors had either surrendered or managed to escape the Cluster by the time
the main fleet returned. A particularly noteworthy incident occured in the
Sturgeon\'s Law system when a squadron of Krait-C\'s caught up with two
Imperial light cruisers that had been raiding freighters. The squadron
commander split his fire, hoping to cripple the cruisers\' engineering
sections before they could escape. One cruiser was temporarily put out of
action, but escaped before a destroyer could arrive to capture it. The other
cruiser blew up instantly, and Ensign Juliette Romanova went into the
Alliance history books as the first fighter pilot to score a cruiser kill in
over 3500 years.

Shortly after the Krait-C entered service, a trainer version was ordered. The
FA-5D Krait gave up its stateroom for a second set of controls which could
override the first, and an additional ton of fuel. The Krait-D remains in
service in 5650, with around 250 built over the years.

At around the same time, the Amondiage Navy used the Krait-C as the basis for
the MD-1 Mjolnir planetbuster missile. The Mjolnir carries a 5 ton antimatter
warhead and lots of extra fuel in place of the bridge and stateroom, and also
does away with the XO racks. Mjolnirs can be piloted remotely (and usually
are, from an escorting fighter) or launched on internal control. Mjolnirs are
capable of up to 50G thrust, but still have a maximum agility of 12. The
Mjolnir can be carried by any ship with an ER missile magazine if necessary,
but only heavy battlecruisers and battleships would carry them normally. It
was a Mjolnir missile that destroyed the Imperial flagship at Pamraeltan. In
5650, an unknown number of Mjolnirs have been built--the Alliance Navy
refuses to discuss how many there are or where they are located.

The Krait-C remained the primary Alliance Navy fighter for ten years. By the
mid 5640\'s, the Council\'s policy of strongly encouraging Fteirle imigration
was beginning to pay off. Fteirle males were entering the Alliance Navy\'s
fighter program in ever increasing numbers--a trend which exposed a hidden
weakness of the acceleration tanks then used for G-compensation. When they
were developed, nobody expected that the fighters and ships carrying them
would ever have crewmembers who weren\'t human. It turned out that they not
fit people with alien builds, and in addition something in the liquid
irritated Fteirle skin.

The Alliance Navy\'s Fighter Design Bureau decided that rather than refitting
a fighter with new accomodations every time the crew changed, or imposing
limits on who can crew what fighters, they would design a new variant. The
FA-5E Super Krait is identical to the Krait-C in performance, but allows
acceleration tanks and crew accomodations to be altered in around fifteen
minutes at negligible cost, thus ensuring that field commanders would never
have to worry about incompatabilty between fighters and crews. Existing
Krait-C\'s were upgraded to the new design (although it was decided that it
was simpler to refit Krait-D\'s as Fteirle-specific trainers), and over
100,000 Krait-E\'s were eventually built.

In 5650, the Krait-E is still by far the most numerous fighter in the
Alliance Navy, and large numbers have been sold to System Fleets within the
Alliance and to close allies. The first antimatter powered FA-6 Cobra joined
the fleet in 5650, and will eventually replace the older Kraits, but this
will take years.

Technology Notes: Most of the new technology used in the Krait series (NH3
fuel, etc.) simply makes components more compact without affecting how they
work. The anti-missile fire control lets a missile battery act as a repulsor
battery 3 factors weaker. The Krait\'s XO racks let each fighter fire the
equivalent of a Missile-A salvo once before rearming. The acceleration tanks
compensate for 12Gs of acceleration, letting the crews function normally
under full thrust.

Ken

