    'body' => 'Here\'s another ship design. This one uses lots of new technology:

BC-25 Nagumo Chuichi BC-P666(8)CJ3-A(A0)0700-D0R0A-0 MCr63,736.8 50,000 tons
bearing                                      8 1 Y   Crew=561.
batteries                                    A 1 Z   TL=13(15).
Passengers=10. Low=281. Cargo=928. Fuel=9205. EP=6164. Agility=6(8).
Marines=150. 25,000 XO Racks.
                             Y=40, Z=50
Notes: Uses beam lasers, particle accelerator is APAWS. Has NH3 fuel system,
enhanced output maneuver drive, H-C overdrive, afterburning plant,
superconducting armour, anti-missile fire control. Has a 1-tonne AM
containment pod. Has ten shield bays, 1500 ton missile magazine (500
battery-rounds), 80 ER missile gunners, 2 30-ton small craft, 5 90-ton
planetbusters, 12 parsecs jump fuel.

Technology: This class mounts a factor ten shield (the first of the two
"sand" factors). This operates the same way as a Star Cruiser screen. Each
factor can absorb fire from one directed-energy (but not meson) battery per
turn, for 30 factors of absorption in this class. The XO racks hold the
equivalent of 500 Missile-A salvoes. An Antimatter Particle Accelerator
Weapon System (APAWS) is based on a PA, but does 1 surface explosion, 2
radiation, and destroys one armour factor for each factor by which the APAWS
factor exceeds its target\'s hull size (_not_ reduced by armour) until the
target is stripped of armour. Then, it does one surface, 3 radiation, and one
critical hit for the same period. Superconducting armour halves damage from
lasers and nukes.

The planetbuster launch bay is part of a shell game. The Alliance doesn\'t
have anywhere near enough of them to fill the bays on the battleships, even,
so they shuffle them around instead to keep enemys confused.

The _Nagumo Chuichi_ and several others of the class were built during the
Imperial Occupation and served in the CLW. The XO racks and ER missiles had
been kept more or less hidden from the Imperials up to that time, and so the
capabilities of this class came as a shock. A squadron of eight Nagumo-class
ships have a throw weight in their opening salvo comparable to 20
Tigress-class battleships--when told what was being fired at them, some
Imperial commanders simply refused to believe it.

The Nagumo Chuichi-class is one of the Alliance Navy\'s most important ships
following the CLW. There are few heavier ships stationed on the frontiers, so
when the Alliance Navy brings in capital ships to deal with some crisis it\'s
almost always the Nagumo-class that is called. Several squadrons took part in
the Sarage and Quiver Campaigns, and performed admirably.

Not all of the missions assigned to the Nagumo Chuichi-class involve combat,
however. The ships are more commonly seen patrolling Alliance space, engaging
in diplomatic missions, exploring new territory, protecting commerce, and
participating in aid missions.

In 5649 much of Third Fleet, including all of its battlecruisers, was turned
over to shipyards for refit with M/ARA in anticipation of the ready
availability of antimatter. In 5650 these ships have just left yard hands and
are undergoing their post-refit shakedowns.

Ken

