    'body' => 'Yo,
 As many of the long-timers out there have
had the chance to observe I have continued to produce
a number of traveller tools, mainly for system generation.
Well, I\'m still upgrading the SYSGEN stuff to Windows
but the pressures of my new job has meant this is taking
much longer than when I could do traveller work between
9 & 5 :-).
 Anyhow, in a similar situation a few years ago
I was involved developing the Fantasy Realm of a
Multi-User Dungeon but due to the phone company
quintupling the rates (seriously) I could not dial in
in the evening when the MUD was on-line. So I got a bunch
of interested students (who more or less lived in the
terminal room :-) together and did a sort of remote
group management structure. I would generate high-level
specs, one of them would pick it up and implement it,
I would pop in now and again and check it out and do QA.
 So, I am interested in setting up something similar
here. Let me propose a sort of project plan. Those who are
interested (as either producers or consumers) can contribute
comments and if everyone (or enough) is happy we can make
a start of it.

PROPOSAL
 The Traveller Tools Group; a group for producing
utility Traveller software and tools others can use for
the use of writing their own utilities.

DELIVERABLES
 The output of the group will fill into three levels.
 On one level will be libraries of utility routines
in static and dynamic link libraries. The next level would
be libraries of UI objects for creating, viewing, and editing
objects of the first level. Lastly, applications would be
produced using those UI elements to perform some functionality.
 Documentation and examples will be provided with the
releases.

COMPATIBILITY
 Each area of production would have its compatibility
defined at design stage. Where multiple standards can be
maintained (i.e. Class, MegaTraveller, TNE) they should be
done or if not the structures should be implemented in such a
way that the additional areas could be written when someone
becomes available who is interested in expanding them to
that level.
 Although the drive should be towards being compatible
with official GDW rules the emphasis should be on tailorability
and, ideally, many of the processes should be table driven so
that the end-user can configure them as they wish.
 [My main desire is for MegaTraveller compatibility and
upward compatibility with previous SYSGEN stuff.]

SCHEDULE
 The schedule should be largely driven by who volunteers
for which pieces. As there is already a large code-base for
system generation that would probably come first.
 Other areas: trade, character generation, ship generation,
floorplan construction.

IMPLEMENTATION
 Releases will be produced for the Microsoft Visual C++
compiler [negotiable, if enough volunteers wish to support
another compiler, lets discuss]. Static libraries of level
one deliverables will be produced for those who wish to
construct DOS applications. DLLs will be produced for Windows
development. Level two deliverables will all be for Windows.
Possibly as VBXs. Level three will, ideally, be MFC apps.

ROLES
 Co-ordinator  Someone to co-ordinate and organise
    the efforts [probably me]
 Architects  People to design the objects and
    interfaces of each bit. Co-ordination
    between the architects will be managed
    by either the co-ordinator or else a
    chief architect.
 Implementors People to volunteer to implement specs
    produced by the architecture department.
 Test and Doc People to test the implementation against
    the specifications and to produce final
    documentation from the spec.



 So, anyone bite?
