    'body' => 'Here\'s another Alliance Navy ship design:

DDF.1 Tisiphone DD-K656(C)EJ3-600700-D000A-1 MCr12,010 10,000 tons
bearing                              5   A   Crew=133.
batteries                            5   A   TL=15.
Low=67. Cargo=245. Fuel=2235. EP=1414. Agility=6(8). Marines=41. 1000 XO
racks.

Notes: Uses beam lasers. Has scoops, plant, two computers. Has enhanced
output maneuver drive, afterburning power plant, H-C overdrive, NH3 fuel
system, anti-missile fire control, superconducting armour. Has 15 parsecs
jump fuel, 15 ER missile gunners, 120 ton missile magazine (40
battery-rounds), 1 tonne antimatter containment pod. Carries 1 30-ton small
craft and 5 90-ton fighters. The XO racks hold 20 battery-rounds.

The Tisiphone-class can reach 12Gs maximum, but normally has only enough
power to sustain agility 8. However, if four of the laser bays cease fire,
the ship can reach its maximum agility of 12.

The fighters are used as part of an integrated point-defence network. One
fighter can be launched per turn. As of 5650, the FA-5E Super Krait is the
only fighter that has been carried by this class.

The Tisiphone-class destroyer was developed as a result of a NFN project to
improve fleet defence. Starting in the late 5620\'s, the NFN began conducting
experiments to determine the feasibility of using fighters as point-defence
weapons. The fighters of the day weren\'t up to the task, but with the
development of afterburners the project became much more practical.

By the time the _Tisiphone_ was laid down following the CLW, the FA-5C was in
service. The high agility and anti-missile capabilities of the Krait-C made
it very well suited to the point-defence role. Since the CLW, hundreds of
destroyers have been built for the Alliance Navy. The class has seen service
in both the Sarage and Quiver Campaigns, and also patrols many frontier
systems looking for pirates and smugglers.

Ken

