    'from' => 'Steven M Bonneville',
    'body' => 'Since I opened this can of worms, let\'s see if I can help 
figure it out (with out mixing more metaphors).

A)  Reference

It\'s in TD #10.  Mainly, it has a low *permanent* population since
most of the rock is filled with thousands of computer systems in
vaccuum chambers.  DGP claims that historically it was a Vilani
research station that the IGS picked as a data repository and 
astrographic datum point for their baselines.  I figure it must 
be an M star with a nearly circular galactic orbit at the right
distance.  The usage must be traditional, sice the First Survey
took place after the sector boundaries were originally set, as far
as I can tell.  M stars last a heck of a long time, so it would
be a better choice than something brighter.  Note that it is in
hex 0140 -- the lower left corner of Core sector; this suggests
that the rimward and spinward boundaries of Core are the original
Imperial Grand Survey baselines.

B) Double Star

The stellar data in that Core sector file seems to be faulty.
Don\'t trust it.  The star for Capital is clearly wrong.

C) IISS Patron

Empress Iolanthe, in particular (Strephon\'s wife).  I forget
where this was mentioned, but it was one of the CT adventure
library data sections.

D) The Emperor

Marc Miller once wrote an article mentioning the "Office of the
Emperor".  This isn\'t just the Emperor, but all the advisors,
functionaries, courtiers, and bureaucrats that directly help
him execute his offices.  There\'s plenty of room in the 1 km
Imperial Palace for legions of them.  That\'s not counting the
IN offices buried in the complex *under* the Palace.

Strephon\'s two biggest skills?  Administration and Leader.
That\'s his job, to coordinate the government, and elicit the
best advice, since no person could possibly know it all.
He knows some history, linguistics, and has some skill in
persuasion as well.  For that matter, Norris has similar
skills, except he has training in law and naval strategy.
Both possess skills appropriate to their specific jobs.
Even Norris\' job is quite a load, let alone Strephon\'s, but
somebody has to try to execute the jobs.

If you haven\'t read Silverberg\'s "Lord Valentine" trilogy,
I recommend them.  There\'s a scene in _Valentine Pontifex_
that this discussion reminds me of.  If the Imperial 
bureaucracy and nobility can\'t be relied on in general,
there isn\'t a lot the Emperor can do to fix it.  That\'s 
part of why the penalties and restrictions on the crimes
of nobles tend to be more dramatic -- they have more 
responsibilities to live up to.  The emperor need to be
able to distinguish bad advice from good, and weed out the
bad advisors from the good in his or her staff. 

Note that the Office of the Emperor is different from the
Imperial Household, which involves other members of the
Alkhalikoi family and their staff.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonnevil@mermaid.micro.umn.edu>

