    'month' => '09',
    'body' => 'Roger Sanger writes:
>If refined fuel is hydrogen, and unrefined fuel is water, how is it that
>unrefined fuel gives the same range as refined fuel (in terms of the 
>length of jump supported, or weeks in maneuver)?
>
>Wouldn\'t unrefined fuel provide far less energy?
>
>Hyperfueled,
>Hyperodge.

Yes.  IF UNREFINED FUEL IS WATER.

BUT - Unrefined fuel is NOT water.  Refined fuel is hydrogen
only.  Unrefined fuel is mostly hydrogen with those inevitable, and
never-to-be-sufficiently-damned impurities (minerals, trace elements,
and other plot devices) that you scoop up when you skim a gas
giant\'s atmosphere (or take on fuel that has been so acquired).

To turn WATER into fuel you must run an electrical current through
it, SEPARATING the Hydrogen from the Oxygen, then eject (or
store for later use) the Oxygen.  What you\'re left with is Hydrogen,
Minerals, Trace Elements, etc ----> Unrefined fuel.  That can be
refined if you have the right equipment.

Note that you have to be careful separating the Hydrogen from
the Oxygen.  You have to make sure that they STAY separate.
(By default, they will try to recombine into water, giving back the
energy used to separate them in the form of a kaboom.  No
"spark" is required for  this.)

There may be other ways of separating the H from the O in water,
I just don\'t  happen to know them.  Additionally, there may be
higher tech means of separating the elements that nobody knows
about (yet).

--Derek Smith

