   A big question, (and an intentional weak point in several of
GDW games) would be the actual technical limitations of
building, outfitting and staffing starships.  If there is some
bottle neck such that there were on both Kafer and human sides
a limited number of ship yards "capable" of building ships,
a major goal of "attrition" wwould be to destroy them.
  If (IMHO more realistic) a space ship factory could be
built almost anyplace in an industrial zone, the battle becomes
harder, as the society has to be broken down.
   Both 2300 AD and Traveller treat starships like historical
large marine ship construction and ignore the kinds of technical
skills developed around WWII for mass producing aircraft and
smaller ships like destroyers and pt boats.  I don\'t
think it is appreciated what a planetary "war footing" productive
system would be like just with todays technologies, much less 
what we will have after 350 years of "doing computers and robots"

  Visualize if you wish, an automated "astroidal" or "space habitate"
factory capable of producing one fully outfitted "military starship"
per hour.  As a production line, this might a thousand  in the
"pipeline".  The scale of this "factory" is equivalent to
say OakRidge or todays Boing Corp.      
   Think  of a mostly automated factory space, (to hold a thousand
300 meter by 100 meter diameter ships) 10 tunnels, each 300 meters
wide, 600 meters tall and 4 km long)
  It might be a great place for a scenario.
Les

