alvin plummera <plummera@hubble.sheridanc.on.ca> writes:
 >       a) The data for Reference is D100100-B.  Why is there so few
>people on Reference? I mean, this system is important enough to be on all
>the \'Charted Space\' maps, but there are only 30 people!
 >          (And, if Reference was just a astrological point of
>measurement, why Reference?  wouldn\'t Capital make a better choice?)
 Greenwich, England, is not a large town. Yet all the lines of
longitude for the whole world are based on it (plus the time system).
Wouldn\'t London have made a better choice?
 From a historical perspective these sort of things have no
real satisfactory answer. It is usually the case the a while range of
"standards" crop up where no definitive answer exists, each one based
on  local criteria, yet one wins out in the long run. The actual basis
for it becomes anachronistic and is overtaken by its justification because
it has been adopted.
