    'month' => '09',
    'index' => 'aa106',
    'body' => 'Ken Hagler wrote a summary of what happened after Steve Higginbotham\'s TCS
campaign closed. Thanks, Ken, it was fun to read. But I\'d really like to 
know what happened to the Great Rift Administracy in all this. (The GRA was 
a group of six worlds coreward of the Islands clusters which I ran. The game 
stopped just as you guys finally deigned to make contact.) I don\'t know how 
much Steve told you, but the GRAlians had a simple little idea that would 
have turned the Imperium inside out all by itself. And I\'d also like to
know what happened with that jumpdrive-less multi-billion population world 
that I was only beginning to learn about.

However, the basic trouble with the whole scenario is IMO the incredible 
disproportion between the success of research performed by the various rift 
nations and the Imperium. Don\'t get me wrong, I approve of the way Steve ran 
research to make it something you could see results of within years rather 
than the \'one TL in 300 years\' that apparently apply in the GDW universe. But
when you put your Alliance scientists up against the Imperium scientists
without letting the Imperium enjoy the same rapid research ability then
you\'re mixing two different universes. No wonder that the Alliance can
kick Imperial butt if they can play around with anti-matter while the
Imperium is still only experimenting with it. But try postulating that
the Imperium could duplicate any Alliance discovery in the same time it
took the Alliance to develop it and tell me if you still think your
history is reasonable? (Not just a snide question; I haven\'t had time to
study your history in detail. I just feel that the Imperium is getting 
shafted in the research department.) Now allow the Imperium to get the
same amount of new ideas that the Alliance does so that the surprises
aren\'t all on the Alliance side. Now allow them as many MORE new ideas 
proportionally as the Imperium has proportionally more people than the 
Alliance...
 


      Hans Rancke
University of Copenhagen
