    'subj' => 'language, race, religion',
    'from' => 'sudet@well.sf.ca.us',
    'body' => 'I\'ve always disliked the name "Galanglic," because, as I learned in my brief
study of Egnlish lnguistics, vowel shift that is always occurring won\'t sent
send the E of English back to A, but will send it on to I; the next name of
the language will probably be Inglesh or Ingles.  A thousand years ago, it
was Anglic (pronounced with a "tch" kind of sound at the end); it won\'t go
back.
I think that the official history supports the hegemony of an English-based
language, however.  English is rapidly becoming the language of commerce and
science in the world.  In a few hundred years, it will probably have
supplanted local, national languages in many areas.  (I don\'t think that
this will be a good development, but it\'s happening now.)  There are several
reasons for this development.  One is that the existence of a standard makes
it easier for people to communicate by learning the standard, rather than a
host of languages.  Thus in India, with its plethora of languages, many
people use English to communicate across ethnic lines.  
Anyway, by the time jump drive is developed, English will probably be the
first language of space travel, and will naturally be exported to the
conquered Vilani possessions.  The Vilani will necessarily learn English,
just as the aboriginal Americans and Australians, the Indians, the Persians,
and many Africans did in the last three centuries.
But they won\'t call it English, nor Anglic.  At least not in my universe.
