    'ts-index' => '1994-09-13.aa111',
    'body' => '
"Glenn M. Goffin" <sudet@well.sf.ca.us> writes:

>Someone asked about the cost of xmail.  It\'s in The Traveller Adventure
>p.145:
>Cr10 for 20 kilobits of text
>Cr20 for 200x200 bit matrix picture

Which is clearly extortionate, at tech-8 let alone tech-13 (the 
original xboat tech-level) where electronic transmission by laser
communicator of interstellar messages is the norm.  Private "ImpEx"
service would rapidly establish itself at a far cheaper level. 
In our local games, those rates only applied if one wanted the
*original hardcopy* to be physically delivered to a specific
address.  Anyone care to make a lower-bound estimate of the 
memory capacity of a holocrystal-based xboat?

The economics are interesting.  Figure in the IISS Commo Branch
salaries, xboat and tender maintenance (and payment to replace
worn out or pirated ships), "cargo fees", and the possible costs
of near perfect duplication for delivery.  Price still seems
high, especially since the messages seemed so much more like 
faxing.

Also, my players often would send the same message to several places
in hopes of catching up with someone who was travelling on an 
irregular schedule (like a tramp freighter).  One way we did this
was to have, as an additional complimentary service of the TAS,
free transmission of casual correspondence between members to
other TAS hostels in the subsector.  (Wider ranges, longer distance,
and big messages had a service charge attached.)  After all, the
TAS has to maintain the communication lines for the TNS anyway, so
a little extra traffic doesn\'t hurt. 

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonnevil@mermaid.micro.umn.edu>

