    'topic' => 'TCS ship design',
    'body' => 'Here\'s another Alliance Navy design, circa 5650:

BCH.1 Tokugawa Ieyasu BC-Q656(8)EJ3-B(F0)0700-D0S0A-0 MCr95,350 75,000 tons
bearing                                       P 1 Y   Crew=845.
batteries                                     W 1 Z   TL=15.
Passengers=30. Low=423. Cargo=3057. Fuel=12,799. EP=10,990. Agility=6(8).
Marines=600. 30,000 XO Racks.        Y=49, Z=65

Notes: Has NH3, enhanced output m-drive, H-C overdrive, superconducting
armour, anti-missile fire control. Carries 2 30-ton small craft, 5 90-ton
planetbusters. Has 1950 ton missile magazine (650 battery-rounds), 120 ER
missile gunners, 1 tonne AM containment pod, 600 battery-rounds in XO racks,
10 parsecs jump fuel.

The _Tokugawa Ieyasu_ was begun before the Serendip War as a heavier version
of the old Gorbachev-class BC. Before it was completed during the Occupation,
it\'s role and design had changed substantially. The Tokugawa-class as built
was meant to serve primarily as a close-in heavy hitter in a major fleet
action, providing short-range firepower while guiding missiles in for the
Manta Ray- and Alliance-class ships which provided long range firepower.

When the Alliance began expanding outside the Islands Cluster, the
Tokugawa-class began to see use as a flagship for small Task Forces (since it
had a flag bridge). Later, when the Alliance fought skirmishes with the
Imperium and some of its Fteirle neighbors, the class was pressed into
service as a battleship replacement, since the skirmishes generally were over
before a real battleship could arrive.

This expansion of the class\' role has led to a recent shuffling of
assignments. Originally, nearly all _Tokugawas_ were assigned to Third Fleet
along with the other heavy units. Since 5647, though, many have been
transferred to First Fleet for duty on a variety of missions in the Trojan
Reach.

The _Tokugawa Ieyasu_ itself was not completed until a few months before the
CLW--it\'s construction was delayed considerably when the partially-completed
ship had to be broken down and moved from St. Hilaire to Amondiage to prevent
capture by the Imperium. The class has performed admirably in the CLW and a
variety of small campaigns, proving itself more than a match for Imperial and
Fteirle battleships. By 5650, foreign battleships are appearing with
technology copied from the Alliance, which had put them on a much better
footing when facing the Tokugawa-class. However, most of the class has just
recieved the Series C refit which adds antimatter power--this is expected to
preserve Alliance superiority into the 5660\'s.

Ken

