    'topic' => 'Starports (XBOAT digest 35)',
    'body' => 'Lurk... lurk...

Jeff Zeitlin asked about starports. My own rules for starport generation 
assume the following answers to his questions:

>Airport runways v. ships docks
Starships are big heavy dangerous things while in the air. Hence valuable 
buildings (hangars, etc.) will always be well away from where the ships 
land. I use runways extensively in my starports because any aerodynamic ship 
should be able to save a good bit of fuel landing and taking off from a 
runway rather than using brute force engine power for VTOL. Runways are also 
safer, reduce the amount of landing beacons, etc. required (kit for 2 
runways vs. kit for 30-100 VTOL circles!); also a clear blast area can be 
allocated behind each runway for all those \'dirty\' ships drives, rather than 
having to build extensive blast bunds around every VTOL location. etc. etc.

>Are all starships, shuttles, etc., VTOL-capable?
Even if they are, see the answer above for why many would still land like an 
aircraft.

>Newtonian reaction mass takeoff clearance area?
Any VTOL pad requires a good bit of clearance around it - ever seen one of 
the Apollo rockets that didn\'t manage to make it off the ground and 
exploded? ANY ship that goes straight up/down needs a lot of safety room - 
hundreds of metres preferably with blast walls et al.! This problem doesn\'t 
apply to runways (in general) because you just dedicate a strip a couple of 
kilometres long and wide at the end of the runway as a clear zone - any 
vessel running off the end of the runway would plough into a \'crash zone\' of 
impact-absorbent barriers to slow it down; one that took off and then 
couldn\'t climb, etc. or an incoming ship that lost too much height, would 
know that they have a totally cleared flat area in front of the runway on 
which to crash-land. And if they still blow up the ship, the several 
kilometres clearance means no one else should get too hurt.

>How big should I make the "parking" zones for the ships, and how far apart?
My low class starports just park you on roadways off the runway! But 
typically a port will have parking bays allocated to ships - either 
individual or in groups, with each ship\'s area enclosed by blast walls which 
will direct any explosions upwards and away from other 
ships/people/buildings. Bays will be of different sizes (e.g. up to 400 ton 
displacement, up to 1000 ton, etc.) with each having a different berthing 
cost. High class and low class bays are available, some with accomodation 
provided on-site, others with no more than a refuelling point.

Then all you have to consider is the multitude of other stuff found at a 
starport - from customs to the cleaners, from security to technical ground 
staff, hotels, shops, air traffic controls, etc. etc. etc. (it\'s a huge
list!)

Hope this is of help...

Andy
Commander Lilly, PITS (Political Intelligence Team, Scout)
Nothing I say or do in any way reflects the views of my very kind and
generous employers.

