    'file' => 'XBOAT94/XBT94036.TXT',
    'mo' => 'Sep',
    'subj' => 'City Building',
    'from' => 'Rob Prior',
    'body' => 'Jeff Zeitlin had some questions about cities.  HIWG discussed this several
years ago in a paper mailing list; I\'ve _briefly_ summarized our conclusions
below.
 

Which model to follow depends on how manuverable your starships are on the
ground (or at slow speeds at low altitudes).  If they can maneuver easily
(and safely) then the seaport model is reasonable, otherwise the airport one
makes more sense.

The general conclusion seemed to be that the airport model made the most
sense because landing a large starship was potentially dangerous.  If you
assume that your starships can\'t move easily once landed then you have
shuttle busses and cargo transporters.  From an adventuring viewpoint, this
also provides more places for smugglers to impersonate longshoremen,
air/rafts to swoop in and hijack cargos to kidnap passengers, etc.  

A useful technique is to \'grow\' the starport through several phases, or have
older ports left after a new one is built.  This makes it feel more real and
also lets you have some seedy areas.  

Don\'t forget to route flight paths away from densely settled areas.  Take
planetary rotation and winds into account when planning flight paths and
COATC (Close Orbit and Aerospace Traffic Control) rules.  

As to blast pads, calculate the drive as a high energy weapon and figure out
the danger area.  Multiply by a _good_ safety factor and throw in some more
for pilot error.  Add blast berms around the pad.  

Check out JTAS 5 for a decent example.  
