    'id' => '<9409141625.AA06559@stedee.YP.attc>',
    'date' => 'Wed, 14 Sep 94 10:25:13 MDT',
    'body' => '
Andy Lilly\'s post 

>Starships are big heavy dangerous things while in the air. Hence valuable 
>buildings (hangars, etc.) will always be well away from where the ships 
>land. I use runways extensively in my starports because any aerodynamic ship

>should be able to save a good bit of fuel landing and taking off from a 
>runway rather than using brute force engine power for VTOL. Runways are also

>safer, reduce the amount of landing beacons, etc. required (kit for 2 
>runways vs. kit for 30-100 VTOL circles!); also a clear blast area can be 
>allocated behind each runway for all those \'dirty\' ships drives, rather than

>having to build extensive blast bunds around every VTOL location. etc. etc.

reminded me of an issue I had when designing a spaceport a few years ago. All
the starship designs I\'ve ever seen had landing jacks, even the streamlined
little scouts. What do these ships do when they use a landing strip? A 
100 ton Scout/Courier on final approach, landing jacks down, heading for
the tarmac, the jacks hit the strip and then what? Do they act as skids? Or
do they dig into the ground and flip the ship over into a flaming crash?
And when the ship comes to a stop, it\'s still sitting on the runway. How does
it get to the parking area? Do aerodynamic ships come with wheels? Does a
really big tractor come out and drag the ship on its skids off the runway?
Or do they hover under power from landing area to parking area? If they can
hover, then why do you need landing strips in the first place? If they
can\'t hover, how are the ships moved on the ground? If you can\'t move a
ship once grounded, that implies that ships land on their parking area, which

implies no landing strips.

I ended up with the seaport model. The assumption was that ships can land 
on water, so the aerodynamic ships land and takeoff like seaplanes. The
big ships can land and takeoff where ever there\'s an open space of sea.
Tugs move the ships in and out of the landing areas to terminals, cargo
areas, parking areas, etc. Cargo can be moved directly between starships
and surface ships. Landing mishaps occur over water, away from valuable
real estate. Add a lot of artificial floating "islands" that provide
terminal,
customs, maintence, and other services, you\'ve got a configurable starport
that seems to make some kind of sense no matter what the capability of the
starships. You could add a land component with landing strips for aircraft
and aircraft-like spaceships. This could be the old, multi-generation
starport that\'s seen a lot of development over time.
