Tech level advantages - Alliance vs. Imperium:

> However, the basic trouble with the whole scenario is IMO the incredible
> disproportion between the success of research performed by the various
rift
> nations and the Imperium. Don\'t get me wrong, I approve of the way Steve
ran

Amen to that.  The ongoing disparity is difficult to explain.  Although no
more difficult then the Sword Worlds languishing at TL-11 since
Grandfather-knows-when.  The developments devised by the Alliance are very
good, but it is unreasonable to assume they would not disseminate quickly.

One possible defense is the size of the Imperium reducing the speed of
adoption of the new technology.  However, the degree of local autonomy
allowed to sectors (and even subsectors) would result in the local yards
refitting ships immediately, and worrying about the paperwork later.   Even
the resources of a single high-pop world are considerable, and most
subsectors contain two or three such worlds.

BTW - In my own campaign, I bumped the Sword Worlds & Darrians to average TL
of 13; although in the case of the SW this had not filtered down to the
civilian population.  Shades of the Soviet Union...  The various
developments outlined for the Alliance will probably appear in bits and
pieces.  Luckily, we don\'t do much ship combat, so I won\'t have to retrofit
my INS ships.  :)

> Landing at starports

Most of the starship designs use landing jacks, not wheels.  The Starship
Operators Manual also implies use of the manuver drives for VTOL landings.
 This would rule out the landing strip concept - unless you make a few
pencil changes to the ship designs.

For that matter, even the "streamlined" designs aren\'t all that streamlined.
 Nor do they show any apparent shielding or insulation.  Thus they don\'t
seem to be doing any high speed atmospheric landings.

So if you have to slow down anyway, you might as well just plop down in
whatever landing bay you wish to use.  I have always assumed this to
resemble the starport at Mos Eisley, featured in _Star Wars_.  Actual
interpretations may vary.

It also occurs to me virtually any sort of starport could be justified based
upon local technologies or conditions.  A high-pop, TL-7 world could have
fleets of NASA-type shuttles working out of hugh airports.  A water world
could use the seaplane or harbor approach, etc. etc.

>

Guess I had better get back to my paying job.  :)

Andy St. John / andy_stjohn@nih.gov / "sig-less in Micro$oft Mail"

