To: UNIXML::"xboat @ MPGN.COM"
Subject: Re: Food in Space

Mitchell K Schwartz writes...
>How much space aboard a vessel do rations take up?
 If you remember, when computing the space used up by
cabins it says that only half the volume required is for
the cabin itself. The other half includes coridors, lounges,
toilets, ... I always consider that this also includes
kitchens and pantries.
 Thus the space necessary for rations is already
computed.

>I\'m curious what other folks have done. Or whether it has
>occurred to any of you at all.
 The purchase and stocking of food is the duty of
the stewards. On a small ship this just involved going
out to the port and doing the (bi-)weekly shopping. On
larger ships with a regular route they probably already
have previously arranged deals with catering firms.
 Having done a lot of flying recently I am reminded of
sitting in the plane waiting for takeoff as they forklift
into it those large silver crates with those pre-prepared
meals on it.
 Most starports with any sort of facilities will
probably advertise several different catering agencies
that offer a variety of pre-prepared meal packs for ship
in a variety of different styles and qualities. Sort of
like the lunch-boxes they sell to buisness people in Japan
(any Japanese lurkers on the TML?).
 A well appointed ship would allow the customer, upon
booking, to electronically order their meals for the entire
flight. This would then place orders with the local agencies
which get delivered automatically. This could make an interesting
plot device: Someone books onto the players ship, orders a
special meal for a certain restraunt. At the last minute,
after the delivery has been made, they cancel. The meal actually
contains some sort of contraband that is being smuggled.

As for recycling, I always got the impression that the
automatic recycling on most ships just covered air and water.
Material wastes are sorted by category (metalic, plastic,
organic, and scrap) and held for resale to the next station.
Most stations would quite happily pay (small bucks) for
recyclable raw materials.

 The germ of my ideas about food stems from C.J.Cherryh\'s
"Merchanter\'s Luck". It coveres a good number of day-to-day
aspects of running a merchanter. Cherryh was also the origin
of my recycling ideas (cf "Rimrunners" and "Chanur\'s Legacy").


   Jo
