To: PLATO::"UNIXML::"xboat @ MPGN.COM" @ DUNVAX"
Subject: Re: Home for Scouts

alvin plummera <plummera@hubble.sheridanc.on.ca> write
>First:has anyone generated a "home system" for the Scouts? Or,should I
>say, where the largest Scout bases are (Perhaps in the Glimmerdrift
>Reaches?)  
 In my campaign setting the Imperium is much, much larger. This
affects many things, including the Scouts, but I think much of how my
scouts are organised is relevant to a standard 3rd Imperium setting
discussion.
 The Navy and the Scouts can be contrasted as being two
entities of interstellar government that exist in a coordinated
way. Both have had to deal with a very diverse galaxy with members
of all races, religions, and social structures. The Navy has taken
the approach of creating its own culture. When you join the Navy
you *must* become of its society. (Short hair, drinking rum, etc,
etc). The Scouts have taken the opposite approach: creating an
orginisation where *all* cultures can exist.
 The Scouts as sort of the ultimate in a distributed
working group. Sort of modeled like a neural net across stars. Any
sort of structure is loose and free form and subject to change
without notice. There is a high level of empowerment at a local
level for making decisions. Powermongerers are not so much
discouraged but looked down upon where they crop up and aren\'t
invited to the best parties. Money sort of floats around from where
it is generated to where it is used according to the laws of
fluid dynamics.
 What really holds the Scouts together is their Computer
network. It is a vast, interlinked, "information superhighway"
were data gets replicated from planet to planet. The "mission" of
the Scouts is the maintenance and development of this vast
data bank. Any information they can acquire is fed into it.
Most Scouts can access most of the information. There is very
little "traditional" protection. The "protection" is mainly
through the archane and haphazard organisational system. The
longer you have been in the Scouts the better you can navagate
and the real old hacks even claim to understand how it works
(although this may be the effect of going to too many of the
best parties). Hackers and "data vandals", again, are not much
discouraged but looked down on and never invited to the best
parties.
 Scout software itself is known for being extremely adaptable.
This is mainly seen through their user interfaces. Given the
big emphasis in the Scouts on communication *all* programs
are "self-learning". They will modify their presentation and
input parsing not only by user demand but also by what they
perceive as desired behaviour. A simple example:
 Pilot: "Damage Report?"
 Comp: "Life support marginal, power-plant output at
20%, and port thruster unoperational."
 Pilot: "So we\'re fucked."
 Comp: "If you say so."
Assuming both pilot and ship survived the incident and live to
experience the same sort of conditions:
 Pilot: "Damage Report?"
 Comp: "We\'re fucked."
So, interactive Scout programs tend to be chatty, use coloquial
language, be idiosyncratic and general bug the hell out of most
serious users but loved by the Scouts. (Especially X-boat pilots.)
 Scout network software is distributedly developed across
the civilised galaxy. Anytime anyhone feels something needs
to be added, they add it. The chances slowly replicate across
the network. It is similar in many ways to the development of
NetHack.
 Some have theororised that it is the concentration on
communication that makes Scouts such party animals. The more
intamate, the more communication. Alcohol, and other inhibition
removing substances, open the barriers to communication.
 In a typical down-port, the Navy people on leave will most
likely be found in the nearest "Navy" tavern drinking rum. The
Scout people will most likely be found in the furthest local
tavern drinking whatever the locals drink. (And attempting to
claim expenses for "gathering information on the local culture".)
 Once a Scout, always a Scout. You can *never* leave the
service. You just go "on detached duty". While on "detached
duty" you don\'t draw pay (although the Scouts will frequently
pay for freelance surveys done by detached personell) but can
avail of facilities on any Scout base. This includes free fuel,
accomidation and food (see later).
 Of course since everyone is on detached duty that means
there is always the chance they can be called up and
reactivated. This isn\'t as threatening as it sounds. Reluctant
Scouts have been known to flee, hide, or admit themselves
into insane asylums to avoid activation. Generally, depending
on the real urgency of the situation, the Scouts won\'t pursue
anyone beyond a certain radius of inconvienence. If the Navy
is the one re-activating them, that is much more serious and
harder to evade.
 Scout ships are known to have some of the worst
accomidation known to space. There is the famous coffin
X-boats, and the minimal Couriers with their dodgy ventalation
systems. The shipboard food is even worse. However, this is
paralled by having some of the best on-base services. The
rooms border on luxurious (certainly the beds, given the
Scouts gregarious nature) and the food is Cordon Bleu, at
the least. The one things a Scout knows is that when they
get back to base they can have a needler shower, a massaging
bed and their choice of at least eight cheeses.
 


Some examples from my campaign:
 Having evaded arrest the characters have now decided that
they should turn themselves in somewhere (preferably where
there was no navy base). They start querying information on
various administrative heads of nearby Scout bases asking about
their previous rulings in legal cases. After a while the
computer starts describing them in terms of "boring", "a real
A-R", etc, etc. Eventually it asks the players if they are
trying to get a light sentence somewhere. They consider momentarily
if they should admit such to the computer but eventually
settle for "suppose we were". It then proceded to search for
what it considered lienent officers...
 
 The players were on a courier mission that took them
near a "police action" zone. They were picked up by the Navy
(frigates can *really* surprise you when they have their
transponder off and their EMS masking on). A Scout Donasev
attached to this fleet had gone missing. (Donasev\'s have an
impressive scanner array usually used for survey but equally
applicable for espianoge.) It was a Scout ship that had gone
missing, potentially working for the enemy, and these were
Scouts with a ship, therefore, by Navy logic, they were to
be assigned searching for it.
 One crew member had been left behind. He was an incredibly
boring person who kept telling everyone to relax, they rest
of his crew had probably just gone crusin and would be back
in a few weeks. The local Scout representative didn\'t beleive
that they had "gone crusin". There is a reason the Donasev is
so ugly: so Scouts won\'t steal them. She was quite convinced
that they had just jumped system to leave their repellant
crew member behind.
 One Navy opinion and two Scout opinions.
