On Traveller\'s view of religion: 

   Traveller, like most modern science fiction (like most modern
intellectual works, actually), tend to view religion as a set of cultural
lies, used to justify the rule of an elite or as an emotional mania.

   This is rather understated in Classic Traveller: there, (as far as my
pitifully small knowledge permits me) it seems to merely assume that
future religions will exist, but materialism is better.  The only religion
of importance was a Vargr Superiority faith, seen merely as a threat to
Imperial Rule.

   In MegaTraveller, religious viewpoints also seem to play only a small role
in the game.  And, in this case, this is as it should be, since the most
dramatic events of the era are basically political.  Only under intense
scrutiny (which is rather unfair) can \'gameworld\' religious structures be
guessed at. 

   Of course, current modernist/atheistic assumptions can be found.  For
example, the World Builders Handbook assumes the typical sociological
model of technology: that, as technology rises, polytheism gives way to
monotheism to deism to atheism.  

   This ignores the example of India, China, the Middle East, half of Africa,
and large areas of North America.  But it did work for Europe (can anyone
say "Eurocentric?").  And GDW can\'t be blamed for following the
intellectual consensus of everyone of importance, after all...


   In Traveller: The New Era, Things Get Interesting.... 

And I quote:
   "I\'ve been out there a half dozen times, and if that doesn\'t give you
religion, I don\'t know what does....
