    'subj' => 'Re: Religions...',
    'from' => 'JSHiggin@aol.com',
    'body' => 'Alvin Plummer:

> A) All known feudal societies have a single religious viewpoint: one
> of the functions of religions in feudal societies is to promote the
> idea of "rule by divine right".  

> Christian monarchies believe in "Divine Right". Islamic monarchies
> believe that they are decended from the Prophet Muhammad.  The Thai
> monarchy appoints only Buddists to work for the state.  The Japanese
> Emperor is, first and foremost, a Shinto priest.  The Roman and
> Chinese Emperors made supplications to the gods.  Both Roman Emperors
> and Egyptain pharoahs believed that they WERE gods.  

 Hmmm...it looks like you are equating "monarchies" with "feudalism".
 Of the examples you provided, only the Christian monarchies (and not
all of them) were feudal.  The Islamic monarchies were patterned on the
Eastern model of the absolute monarch.  The Japanese Emperor did not
actually rule Japan for most of Japan\'s history.  And the Shogunate,
which did rule, was a military dictatorship, _not_ a feudal monarchy. 
While the Egyptian pharoahs may have actually believed they were Gods,
only a few of the Roman Emperors ever gave a hint that the believed that
they were Gods.  Being a Roman God-Emperor was a political move, having
little if anything to do with Religion.

 And then there is the Persian Empire (you know, the one ruled by the
"King of Kings, Great King").  They rather specifically allowed all of
their subject people to worship as they wished, as long as their taxes
were paid and the Imperial Laws were obeyed.
 For that matter, didn\'t the Egyptians allow the Jews to worship as
they wished while they were slaves in Egypt?
 And didn\'t the Caliphate allow their Christian and Jewish subjects
to worship freely?  As long as they paid their taxes (which Moslems were
not subject to), anyway...



> B) All enduring societies had a single religious/philosophical
> viewpoint, which motivated and justified their actions.  The examples
> from ancient history are too numerous and obvious to mention.

 Mention some.  The only one I can think of off the top of my head
were the Jews, who were a minor society, even at their height.
 The Japanese had Shinto and Buddhism (and later Christianity), which
were not necessarily compatible.
 The Persians had many religions, as mentioned above.
 The Romans followed the Persian practice, up to the point when
Christianity was declared the State Religion.  Even after that,
Mithraism and similiar mystery cults were popular in the Legions (the
real political force in the late Roman Empire).
 The Egyptians had the Gods of upper and lower Egypt, which were
eventually combined to form a single Pantheon (with a legacy of much
confusion as a result (Amon-Re was the combination of Amon and Ra, the
two solar deities of the original two pantheons)).  Plus others (the God
of the Jews comes to mind, plus the Roman deities, which were integrated
into the Egyptian pantheon in much the same way the Egyptian deities
were integrated into the Roman pantheon)...
 The Christian Monarchies had Catholicism, Protestantism (in all its
many forms), Judaism, and (in the case of Spain) Islam.  Plus the
Orthodox variation in the Eastern monarchies.  Which resulted in more
religious wars than at any other time in history, as far as I can
tell...
 All of them fought among themselves at times to try to establish
that single religious/philosophical viewpoint you mentioned.  None of
them, except possibly the Egyptians, succeeded.

> especially compassionate, caring people like our current rulers.

 I will assume this is sarcasm...:-) :-)



> Honour is but another word for Truth;

 Well, no.  It\'s not.  If you believe that this is so, then read more
Japanese history.  Or more Roman history, for that matter.  Or try to
explain how allowing one\'s opponent in a duel to recover his feet after
falling on his duff (thus putting him in an unenviable position re the
duel) equates to "Truth"...

 Honour means many things, depending on the culture it is attached
to.
 The Japanese equated Honour and Duty.  Truth didn\'t even come into
the picture.
 In the Christian lands, Honour was more often equated to Fairness.
 The Romans mostly equated Honour and Truth.  Except when Honour was
equated with Duty.  Or Fairness.  Or just Winning.
 The Persians taught their nobles "to ride, to shoot the bow, to
speak the truth".


> Among all the groups I know of, this allegance to truth is based
> on supernatural forces. (i.e. swearing on Bibles, "...before God/the
> Revolution/Science/Truth/State/People/etc.."  Note the _capitalized_
> words)

 And then their were the rest of the people, who tied honour to
themselves, not their Gods/Semi-Clods/Submarine sandwiches/etc.  Most
people I have heard of did not think of "honour" as something done
because God made them do it, but because rather as something they did to
feel good about themselves...


> The Emperor is nowhere worshipped or adored in Traveller literature. 
> But people do kill for him.  And a large percentage of Imperial
> society was prepared to follow an insane Emperor. 

 So?  People have fought for a lot of things that they did not think
of as a God.  The Carthaginians come to mind, who had religion, but who
fought wars for purely pragmatic reasons, and left the Gods out of it.


> But Archduke Dulinor led a bloody rebellion, and killed billions, in
> the name of The People.

 Mostly because Dulinor was a complete _idiot_!  If he had studied
Revolutionary Theory, he would have been aware that you need the people
behind you BEFORE you start your "revolution"...Waiting till the
shooting starts to convert the "hearts and minds" of the populace is a
guaranteed road to failure, since human conservatism is almost guranteed
to stick to "the way we\'ve always done things" in Times of Trouble.  So
all Dulinor ever accomplished by his war was to convince everyone that
they should follow their traditional leaders...


 However, I mostly agree with you that Traveller has stereotyped
religion into the H.Beam Piper/Robert Heinlein model.  I prefer the Gordon
Dixon model
of religion myself...;-)
 And in my games, the Gordy Dixon model holds true - religions are a
widespread part of the "Imperial Society", with variations of
Christianity and Islam and Zoroastrianism keeping most of the people
happy, and Buddhism and/or Animisim covering the rest.
 And, yes, this is Terrocentric.  But, then, I\'m a Terran, and I
don\'t have too many non-Terran models to go on.  These are the most
exported religions in our world, and I (on a blind leap of Faith) assume
they will be exported to the Stars also...

    ----Steve


