    'date' => 'Sat, 24 Sep 1994 10:56:47 +0100 (BST)',
    'body' => 'Having seen the data on these for the Alliance, I\'ve got a few comments 
to make. Firstly: it\'s a really brilliant idea. Secondly: I\'m not sure 
how well it\'d work.

The problem is this: while NH3 takes up somewhere between 50% and 55% of 
the volume of liquid H2 (the author quotes 52%, which I\'ll believe), 
fusion powerplants run on L-Hyd. This means one has to convert the NH3 to 
N2 and H2, separate out the H2, and then feed the H2 into the drives.

Converting NH3 to N2 and H2 is easy (it\'s doing it in reverse that\'s 
hard.) It works really well at high temperatures... the problem being 
that it\'d have to be done in the gas phase, so to treat 1kl of liquid 
would require c. 1000kl of volume -- more like 2000kl, since we have

 2 NH3 --> N2 + 3 H2 (i.e. 2 mol --> 4 mol of gas)

For the same reason, you can\'t do the reaction under very high pressure.
(I have assumed 1 atm pressure here, but corrected below.)

Separating H2 and N2 is easy: just freeze out the N2 (since you want 
L-Hyd, you\'ll cool the stuff anyway.). Then discard the N2 and pipe the 
H2 to your drive.

My guess is that at TL14 one would require a refinery approximately 10 
times the size of the powerplant. Perhaps high pressures can reduce this 
significantly... let\'s say by a factor of 50. That gives 20% of the size 
of the PP, which is acceptable. So, you can run your powerplant off NH3.
These are guesses -- 10% or 5% of PP size may be possible.

Jump drive is a different story. I reckon 5% of ship volume is required 
for the L-Hyd to initiate jump, which is burned VERY fast. (And very 
inefficiently at TL9-16, which is how J-fuel usage can decrease at higher 
TLs.) I think that requires all the 5% to be ready as L-hyd at jump. An 
absolute minimum volume for an NH3 refinery (liquid phase) would be about 
10% of ship volume, in order to use NH3 for jump. So maybe it\'s possible 
and just about worthwhile to use NH3 for J-fuel. I think it isn\'t, but
your technical assumptions may vary.

The real problems with using NH3 concern refuelling. In order to refuel 
from a gas giant etc., a starship must collect hydrogen fuel, refine it, 
turn it into ammonia (which requires a source of N2 on board i.e. not 
discarding N2 when it is produced) and store the ammonia. This will take 
lots of volume to produce at a reasonable rate: one has to store the H2, 
N2 _and_ NH3, _and_ provide a large reaction plant. (You also have to 
work out how to remove the ammonia -- you can\'t dissolve it in water as 
one does at present -- but I\'ll assume that problem solved at TL14!). N2 
storage will take up half the volume of the NH3 capacity. Fuel processing 
will be slow: the speed of fuel conversion rather than fuel skimming will 
be rate-determining. Plus, ammonia is going to be far more expensive to 
buy than hydrogen fuel -- another reason for using hydrogen for jump. 
(Ever wonder why no rules exist for anti-matter jump fuel? It\'s insanely 
expensive, that\'s why.)

One possibility is a set of NH3 drop-tanks. There\'d be no worries about 
retaining N2, so it\'d be an efficient way of carrying extra fuel. They\'d 
have to be carried through jump, alas. And of course they\'d be expensive, 
but drop-tanks aren\'t expensive compared to starships. I like the idea of 
NH3 auxilliary tanks.

Summary: NH3 fuel is impractical for jump drives, possible for 
powerplants, and a great idea for auxilliary tanks. IMHO.

Comments welcome.

Nick

