    'body' => 'Nick Munn writes:

> Having seen the data on these for the Alliance, I\'ve got a few comments 
> to make. Firstly: it\'s a really brilliant idea. Secondly: I\'m not sure 
> how well it\'d work.

Since I sent the file, I\'ll try to address this, with the following caveats:

1. I didn\'t invent the thing, and I don\'t know the name of the player who
did, but I hope he or she is reading this and will comment.

2. I know nothing about this stuff in real life, and in fact I had to ask
somebody to find out what "NH3" was. :-)

3. My experience with the system in the Alliance campaign is as an end-user.
I just design ships based on a specified capability, without any idea of
exactly how it\'s supposed to work.

> The problem is this: [something way too technical for me about gas volume]

Well, how about explaining the discrepancy between reality and the stated
performance by saying that the difference is achieved through gravitic and/or
nuclear damper technology? That seems like a pretty popular explanation for
why Traveller science isn\'t "realistic." :-)

> Jump drive is a different story. I reckon 5% of ship volume is required 
> for the L-Hyd to initiate jump, which is burned VERY fast.

As I recall (the hardcopy is filed away somewhere) _all_ the fuel was used at
once when going into jump over a period of around 20 minutes. The NH3 jump
fuel refinery was oversized because of the need for refining the jump fuel 10
times faster than would normally be required.

As far as I can decipher from all this, the NH3 refineries in the Alliance
campaign _do_ work on liquid NH3 rather than gaseous. Okay, so maybe this is
impossible in real life. So what? So\'s jump drive... :-)

> The real problems with using NH3 concern refuelling.

Indeed. To date, I\'ve taken note of the need to refit all existing refueling
systems to accomodate NH3, but haven\'t really gotten beyond that.

> In order to refuel 
> from a gas giant etc., a starship must collect hydrogen fuel, refine it, 
> turn it into ammonia

Hmm. So then gas giants don\'t have any ammonia in them already? How about
those planets that have exotic atmospheres--do they? For that matter, what
about Nitrogen? I was under the impression that gas giants already had stuff
like this in them...

Anyway, if there\'s no way to scoop ammonia, the Alliance (and other NH3
users) would probably build "factory ships" as part of the fleet train which
would carry N2 and use it (along with scooped hydrogen) to produce NH3 as
needed. Considering that the Alliance fleets will already be needing a
substantial fleet train just to lug around spare missiles, I don\'t think this
would be a major hardship...

Anyone else with knowledge of NH3 as seen in the Islands want to comment on
this?

Ken

