  {
    'body' => 'On Mon, 26 Sep 1994 xboat@MPGN.COM wrote:

> Well, how about explaining the discrepancy between reality and the stated
> performance by saying that the difference is achieved through gravitic
and/or
> nuclear damper technology? That seems like a pretty popular explanation for
> why Traveller science isn\'t "realistic." :-)

I don\'t think you can do it in this case. The Traveller universe seems to 
take as given real physics, and add a minimum number of 
not-yet-proved-impossible quirks to allow FTL travel, anti-gravity etc. 
(all of which probably derive from one new piece of physics). The problem 
here is pretty straight thermodynamics, which really ought to work in 
_any_ human-occupied universe.

> As far as I can decipher from all this, the NH3 refineries in the Alliance
> campaign _do_ work on liquid NH3 rather than gaseous. Okay, so maybe this
is
> impossible in real life. So what? So\'s jump drive... :-)

8-). Point taken. The only way I\'ve come up with a liquid NH3 converter 
to work is a laser tuned to dissociate NH3, which will reduce but not 
solve the problems of heating up the NH3 and having the H2 want to 
expand. We can postulate a good cooling system... OK, it\'s probably not 
so physically impossible as I thought, or rather it\'s not provably so, 
and hence (in my book) OK to use.

> > The real problems with using NH3 concern refuelling.
> 
> Indeed. To date, I\'ve taken note of the need to refit all existing
refueling
> systems to accomodate NH3, but haven\'t really gotten beyond that.
> 
> > In order to refuel 
> > from a gas giant etc., a starship must collect hydrogen fuel, refine it, 
> > turn it into ammonia
> 
> Hmm. So then gas giants don\'t have any ammonia in them already? How about
> those planets that have exotic atmospheres--do they? For that matter, what
> about Nitrogen? I was under the impression that gas giants already had
stuff
> like this in them...

Yes, they do. The problem is that ammonia is denser than H2, and N2 even 
more so. Thus, it all lies deep in the gravity well of a gas giant -- 
probably too far in for a 6G spacecraft to remove it. The other problem 
is relative abundance: you\'d need to skim for _far_ longer in the 
accessible upper atmosphere in order to get an equivalent amount of 
ammonia fuel to the available H2 fuel. Some exotic atmospheres could 
indeed contain NH3, though it might take some explaining why and it 
wouldn\'t do a starship much good to fly through them too much.

> Anyway, if there\'s no way to scoop ammonia, the Alliance (and other NH3
> users) would probably build "factory ships" as part of the fleet train
which
> would carry N2 and use it (along with scooped hydrogen) to produce NH3 as
> needed. Considering that the Alliance fleets will already be needing a
> substantial fleet train just to lug around spare missiles, I don\'t think
this
> would be a major hardship...

Hmmm. It\'d be rather like adding an extra stage to a space rocket: it\'d 
have to be bigger than all the other stages put together. I think it\'d 
require two or three times the tonnage of an equivalent-capacity H2 
tanker fleet, off the top of my head. But yes, it\'s possible. And it\'d 
lead to some really interesting space actions, as the Imperials try to 
trash the tankers to stop the Alliance fleets....


Let\'s look at it the other way round: why doesn\'t the Imperium use NH3 
fuelling? Either it doesn\'t work, or it\'s too expensive, I\'d suggest. If 
one assumes it to be possible, it\'s got to be expensive (which includes a 
need for extra/specialised tankers, etc.), IMO.


Besides, there\'s a far better way to improve fuel performance. Use D2 
instead of H2! (Deuterium is the isotope of hydrogen which ``does\'\' 
fusion reactions. This is based on nuclear energetics I assume to be 
fixed). Since D2 is < 1% abundant, it follows that fuel volumes can be 
reduced enormously. By my own logic, this is going to be expensive, of 
course. But definitely worth it... one can imagine ships with small D2 
tanks using it to `enrich\' skimmed H2/D2 mixture, to improve range at 
decreased cost. Alternatively, one rules that the H2 is necessary to keep 
the reaction under control, or something, and that D2 can\'t be used, tho\' 
I reckon it\'s implausible.


Nick Munn
University of Cmabridge, England
