    'body' => 'Alvin -

>And is their a \'realistic\' way to make freight profitable?

Freight merely guarantees that you will have an income per ton of stuff 
in teh cargo hold. Its a reliable income, but not an intersting one. Trim 
ship operating costs to increase your profiut margin.

As an exercise, I created a 200 t freighter in CT, and used its cargo system
and ran about in my campaign space (non-Imperial but randomly generated).

I included docking fees (about 10 times what the docs suggested), 
payments, fuel costs, maintenance costs, etc. They only had a moderate 
Trading skill.  By selecting their cargos with some care as to where they 
were going, they quickly amassed a small fortune - enough to pay off the 
ship in 5 years instead of 20, and to amass a downpayment on a 300 ton 
trader... 

While limited, CT\'s trading rules were easily enough expandable by adding 
new products.  From what I have heard of the MT/TNE trading, the actual 
adventure of merchanting has fallen into deep disrepair/disregard.

I am working on (slowly; its about 3 projects down in my non-work queue) 
is a better (more detailed) means of trading rules based around the 
relation between product, market size, market tech, and planet trade 
classification.

I\'ll let you know how it workds out...

>How profitable is chartering your ship, as opposed to carrying cargo?

That, of course varies wildly depending on what/who you haul where.
