    'ts-index' => '1994-09-27.aa171',
    'topic' => 'NH3 fuel...',
    'index' => 'aa171',
    'month' => '09',
    'body' => 'Re: NH3 fuel systems,

 Comments on the various comments about NH3 fuel systems:

> Having seen the data on these for the Alliance, I\'ve got a few
> comments to make. Firstly: it\'s a really brilliant idea.

 Thank you.  I think.

> Secondly: I\'m not sure how well it\'d work.

 Neither am I.  However...


> Converting NH3 to N2 and H2 is easy (it\'s doing it in reverse that\'s 
> hard.) It works really well at high temperatures... the problem being 
> that it\'d have to be done in the gas phase, so to treat 1kl of liquid 
> would require c. 1000kl of volume -- more like 2000kl, since we have

 Too true.  14Kl of H2 per Energy Point are required every 2,500,000
seconds under HG rules.  Which translates to 5.6 ml per second per EP. 
Multiply by 1000, and you have 5.6 liters.  Assume that it takes you
about 100 seconds to process the NH3.  That gives you half a Kl per EP. 
Which is 4% of the size of you power plant (assuming TL15 power plants),
smaller percentages for lower Tls.  If you operate at high pressures,
then you can use even smaller refineries.


> Jump drive is a different story. I reckon 5% of ship volume is
> required for the L-Hyd to initiate jump, which is burned VERY fast.
> (And very inefficiently at TL9-16, which is how J-fuel usage can
> decrease at higher TLs.) I think that requires all the 5% to be ready
> as L-hyd at jump. An absolute minimum volume for an NH3 refinery
> (liquid phase) would be about 10% of ship volume, in order to use NH3
> for jump. So maybe it\'s possible and just about worthwhile to use NH3
> for J-fuel. I think it isn\'t, but your technical assumptions may vary.

 Where did you get your "absolute minimum volume" from?  However, the
rule I used required larger fuel refineries than that for the J-drives,
so it really doesn\'t matter, I guess.  Even with a very large refinery,
the savings in J-fuel makes for a net volume gain for the ship.  And
every spare ton helps in designing a warship...


> The real problems with using NH3 concern refuelling.

 I won\'t argue with this.  In general, in the Islands, gas giant
refueling was a minor issue.  It never became an issue after the
development of the NH3  fuel system, though.  Mostly because the Islands
were all civilized, and drop tanks were common, and gas giants were
out-of-the-way places where noone went without an overriding concern
(which happened twice in the course of the game)...

 I should note that NH3 refueling is easier in a terrestrial planet
than a gas giant.  The N2 is available from the air, the H2 from the
water, the energy required from the ship\'s fusion plant...


> Plus, ammonia is going to be far more expensive to buy than hydrogen
fuel -- another reason for using hydrogen for jump. 

 Nonsense.  It is easier to make NH3 on Earth today than it is to
make LH2.  NH3 is extremely cheap compared to LH2.  Also easier to
store.


> (Ever wonder why no rules exist for anti-matter jump fuel? It\'s
> insanely expensive, that\'s why.)

 Exactly so.  AM will only be used for fuel (jump or otherwise) when
the cost comes WAAAAY down, OR when the AM is used by someone without
concerns for money (like a government).  It is, of course, useless to
the Imperium, since the Imperium has a multitude of planets where H2 (or
NH3) can be gotten cheaply.  The Alliance guys might use AM to deal with
the relative sparsity of refueling points out there in the Rift where
they are, but even they will never use it very much until and unless a
Stage II or III AM production facility is built.  Which is unlikely,
whatever Ken thinks, until the Alliance finds itself no longer at war
with the Imperium -- destroying one of them is a trivial effort, unless
the Alliance pushes its borders out about thirty parsecs...


>> Well, how about explaining the discrepancy between reality and the
>> stated performance by saying that the difference is achieved through
>> gravitic and/or nuclear damper technology? That seems like a pretty
>> popular explanation for why Traveller science isn\'t "realistic." :-)

> I don\'t think you can do it in this case. The Traveller universe seems
> to take as given real physics, and add a minimum number of 
> not-yet-proved-impossible quirks to allow FTL travel, anti-gravity

 Well, no.  They don\'t.  If they did that, then the lasers wouldn\'t
be described as using "gravitic focusing".
 However, I wouldn\'t go so far as to say the "gravitic and/or damper
technology" is required to allow NH3 fuel systems to be designed and
built.


> Let\'s look at it the other way round: why doesn\'t the Imperium use NH3
> fuelling? Either it doesn\'t work, or it\'s too expensive, I\'d suggest.
> If one assumes it to be possible, it\'s got to be expensive (which
> includes a need for extra/specialised tankers, etc.), IMO.

 It is not used in the Imperium primarily because the people at GDW
were/are ignorant enough of chemistry to not be aware that NH3 (or H2O,
for that matter) is a more efficient way of transporting H2 than
carrying it in liquid form.
 In MY Universe (which is the root source for this speculation), the
Imperium doesn\'t use NH3 because they find it more valuable to be able
to do "wilderness refueling" than it is to save the space in their
ships.
 Also, over here, the Vargr are big users of NH3, both in the basic
form and the "so-called" "Hellson-Canomaar Overdrive".  Especially out
in the far reaches of "Vargr Space".  Which extends about a third of the
way to the Core, btw.
 Ditto the Solomani.  The Solomani Sphere is still here, but in this
Universe, MOST Solomani live rimward of the Sphere in small states and
independent worlds extending most of the way to the Galactic Rim.  The
Solomani of the Outer Reaches use NH3 almost exclusively, especially
near the big rifts...


> Besides, there\'s a far better way to improve fuel performance. Use D2 
> instead of H2!

 Can\'t make the assumption that D is used to fuse, instead of H.  If
that were true, then the tiny little fusion plants in the back of your
air-rafts would irradiate the driver (and passengers, and bystanders). 
The assumption that GDW makes that fusion plants can be built VERY small
implies that the reaction used in Trav fusion plants produces a minimum
of neutrons.  Which implies Protium fusion.
 And don\'t bother telling me that that is impossible.  It happens in
the Sun (we think) so it is certainly possible (wt).  It is also
certainly VERY difficult.  Quite possibly TOO difficult to be feasible
given Trav TLs.  Which is irrelevant.  No Protium Fusion, no small
fusion plants.  (NOTE:  It bothers me not at all that you might be
restricted to big fusion plants, since I tend to play Trav at TLs below
where the itty-bitty fusion plants are allowed....

 However, I have always assumed that MOST of the H2 used in Trav
power plants and J-drives is actually used to provide cooling to the
reacting mass.  Note that this allows the _possibility_ that an NH3 fuel
system could use that waste N2 as coolant after redesign of the heat
exchanger.  Which is the basic assumption behind the H-C Overdrive,
btw...

    ----Steve Higginbotham
