Let me interject a couple of comments here.  I don\'t know what the highest
practical pressure would be that would favor the formation of hydrogen and
nitrogen from the ammonia, but I remember bits and pieces of this from my
undergraduate days (12+ years ago) as a chemical engineering student.  The
ammonia reaction is a classic case of a reversible reaction, where "pushing"
any of the factors causes the equilibrium to favor the opposite product.
Thus, remembering that the formation of ammonia is done at high pressure
(600 atm?), to increase formation of hydrogen, you\'d want to go to as low
a pressure as practical, balancing throughput with volume of the equipment.

> > Let\'s look at it the other way round: why doesn\'t the Imperium use NH3
