Steve answered this one. Personally, I think it\'s an unwise decision on their
part, but it certainly fits with all the other unwise design decisions the
Impies make! :-)

The Aslan would also have access to NH3 (via the Alliance if nothing else). I
haven\'t really given more than passing thought to their technology, but at a
guess I think they\'d use it for their warships at least.

>  In general, in the Islands, gas giant
> refueling was a minor issue.  It never became an issue after the
> development of the NH3  fuel system, though.  Mostly because the Islands
> were all civilized, and drop tanks were common,

This is likely to be the case throughout Alliance territory in 5650. I
haven\'t worked out the details yet, but basically every system in the
Alliance will have at least a Class B port, and probably a Class A.

>  Alliance guys might use AM to deal with
> the relative sparsity of refueling points out there in the Rift where
> they are, but even they will never use it very much until and unless a
> Stage II or III AM production facility is built.

They wouldn\'t. I thought at first the Alliance might have an AM powered ship
or two before the Stage II facility was finished, but then I realized that
keeping even one ship powered would use pretty much all the AM produced. It\'s
not worth it, since the AM is more urgently needed for weapons (which also
use much less of it).

> Which is unlikely,
> whatever Ken thinks, until the Alliance finds itself no longer at war
> with the Imperium -- destroying one of them is a trivial effort

Not really. A big AM plant is vulnerable to destruction, true, but the
Alliance hasn\'t fought any _major_ wars during the 5640\'s, when the plant
would be built. The wars it has fought, with the Imperium and maybe with some
Aslan clans, have been small affairs that ended before anyone hit the other
side\'s commerce or planets. Except for these incidents (which don\'t last more
than a few months at most), the Alliance has been in a "cold war" with the
Imperium, not a hot one--and neither side would be terribly eager to _start_
a major war...

Ken

