    'body' => '[stuff on how much pressure a hull can take]

Does anyone have any idea how to determine the pressure a hull can take, or a
reasonable approximation thereof? I\'m a bit curious about this...

> The only points of agreement we have come to are that
> destroying a large AM  facility would either be (a) very easy, or
> (b) very hard, and (c) a very good idea for your enemies, or (d) 
> a very bad idea.

Well, looking at it from the Alliance\'s perspective, they have to take a
chance. The Alliance pretty much has to keep a substantial technological edge
over the Imperium to stay free. Since the Impies start copying Alliance
technology as soon as they see it (mostly in 5640), by 5650 they\'d have
gotten a good deal of it into production. Even allowing for the slow rate at
which it spreads through their Navy, and the greater need for it on other
fronts, by 5650 the Alliance\'s once-great technological edge would be badly
eroded.

The development of AM technology pushes Alliance technology back up to a
comfortable lead--it would take the Impies something like ten years to catch
up, assuming they bothered to. (I\'d think they would, but then I also thought
they\'d develop NH3 fuel systems. :-))

So, given the importance of AM power to the Alliance, the Imperium would have
to consider the possibility that a preemptive strike at the facility would
lead to a major Alliance response. While the Imperium could certainly overrun
the Alliance in an all-out war, the cost would be great--too much for a
country already fighting two other major wars to undertake lightly. In
addition, the Imperium would have to consider the possibility that the
Alliance would retaliate by attacking Imperial planets. Whether the Alliance
would actually do this is undecided, but it\'s certainly working to make the
Impies _think_ it would.

Given all this, I\'d say that the Imperial Navy would have contingency plans
to destroy the facility, and would even run exercises to test those plans,
but wouldn\'t actually do that unless they were _already_ engaged in a major
war with the Alliance.

[comments on stutterwarp performance]

Well, without the actual drive info I can\'t be sure. It is faster than the
ships I\'m familiar with from 2300AD. Keep in mind, though, that stutterwarp
is _supposed_ to be vastly faster than conventional jump drive. In fact,
stutterwarp warships generally are comparable (or superior) in speed to
warp-drive ships in Star Trek...

>  A controllable JI/JD combination, depending 
>   on how they really work, might have the potential to serve as a 
>   "jump gate" method of interstellar travel

There\'s a jump gate of a different sort in the Islands campaign--this time,
not developed by the Alliance. As I understand it, the original design had a
big station with a jump drive in it, and a boom. The ship jumping would dock
to the boom, the jump drive would create a jump field around the ship via the
boom, and away it would go. The inventor of the system mentioned an
alternative whereby the jump field would be created around the ship by
induction, giving a "Babylon 5" style jump gate. I still don\'t have a clear
picture of the technicalities for this thing, but when I do I\'ll add it to
that file on new technology.

Ken

