    'topic' => 'NH3 fuel and gas giant diving',
    'body' => 'Adventure 12, Secret of the Ancients, p 18, gives tables about conditions in
the gas giant Komesh, which is in the Boughene/Spinward Marches system.
Komesh has an equatorial diameter of 72,000 km; the diameter is measured to
the point where atmospheric pressure is 1 standard atmosphere ("atm").  The
surface of the planet is hundreds of km below that.  (Ibid. p. 16.)
The atmosphere is 89% hydrogen, 10% helium, 1% water vapor, methane, and
ammonia.
Refuelling is generally no lower than 0.5 atm, or an altitude of 36,500 m
(measured from the center of the planet, because the location of the surface
isn\'t clear).
Equipment limits given are as follows:
3G maneuver drive is required to get closer than 37,000 km from the center
of the planet.  (Ibid. p. 18.)  I dimly recall a formula from high school
physics that you can use to check this, if you know the mass of the planet.
"Commercial vessels ... can withstand up to 1000 degress K and 1000 atm.
Military vessels can handle temperatures to 1500 K and pressures to 2000
atmospheres.  System defense boats are specifically constructed to handle
temperatures to 2,500 K and pressures to 3,000 atm."
There are also special protective suits which fail at 1,000 K and 400 atm.

(all ibid. p. 18.)

The table indicates that crush/burn depth is between 34,000 and 35,000 km
from the center of the planet, and that liquid H2 occurs up to 33,000 km,
where the pressure is 400,000 atm and the temperature 3,000 K.

(Ibid.)

I leave it to someone with more scientific and mathematical knowledge to
determine if that information is plausible.

--Glenn
