    'topic' => 'SW and AM...',
    'index' => 'aa188',
    'month' => '09',
    'body' => 'Ken Hagler:

>> The only points of agreement we have come to are that
>> destroying a large AM  facility would either be (a) very easy,
>> or (b) very hard, and (c) a very good idea for your enemies,
>> or (d) a very bad idea.

> Well, looking at it from the Alliance\'s perspective, they have
> to take a chance.

    This may be.


> So, given the importance of AM power to the Alliance, the
> Imperium would have to consider the possibility that a
> preemptive strike at the facility would lead to a major 
> Alliance response.

    So, to use one of the arguments in favour of wrecking the 
facility:

    If the Alliance has shifted largely (say, 80% or so) over to 
AM powered warships in their fleets, they are using pretty much 
every kilo of AM they make every year.
    If the Imperium wrecks the facility, then the Alliance 
suddenly finds itself without fuel for 80% of their Fleet. 
Assuming a one year reserve of AM, the Imperium has to hold on 
for only one year before the Alliance grinds to a halt.  Note 
that use of weapons of mass-destruction by the Alliance speeds up
the time when the Fleet grinds to a halt.
    Given this, the Alliance has to either (a) try to wreck the 
Imperium within a year, or (b) go on the defensive, minimizing 
use of AM until the facility is repaired/rebuilt (which should 
take another ten-twenty years, given the cost and resources of 
the Alliance).
    Given (a), they have to wreck about 1000 worlds, all high 
pop, most heavily defended.  The Alliance will NOT have what it 
takes to do that by 5650AD.  And probably won\'t for another 50
years after that - not enough yard space to build the ships fast 
enough to be that strong that quick.
    Given (b), they may be able to get away with that.  They may 
not, if the Imperium is willing to push a lot.  I doubt that they
WOULD push that hard, since pushing would invite retribution, and
NOT pushing would STILL neutralize the Alliance.

    In either case, the Alliance is removed as a 
political/military problem for the foreseeable future.


> [comments on stutterwarp performance]

> Well, without the actual drive info I can\'t be sure. It is 
> faster than the ships I\'m familiar with from 2300AD. Keep in
> mind, though, that stutterwarp is _supposed_ to be vastly 
> faster than conventional jump drive. In fact, stutterwarp
> warships generally are comparable (or superior) in speed to
> warp-drive ships in Star Trek...

    I\'ve never actually looked at SW in FF&S.  From what I recall
of SW in the original 2300AD rules, speeds such as you decribe 
are not unreasonable when coupled with the efficient Imperial Era
fusion plants.  In the original 2300AD, a 150MW fusion plant was 
around 250-260 displacement tons, rather than the Trav standard 
of less than one ton.  Since SW is VERY small, and the limit of 
speed of an SW ship is mass of the ship, then speeds should be 
EXTREMELY high when Impy technology is added in to the picture. 
SW speeds in excess of J-8 equivalent should be quite easy 
really...

                    ----Steve H.
