    'topic' => ' Chameleon Commerce Raider',
    'body' => 'High Guard stats can\'t be copyrighted?  I think that\'s tables based on
physical properties (such as the periodic table) that are inherent in the
universe.  Certainly strings of numbers in a particular context can be
copyrighted (what else is computer code?).

In any case, the original FASA description, which is definately copyrighted,
was also uploaded.

As to caring, last time I talked to them Seeker wasn\'t on any form of
computer network.  They did, however, care about the copyright.  They did not
threaten me with a lawsuit, just explained that they were the new owners of
the FASA designs and asked me not to distribute copies any more.  Nothing
heavyhanded about it.  I strongly suspect that they don\'t have the resources
to sue anyone even in the USA, let alone internationally (I live in Canada). 
However, they paid money for the rights to these designs, and I believe that
they are under no legal obligation to publish them in order to retain these
rights.

Naturally, I asked when they planned on reprinting them, and was told that
they didn\'t know; Seeker runs on a _very_ small budget and can\'t carry many
projects at once (another of those part-time companies like DGP).  They
_wanted_ to, and indeed asked me if I\'d be interested in doing the artwork to
change the deckplans to 25mm scale because then they had no spare resources
to do that inhouse.  They also asked if I\'d like to buy the rights/molds for
the 15mm Martian Metals figures, which they had acquired but didn\'t have the
financial resources to produce themselves.  (I still don\'t, but if someone\'s
looking for a business opportunity and thinks there\'s a market for 15mm
figures I suspect that Seeker would be willing to dicker...)

Obviously Seeker hasn\'t republished these designs yet.  They may well have no
plans to do so.  If this is true, then they would probably be interested in
selling the copyright.  Another business opportunity...
