    'body' => '    I just picked up World Tamer\'s Guide on the recommendation
of whomever mentioned it on TML last week (thanks for the heads-
ups, btw.  I would never have even noticed that it was out (or
even that it had been conceived of) if not for your note.  And
it is the first thing I have seen recently from GDW that was
worth the cost).  Interesting...

    A few comments:

    The only real hole I saw in the "economic model" was the
lack of provision for "service industries".  Since the model
dealt only with production of real wealth (as opposed to the
distribution methods for same), there is no provision within
the model for things like convenience stores, or fast-food
joints.  This is fine for a starting colony, but it results in
odd results when trying to model LARGE economies...

    I haven\'t pushed all the numbers through yet, but it looks
like the technology curve was accidently inverted in the
model.  It looks like the TL improvements in production (all
kinds) are not sufficient to justify the improvements in TL...

    Also, I note the addition of hydro and wind power generation
in WTG.  Which is the WORST element of the book.  Note
that, at the prices specified in the model (MCr0.25 / KW for
hydro, around the same for wind (which are around 250 times
higher than Real World standards, btw)), an industrial worker at
TL8 (ours now) would take just under 17 years to build
sufficient hydro-power generation equipment to provide the power
required by himself in the model.
    This is possibly realistic (I haven\'t got the numbers
available for the Hoover Dam, so I couldn\'t say for sure), but
it is certainly completely pointless, since ANY of the other
power generation schemes (fission, fusion (STEVE\'S CHOICE
AWARD!), chemical power plants) is much more cost-effective
than the hydro option.
    Note that at TL8, a hydro installation producing sufficient
power for FIVE industrial labour units requires that the five
units spend 17 years building the dam, then it requires that
FOUR of the units do maintenance on the dam in perpetuity.
On the other hand, an MHD turbine requires 0.29% of the output
of ONE materials sector worker to fuel, and 0.032% of the output
of ONE Industrial sector worker to maintain indefinitely (to
provide power for the same 5 workers...).
    Note also that any serious colonization effort done by any
starfaring power should include at least one minimum size TL-9
fusion plant (or an equivalent higher TL plant).  This costs
only MCr20 (and fits into 7 displacement tons of your hold), and
thus, for a cost comparable to the capital investment for your
first 1000 people, you provide power for your first 100,000+
people...

    Other than that, the economic model was fine.  Not
necessarily accurate, but as they said, noone understands it 
well enough to build an accurate model anyways.  But it is more
than adequate for the purposes of the game (and may be the basis
for the economic model used in budgeting my next (if ever) TCS
game...


    Which (WTG) brought up the question around our house:  What
are Imperial rules/regulations/laws regarding colonization of
new worlds?
    Do you get Imperial Charters (a la H. Beam Piper\'s Chartered
Uller Company or Chartered (later Charterless) Zarathustra
Company)?  Or is it first-come-first-served?  Or some other
mechanism?
    Who (if anyone) is in charge of controlling colonization?
The IISS (seems like a logical choice)?  The Navy (they have to
defend these new worlds, maybe)?  The local Sector/Subsector
government (all those lovely new taxes...)?
    Given that multi-system states are not allowed within the
Imperium, how does the Imperium coerce colonies to act
independently from their principals (after all, Trin\'s colonies
can _say_ they are independent of Trin (and even BE independent
of Trin, legally), but how can you make them ACT "independently
of Trin" if they prefer to behave like "New Trin")?
    For that matter, does the Imperium allow members to control
(limit) immigration/emigration?  Or does it control (limit) that
itself?
    Is this last why colonization has never been an issue in the
Imperium?  Because Imperial Law makes it next to impossible to
legally colonize new worlds?

                ----Steve H.
