    'body' => '
> Steve H. wrote-

>     Do you get Imperial Charters (a la H. Beam Piper\'s Chartered
> Uller Company or Chartered (later Charterless) Zarathustra
> Company)?  Or is it first-come-first-served?  Or some other
> mechanism?
>     Who (if anyone) is in charge of controlling colonization?
> The IISS (seems like a logical choice)?  The Navy (they have to
> defend these new worlds, maybe)?  The local Sector/Subsector
> government (all those lovely new taxes...)?

The early CT adventures mention the Forboldn project, where the Imperial
Ministry of Colonization (or some name to that effect) was settling up a
colony
in the Regina subsector.  Also, the Tarsus boxed set mentions the process
of settling up a colony on Tarsus, chiefly from Fornice in the Mora
subsector.

Other sources mention colonies settled and/or conquered by nearby worlds.
 (Garda-Vilis in _Broadsword_, Jenghe/Regina, which is mentioned briefly in
_Twilight\'s Peak_.  I have always played that the "multi-system entity"
prohibition was used more to curb excesses, i.e. small groupings were
tolerated as long as they don\'t get out of hand.  They are a convenient way
of explaining the various Govt=6 worlds littered about.  Not to mention the
Vegan Autonomous District and the Geonee Cultural Region.

Settlement by the IISS (Their Regina HQ on Hefry probably fills the whole
planet - mentioned in _Twilight\'s Peak_) and the Navy (pick a depot, any
depot) also have precedent.  No canonical analogies to the Chartered Uller
Company (et. al.) come to mind, although various megacorporations could fit
the bill.

Andy St. John / andy_stjohn@nih.gov
