    'body' => 'Les Howie:

> Generating a half dozen subsectors, say 200 worlds, I found a 
> significant number of rules with base naval tax rates in the trillions 
> of credits per year (worlds with pop 9 or 10, high pop multipliers, 
> and good exchange rates)

Sounds normal so far...


> The median seemed OK: about 3 billion cr/year.

Also normal, though these little worlds will be absorbed very quickly into
the major worlds\' control.


> Anyway, are bugets in the 10\'s of trillians normal and to be 
> expected, or should I take some remedial action such a fiddling 
> with high end world taxes or  thinning out the populations?

Yes, this is normal.  In my last, the SMALLEST player budget was 
MCr40,000, and that world was played on a lark, with no real 
expectation of being able to accomplish anything worthwhile.  Typical 
player budgets were on the MCr3,000,000 - MCr5,000,000 range, 
though one player could lay claim to a budget of MCr25,000,000 by the end of
the game.
Note that I deliberately removed a position with a budget of 
MCr15,000,000 from the allowable starting positions, but this was 
done ONLY because that budget was so much larger than the other 
starting positions, NOT because it was too large in and of itself.


> Also, any thoughts on a good size for a half dozen players?  4-5 
> sectors, or just a couple?  50% star density, or less:  Any 
> experience you can offer would  be valuable. 

One sector is probably more than enough.  With a uniform 
dispersion, one sector means six players are on average 15+ 
parsecs apart (which means that it will take quite a few turns (10-20) 
for routine communications between players.  This tends to be a problem).  My
last game started out in two subsectors, and added 
pretty much the balance of a sector worth of space before it was 
through.  The original two subsectors had nine players in it, and th rest of
the space was "expansion room" so they might be able to find something to
fight over (trashing home worlds got old fast (but not fast enough,
obviously))...

                      ----Steve
