    'index' => 'aa239',
    'topic' => '1st Addition High Guard',
    'body' => 'Phil Pugliese <PPUGLIESE @ pimacc.pima.edu> wrote:
>I wonder if there\'s anyone on this list that has ever seen
>the 1st ed. rules for \'High Guard\'.
>
>I\'ve never seen them nor have I ever met anyone who has.
>
>I *have* seen some ships stats that hd both 1st & 2nd ed.
>entries for each ship & there were, apparently, some significant 
>differences.
>
>Would anyone care to post up some of the changes between editions?

I used to have these.   Both of them.  First edition was an unmitigated
disaster, in terms of the ship design rules.  (This was, I believe, the
only significant difference)

The problem was that: 

1) the number of bays or turrets or barbettes needed to achieve a given
attack factor was multiplied by the ship\'s size in increments of (if
I remember correctly) 10,000 tons.  Thus if it took 10 triple laser
turrets to give you factor 9 lasers (the highest possible), it took
100 laser turrets to get that factor if your ship was 100,000 tons.
And 1000 laser turrets if your ship was 1,000,000 tons.

2) you could have 1 (ONE) battery per weapon type.

This led to certain conventions in designing warships for 1st edition
High Guard.

For Battleships, you wanted the SMALLEST ship possible that could
have the Acceleration, Jump, Armor, Weapon, and Screens that you
wanted (remember, there was NO advantage in having a bigger ship,
as you just needed to add more weapons for NO gain), AND still be
able to carry the BIGGEST Meson Spinal Mount you could get at your
tech level.

This typically resulted in 50,000-60,000 ton battleships, 10,000 ton
Cruisers, and Destroyers at around 2,000-3,000 tons, which is in
line with their displacement tonnage in later versions.

Any WARship which didn\'t a spinal mount, was built to NO LARGER than
10,000 tons.

It sucked.

There were no significant differences that I remember in the character
generation rules.  The differences in space combat rules were pretty
much given by the ONE battery per weapon type rule (ie - all lasers
had to penetrate your sandcaster rating, vs the need to design your
ship with sufficient sandcasters to stop the number of laser attacks
being made on your ship.)

You didn\'t miss much.

--Derek

----
These opinions are not those of Lotus Development Corporation,
which is not on the "Factor T Meson Gun with incidental
Starship around it" design committee.

