    'month' => '10',
    'body' => 'Les Howie:

> Steve, thanks for you comments: please let me bounce a couple
> of other ideas off you.

	De nada...


> JSHiggin@aol.com writes
>>> Generating a half dozen subsectors, say 200 worlds, I found a
>>> significant number of rules with base naval tax rates in the
>>> trillions of credits per year (worlds with pop 9 or 10, high
>>> pop multipliers, and good exchange rates)

>> Sounds normal so far...

> Good - I take it players would start with whopping big fleets,
> then? 

	Quite.  Expect fleet tonnage on the general order of 1T per
KCr100 of annual budget.  If your players\' fleets have fewer
than, say, 2,000 ships, they are doing something wrong.  Not
counting fighters, of course...:-)
	And, yes, I know that several of my players had fewer than
2,000 ships.  But several of my players had SMALL main worlds...


>>> Also, any thoughts on a good size for a half dozen players? 
>>> 4-5 sectors, or just a couple?
 
>> One sector is probably more than enough.

> I suffer from chronic fingeritus -- I meant 4-5 subsectors!

	Oh.  Yeah, that\'s not too bad.  It\'ll still be bigger than
your players are likely to be comfortable with, though.  They\'ll
average about eight parsecs apart, which still means four (or
six) turns round trip for one message to their neighbor\'s
capital.  And it means that what they read in a turn about their
fleets happened two (or three) turns ago, and they won\'t be able
to get orders to the fleet (to respond to the events of two (or
three) turns back) for another two (or three) turns...


> My first thought on a scenerio is to set up 6 subsectors in a
> 2x6 grid to give a 20 row by 24 column surface.

	2x6 = 6?  I suppose you really meant 2x3 grid? ;-)


> On of my friends has been encouraging me to include some rules
> covering trade and commerce, with an impact on world tax
> levels.  Do you have an opinion on that?

	By all means!  If you come up with _good_ rules, forward them
to me, please.  I used trade and commerce rules in my last one,
but the rules were quite abstract, and never really had much
effect on the game (except for the Alliance, which had picked up
a sizable amount of excess cash by encouraging intra-Alliance
trade, and by being able to protect their shipping from their
neighbors (the Belters, specifically)).  I expect that they would
have been more significant if I had used another theatre, and
allowed for the players controlling a dozen or so worlds apiece
(makes it much harder to defend, eh?).

	I also recommend, though it tends to be a lot of extra work,
using complete solar systems (as generated by Scouts, or whatever
system you like).  You get a completely different picture of the
utility of gas giants when there are more than one per system. 
And when you go to the trouble of figuring out how long it REALLY
takes to get from one of the gas giants to your main world (or
even another gas giant)...

				----Steve H.
