    'date' => 'Tue, 18 Oct 1994 10:24:04  0500',
    'body' => ' Ted7@world.std.com (Mitchell K Schwartz) said:
>
>I\'m producing Xboat maps of (unprinted) sectors.  I figured out the 
>postscript code for creating lines from one hex to another.  What I need is
>a reasonable set of rules for determining xboat paths. Anyone got any?
>
>Anyone know how they were determined in the first place?
>
>                                        Ted7
>

  Statements I go by:
        1.  X-Boat routes are *expensive*.  Dedicated, high performance
jump craft with very expensive data-banks and trained pilots are not to be
squandered.
        2.  Merchant ships hauling mail are *not* expensive.  They were
going there anyway.

  Basic rules I go by:
        1.  Capitol of given subsector is joined by X-boat routes to
capitols of ajacent subsectors.
        2.  The central world in a high-tech clusters of worlds (I go with
a Jp2 cluster, avg TL 13+) are joined to similar clusters by X-Boat routes.
        3.  X-Boat routes *always* take the shortest route between two
points.
        4.  In any condition where there are more than 5 seperate routes in
a sub-sector, remove the lowest-tech routes first until you only have 5. 
These "abandoned" routes will see plenty of frieghter traffic anyway.
        5.  Border areas and fringes generally only have one or two
X-boat"backbones", largely because of rules 1 & 2.  
        6.  Amber Zoned worlds are avoided unless it prevents rule 1 or 2.
        7.  Red Zoned worlds are avoided regardless.
--
