    'topic' => 'TCS ship design',
    'body' => 'Here\'s the biggest of the Alliance warships, along with an explanation of why
anyone would want to build it. :-)

SD. 1 Enterprise SD-Y666(L)DJ5-F(V0)0700-D00!A-50 MCr3,413,988 2.5 million
tons
                                         W  1Y    Crew=30,525.
                                         X  1Z    TL=15.
Passengers=5000. Low=15,263. Cargo=72,265. Fuel=466,400. EP=320,000.
Agility=6(8). Marines=8000. 750,000 XO racks.  V=400, W=300, X=600, Y=1000,
Z=2000

Notes: Has the usual Alliance hardware: two computers, scoops, NH3 fuel
system, enhanced output maneuver drive, afterburning power plant,
Helson-Canomaar Overdrive, superconducting armour, anti-missile fire control.
The ship can reach 20G on afterburner, but has an agility of 8 when firing.
If the star trigger ceases fire, agility is 10, and if the lasers also cease
fire agility is 12.

The ! code represents the star trigger meson gun. This weapon is designed to
flare stars (or ignite gas giants) when fired in conjunction with two others.
It can also be used in ship-to-ship combat. It\'s damage rating is not yet
defined exactly, but certainly very high--probably around Factor-ZZ.

Carries 5 95-ton and 15 30-ton small craft, 500 90-ton fighters. Has 5
100-ton launch tubes. Has 60,000 ton missile magazine (20,000
battery-rounds), 6500 ER missile gunners, 50 tonne AM containment pod, 15,000
battery-rounds in XO racks, 12 parsecs jump fuel. The considerable cargo
space is generally fitted with modular office space appropriate to the
specifc function of the ship.

The Enterprise-class is (as far as anyone knows) the largest, most powerful,
and most expensive warship ever built. The ships are labelled "star
destroyers" after a fictional class of ships similar in purpose (and almost
identical in size). The design originated within the NFN as a pipe-dream--the
sort of battleship they\'d like to build but never could.

Following the CLW, the Alliance Navy had requirements for ships with
substantially different missions, all of which would need to be very large.
These were as follows:

During the Occupation, New Home\'s Station Omega, a deep space command and
control station, had served as Alliance Navy headquarters. It had performed
quite well, and was never located by the Imperium, but the Alliance Navy
command was concerned about the possibility that it would be found in a
future action. In response to this danger, the Naval Construction Board
issued a requirement for a mobile version of Station Omega, which could run
away if it was found by a large force, or destroy a small scout force.

In 5646 Alliance R&D completed Project Starburst, the development of star
trigger technology. The star trigger required huge ships to mount it and the
power plant needed to run it (it uses twice the entire power output of a St.
Genevieve-class battleship). The Alliance Navy wanted to build at least two
sets of three.

By the late 5640\'s the Alliance\'s superiority in battleship power was falling
fast. The Navy wanted to make up for that by building something so impressive
that the mere sight of it would terrify any enemy.

These requirements were combined and put together into one ship based on the
old NFN design. The class\' primary function is a deep space command and
control center. In addition to serving as the emergency capital of the
Alliance, the class will also serve as flagships for the Numbered Fleets. The
class also acts as part of the Alliance\'s strategic deterrent, ready to
destroy enemy systems in response to an attack. Finally, the class can be
used as a giant battleship in a major fleet action or in gunboat diplomacy.

The Alliance Navy has ordered six of these ships, but to date only four have
been completed. These ships have been assigned to the numbered fleets as
flagships. To date, only the _Macross_ has seen any action.

When the class was proposed, there were no other battleships so large in
existence--the closest were the million-ton battleships built by the Imperium
centuries ago (and in mothballs for most of that time). The meson gun simply
made giant battleships too vulnerable to destruction.

With the advent of the afterburning power plant, things are changing--meson
guns simply can\'t track afterburning ships. Because of this, large
battleships (with afterburners) are making a comeback. As of 5650, aside from
the Alliance\'s four ships, the Imperium is refitting ten ancient million-ton
battleships, and the Aslan Clans controlling the Riftspan Reaches have
ordered at least two 1.75 million ton battleships.

Ken
