    'from' => 'Ethan Henry',
    'body' => 'Recently I managed to dig up a few old issues of Challenge
I had lying around semi-lost and an issue of the Traveller\'s
Digest. I found some interesting thing in them concerning
Classic Traveller...

The Traveller\'s Digest is copyrighted 1986 (the publishing date
is 344-1112, ho ho) and has an interview with Marc Miller about
\'The Future of Traveller\'. There were some interesting quotes -
"If I had to do it over again, I think I could do a 1,000 percent
better job, knwoing what I know now". I dunno about this one.
While the mechanics have certain improved in MT and TNE (which I
haven\'t seen yet) I think the essential Traveller backdrop remains
very intact and largely unchanged, which I like, but I don\'t know
if the new games are "1,000% better". Another quote - "Traveller is 10
years old and not at it\'s peak." Hm. Maybe he changed his mind. Then
again, Traveller has survived a long time and it\'s not all that
surprising that it\'s gone through a few incarnations.

Most intersting is the mention of new products. Spinward Campaign is
mentioned and I have that, but they also mention a Darrians supplement,
which I\'ve never seen or heard of. Anyone?

Coincidently enough, in Challenge #29, there\'s another interview.
(And woah, Loren Wiseman is listed as \'Managing Editor\'. He had
a real job when I was, like, 16. Wow. Anyways...) This interview/
massive-back-patting lists all the GDW publication up until 1987
and _doesn\'t_ list Darrians, so I guess it got shelved. Anyone know
why? (Loren?) Not too much meat in this interview, but there are some
more products I\'ve never seen - \'Alien Realms\' and \'Atlas of the
Imperium\'. Anyone care to fill me in on what\'s in these?

Anyways, Traveller was 15 in 1992 and will be 20 years old in 1997.
That\'s not that far off. Considering the number of games that have
come and gone in that time, it\'s a real testament to the great
game(s) Traveller is. Traveller has survivied a lot of trends in
the industry (re: the \'dark setting\' thread) but has come
through looking a lot today like it did in 1977. Well, somewhat.

Just thought I\'d share that historical data with the rest of the list. :)

Ethan

PS. Anyone got a copy of K\'kree for CT they wouldn\'t mind parting with?
Anyone reasonably close to Ottawa so I don\'t have to pay shipping
halfway across the subsector?
