    'body' => 'ehenry@Newbridge.COM (Ethan Henry) wrote:
> [In ...] an interview with Marc Miller about \'The Future of
> Traveller\'.  "If I had to do it over again, I think I could do a 1,000%
> better job, knwoing what I know now". I dunno about this one.

It\'s interesting to note that Marc Miller never did \'do it over again\'.

It seems, from reading the credits on the rulebooks, that the MegaTraveller
re-write was done primarily by the folks at Digest Group Publications,
without a lot of input, checking, or even proofreading by GDW\'s Traveller
people.  It\'s sad to say, but I think a lot of the problems with
MegaTraveller were caused by this, and generally sloppy work on the part of
both groups.

Traveller: The New Era is indeed a complete re-write of Traveller, but
again, this was after Marc Miller left the company.  From reading the
credits on that book, it seems that most of the work was done by Dave
Nilsen and Frank Chadwick.  T:TNE uses the Twilight:2000 role-playing
system, which IMHO has no relation to Traveller (although GDW Official
Company Policy is that the T2k2 system is a direct descendant of original
Traveller, through unspecified provenance).

It would have been interesting to know what changes Marc would have chosen
to make to the game, if HE had to do it over again.

> Most intersting is the mention of new products. Spinward Campaign is
> mentioned and I have that, but they also mention a Darrians supplement,
> which I\'ve never seen or heard of. Anyone?

I\'ve had my hands on both.  I believe I own a copy of the Spinward Campaign
(or at least, most of it - purchased used, and rather beaten up).  I have
read, but do not own, the Darrians supplement.  Both are the 8.5x11
(large-size) modules produced late in the life-cycle of Classic Traveller.
It\'s quite possible that these were pulled from the shelves when 
MegaTraveller was released, so there wasn\'t much chance to pick them up.

Spinward Campaign is a campaign-seed (not really a campaign in the sense
that The Traveller Adventure is a ready-made campaign) set, logically enough,
in the Spinward Marches immediately after the 5th Frontier War.

Darrians is a typical Classic Traveller aliens module, and covers the
Darrians in detail.  Not much to say, but this is one I should pick up at
some point.

> Coincidently enough, in Challenge #29, there\'s another interview.
> (And woah, Loren Wiseman is listed as \'Managing Editor\'. He had
> a real job when I was, like, 16.

Loren edited _The Journal of the Travellers\' Aid Society_ (direct
predecessor to Challenge, and a truly excellent single-product magazine),
all the way back to issue #1 (and since the Journal was quarterly, go
figure what age you were when he started that particular \'real job\').
If Loren is reading, didn\'t you win some awards with the Journal, too?  :-)

> more products I\'ve never seen - \'Alien Realms\' and \'Atlas of the
> Imperium\'. Anyone care to fill me in on what\'s in these?

I own both of them.  They\'re both the large-size (8.5x11) modules that GDW
produced during the last years of Classic Traveller.  The Atlas of the
Imperium contains computer-generated maps of the WHOLE imperium - I believe
the data files for these maps is the original source for the sector files on
the archive site.  In any case, it\'s just maps showing the locations of all
worlds in the sector, and naming the high-population and subsector capitol
worlds.  This is interesting, but not terribly useful, but does make a neat
wall mural (tape the maps together edge-to-edge, and color occupied \'hexes\'
in in light colors - if you want to get weird, color the \'mains\' in in
slighly darker colors).

Alien Realms is a set of short adventures, each one featuring one of the
alien races in one way or another.  Sometimes the PCs are aliens, and other
times the PCs are humans who have to deal with the aliens.

> Anyways, Traveller was 15 in 1992 and will be 20 years old in 1997.

Keep the dust off those old Books 1-8, and start planning your Traveller
20th Anniversary Campaign now.  :-)


