    'from' => 'alvin plummera plummera@hubble.sheridanc',
    'body' => '
A leser, but mildly interesting, Question...

Within the Third Imperium (Classic) , under what circumstances does the
"run-of-the-mill" dirtsider\'s life intersect with the greater concerns of
interstellar affairs?

Off the bat...
    Big Business (From Empire-wide megacorps to businessess based on
                  nearby, high-pop worlds)
    The Navy (THE reason for the Empire\'s existance)
    Imperial Taxation (For the above Navy, plus Marines)
    Multistellar News services (The TNS, Domain News, etc...)
        "        Cultural associations (To the Imperial Rotary Club to the 
                                        Imperial Catholic Church (Deneb
Rite))
    The Nobility (as celebrities, leaders)
    Scientific Organizations (probably as Info Exchanges, rather than 
                  a megaresearch \'guild\')

What other structures/associations would tend to have interstellar
connections?

More interestingly, what associations would tend to remain system-bound?

----

Continuing along this thread...

I recently posted a profile of a "noble leader" in TML (Queen
whats-her-name, a marchoniess in the New Era Regency).  How would similar
"minor political forces" operate in an interstellar society?  I\'m thinking
of, say, the President of a TL8 high-pop world in Classic Spinward Marches or
the Ruling Circle of a TL 13 high-pop world in Rebellion-Era Core sector.

How would the concerns of a High-pop world differ from a moderate-pop
world?  A low-pop world?

----

And what about not-so-minor officals, say subsector to Domain nobility
(ie. the Archduke of Sol, the Duke of Trin\'s Veil subsector).  I
understand their military responsibilities, and their responsibility to
"keep the trade lanes open": do they have any others?  How do the
"identities" of the different sectors differ? (If I recall correctly,
Daibei worlds like tricolour flags, Verge people are rebellious, the
Spinward Marches folk have a rough "Colonial" attitude and Core has
entirely too much wealth and privelege)

(Anyone cares to add more "regional stereotypes"?)

And why would these worlds in a sector bond together like this?  Why
aren\'t they just seperate, individual, isolated societies, bound together
only by the Emperor, the Navy and the Megacorps?  Since contact with
insystem folk is so much quicker, how could they maintain "fellow feeling"
with a world a subsector away?  

Thinking about it, I feel that the "atmosphere" of a sector would be
strongly dictated by the high-pop, TL C+ systems in that sector.  The
sector capital and subsector capitals would also influence the "mindset"     
of a given sector.  Also, a shared history would also sustain fellow
feeling, especially pre-imperial, (sub)sector-wide governments.

----

A help would be the nature and scope of the nobility\'s economic powers,
since it is via those powers that the subsector, sector, and Domain
nobility would most strongly distinguish one sector from another.  What
can be banned from one sector, but allowed in another?  Why would a
sector-wide manufactoring concern in Massillia be unheard-of in Diasporia?
A TL 5 moviestar, loved across Gushmerge, be laughed at at Vland?

And what does it take to be famous across the entire Imperium?  A musician
on the level of Mozart (interesting: Mozart himself was at about TL 3)?  
But a society of 15 trillion people should have at least 10,000 Mozarts at
any one time.  A genius on the scale of Newton?  Again, the same problem
as Mozart - actually, even worse; a TL 3  Newton would be merely reinventing
the wheel for the 9354th time.

Again, I suspect that only genuses on TL F - G worlds would obtain the
Imperium-wide fame they deserve.  

But, what about all those people at TL 8 or 5 or B?  Are they just treated
like country bumpkins?  And, in situations where the high-pop worlds are 
lower than at, say TL C, how do the other systems react to it?

Of couse, all and any responses are welcome.

Alvin Plummer
("Computers with only 320 MB of storage?  Only four Space Shuttles?!?  No
orbiting factories?  No starport?  Where is this aborigional world,
anyways?" )

