    'from' => 'Ethan Henry',
    'body' => 'First, thanks for all the responses about Darrians. I didn\'t
expect _quite_ that many. I wish I was still in school so I
could ask all you people calculus questions and get that
kind of response. :)

But on to interstellar organizations,

alvin plummera writes:
>And why would these worlds in a sector bond together like this?  Why
>aren\'t they just seperate, individual, isolated societies, bound together
>only by the Emperor, the Navy and the Megacorps?  Since contact with
>insystem folk is so much quicker, how could they maintain "fellow feeling"
>with a world a subsector away?

Television, the drug of the nation. er, subsector.  Look at Terra - 5 or so
billion people and a really disproportionate amount of entertainment comes
out of one place - Hollywood. Although a lot of places have very strong 
regional entertainment industries (India, Hong Kong/China), you still get
Hollywood stuff there. Very rarely does it happen the other way around either
(how many Hong Kong pop starts have broken through on the North American
market?). It\'s very possible the cultural commodities could be just as, if 
not more valuable than more concrete ones. (Pirates make a raid to grab the 
latest shipment of 2-hour holovids from Regina!) Look at some examples today
-
would you rather be in the uranium mining business or in the film business?
Of course, the average asteroid belt dweller has little choice, but a lot
of uranium probably has to go out to get a decent film in.

>Thinking about it, I feel that the "atmosphere" of a sector would be
>strongly dictated by the high-pop, TL C+ systems in that sector.  The
>sector capital and subsector capitals would also influence the "mindset"

>of a given sector.  Also, a shared history would also sustain fellow
>feeling, especially pre-imperial, (sub)sector-wide governments.

Given the influences of technology transfer from high tech to low tech worlds
and the influence of cultural industries the same way, I\'d agree with you.
Most of this influence relies on wide channels of communication, something
somewhat lacking in the Imperium. Still, I think a lot of cultural trading
would go on. (Why do I keep thinking of EuroDisney? I dunno. Maybe \'cause
it\'s
the worlds biggest & worstest cultural export to date. Bad example).

Also, I think that the big interstellar organizations would have a life
and culture of their own, which would have a tendancy to influence cultures
across a large reach of space. Being a member of the IISS would be a 
pretty universal thing, probably because the Scout service goes out of its
way to make it so. So wherever you go, a scout is a scout, more or less.
Due to character\'s habits of hanging around familiar places (ie. getting the
free fuel for your scout ship at the local scout base) I think this would
somewhat homogenize Imperial culture for PC\'s.

>And what does it take to be famous across the entire Imperium?  A musician
>on the level of Mozart (interesting: Mozart himself was at about TL 3)?  
>But a society of 15 trillion people should have at least 10,000 Mozarts at
>any one time.  A genius on the scale of Newton?  Again, the same problem
>as Mozart - actually, even worse; a TL 3  Newton would be merely reinventing
>the wheel for the 9354th time.

Mozart, famous? What % of the Earth\'s population do you think heard of him
before he died? Mozart seems big, but that\'s because he\'s had time to get
to everyone. Unfortunately, that amount of time was a lot longer than his
lifespan. And Newton - a lot of people thought he was a wacko back in his
day.
Not to mention he really believed that the world was going to end at the turn

of his century (or something close to that - I make no promises about real
world historical accuracy). I\'d expect that most geniuses would go unnoticed
for a long time by most people.

>Again, I suspect that only genuses on TL F - G worlds would obtain the
>Imperium-wide fame they deserve.  

Unfortunately, I think the only people who will get famous Imperium-wide
are the Emperor and a lot of pop movie stars. Kinda like today. I think the
question is not \'Who will be the Mozart of the 3rd Imperium?\' but \'Who will
be the Madonna, Kevin Costner and Steven Spielberg?\'

>But, what about all those people at TL 8 or 5 or B?  Are they just treated
>like country bumpkins?  And, in situations where the high-pop worlds are 
>lower than at, say TL C, how do the other systems react to it?

It depends on how you interpret tech level - level of manufacture, level of
imported or remenant artifacts, level of general population understanding?
A lot of agricultural worlds short distances from high-tech, industrial
woulds could have manufacturing TLs of 0. Just import everything. Especially
if the other world doesn\'t grow much food. It might be possible for two
worlds in one star system to be like this, making it even more plausible.
On some TL F worlds, you might find manufacturing capability of level F, but
general populace comprehension of only around level A.

I don\'t think high tech worlds would look down totally at low tech ones -
look at how North Americans love camping and outdoorsy stuff. Some low tech
worlds might make a lot of tourist dollars by being low tech. Of course,
some low-tech worlds would be backwaters. Again, look around you. Some
"third world" nations do ok, some are ruthlessly exploited by large
corporations
or have repressive governments.

Woah, long response. Hope I don\'t break anyone\'s mailbox.

Ethan 

And hey, Earth has starports. Well, spaceports. We\'d get an E or D easily.

