    'topic' => 'Interstellar Organisations',
    'body' => '<alvin plummera> posed a question re: how much do the interstellar 
\'big-boys\' interact with everyday dirtsiders...

I would add:

"Illegal Organisations"
\'Wanted on Thripeen? For a mere CR25k we can smuggle you offworld to 
Kirkwerg, who don\'t have an extradition treaty...\'. Aaah, Thieves Guild Gold 
Card! That will do nicely... There just has to be interstellar Mafias, 
Triads, etc. There would be so many opportunities for bending the rules when 
you\'re operating between say ten worlds each with its different pecularities 
of law.

"Interstellar Banks"
The standard banking mechanism for the Imperial Credit; individual worlds 
may have their own money or use credits, but the Interstellar banks are 
still the only recognised way of transfering (laundering?) money between 
systems (except for carrying large piles of gold bars, etc. - it should be 
pointed out that gold bars are not generally accepted currency in local 
bars, restaurants, etc.)
Of course, banking should also include everything money-related - 
interstellar stocks, shares, trading, brokerage, insurance (how do you 
insure your cargo, or even your ship, if the system isn\'t interstellar?)

With regard to Scientific Organisations, they do not have to be megaresearch 
guilds to avoid the \'info exchange\' tag. Almost any scientific undertaking 
which requires exploration or dissemination of information to the public is 
likely to come to the attention of the local populace: "Famed off-world 
explorer Indiana "Han" Jones Solo discovers ancient Thripean culture in 
jungle", "Interstar Nature Protection League mounts campaign to prevent 
extinction of Thripean Two-Clawed Jungle Tiger", "Imperial Scientific League 
visits Thripeen to distribute anti-smoking leaflets."

SOME THOUGHTS ON LEADERS
State banquet on sector capital...
Young Diplomat: "So from whence do you hail, dear lady?"
Lady: "I am the Duchess of Thripeen."
YD: "Oh, yes, I\'ve heard of you. You must have plenty of time for leisure - 
I hear you\'ve only a few thousand subjects on your jungle-bound planet. I 
guess it _only_ got colonised because it gives access to the western sector 
planets."
L: (scowl) "I have so little time, actually. Mostly I\'m signing orders 
closing the starport because some chauvinistic diplomatic wimp called 
Thripeen \'a pit\' or somesuch. It\'s amazing how quickly they come back 
grovelling when they remember their pitiful little jump-2 traders _have_ to 
pass though my \'humble\' little world.
YD: "Oh, er, yes, er..."
L: "I\'m sorry, I didn\'t catch the name of your planet?"
YD: "My, is that the time. Must dash!"

More seriously, a campaign I played in as a Scout Corp Intelligence officer 
with two colleagues eventually brought the three of us to the level of 
Count(esse)s and we were given control of a world in a developing subsector 
on the Imperial/Aslan border. Countess Marava started an interstellar nature 
protection league - gave her plenty of chance to travel and gave us cover 
for some covert operations. Count Farrar controlled a largish navy; as Count 
Lilly I had control of our system\'s industrial base.
In summary, we had to balance a wide range of tasks, both as nobility and as 
ISC covert operatives:
Subsector stability: there were various powers who each wanted to own more 
land, exploit more planets, convert all to their religion, etc. We had to 
keep the situation stable, preferably without throwing in the navy - a 
clumsy act at the best of times. Other powers mysteriously lost technical 
data (particularly that of general use to the Imperium), one planet went 
bankrupt (after some careful dealing by ourselves which allowed us to buy up 
most of its heavy industry through cover companies, thus achieving control 
over an otherwise unstable populace); we murdered the odd foreign 
intelligence operative (the other planets wanted to infiltrate us and keep 
our Imperial nose out of their affairs); we blatted the drugs baron and 
restored the rightful rulers to their throne; we \'matched\' certain local 
nobles and \'arranged\' marriages to strengthen the more stable planets; we 
coordinated naval patrols of the outer systems where Aslan raiders were 
harrying shipping; we developed starports on nearby low-tech worlds (over 
which we had nominal control) in order to develop a second trade route which 
was controlled solely by us and avoided the Aslan areas; we also wanted to 
build our industrial base using low tech materials from these worlds (okay, 
so call it slave labour...). Clearly we couldn\'t handle every penny of our 
accounts, but we could direct matters, e.g. investment in research into new 
weaponry, psionics, a new gas giant refinery technique, etc. Count/Admiral 
Farrar decided which new warships he wanted built, Countess Marava designed 
her own mansion, I... er, I think I just sat in my concrete bunker and got 
more and more paranoid about attempted assassination - that\'s just another 
hazard of being a ruler - there\'s always someone who disagrees with your 
methods.
None of this was possible without diplomacy, for although we had a great 
deal of power and (secret) Imperial backing, we had to balance other 
factors: the most powerful faction was a fairly independent trading 
alliance, so we wanted to keep them sweet because we couldn\'t (directly) 
control them. And then the subsector Duke was nearing retirement, so that 
meant someone would have to step into his shoes... I\'ll leave you to imagine 
the back-stabbing that went on for that...

With regard to inter-system relations,
(a) The \'colony\' factor is a very strong determinant - almost all worlds 
will have been colonised by people from other nearby worlds in a gradual 
process, spreading out from core (not Core) worlds (probably these are now 
the X-boat routes, which explains why some x-boat routes don\'t seem too 
logical).
(b) Add some star battles in which planet A helped planet B (deliberately, 
inadvertantly, for their own gain, because of a treaty agreement or just 
because they\'re nice people)
(c) Add some mutually beneficial trade arrangements - planet A has the rare 
mineral XYZ which planet B (being older and better developed) swaps for its 
industrial goods.
Ok, stir gently, right now you\'ve got some planets in an alliance.

Now, take (a), but someone left the colony there to die or the colony was a 
group of outcasts. Add (b) where planet A didn\'t bother to aid planet B (or 
was even the attacker themselves). Mix in some (c) but planet B swindles 
planet A by sending them faulty and unrepairable goods and crashes their 
stock markets.
Ok, now you\'ve got a couple of planets who hate each other\'s guts.

We haven\'t even started on the wider issues - Imperial oppression/help, 
similar government types (on planets A and B), the religious nutters on 
planet C, etc. As the Young Diplomat found out to his cost above, some 
planets may only have 10 inhabitants but if they\'re a critical lynch pin on 
a trade route, or the only ones who know where the local lanthanum mine is, 
then they gain an importance totally out of proportion to their size.

TL5 MOVIESTARS
Why is a TL 5 Gushmerge movie star laughed at in Vland? Well, try watching a 
Ronald Reagan cowboy movie now.... Need I say more? Well, okay if pushed... 
remember what flares _were_. How many cultural differences can you get on a 
single planet, let alone between in-system worlds and between systems. Try 
rolling out every planet from DGP\'s Worldbuilder\'s Handbook using the 
cultural oddities tables... you\'ll soon see why one culture finds another 
weird or laughable. There are plenty of modern day equivalences, but they 
are generally racist or ethnic or religious, so best avoided here.

TO BE FAMOUS
There are certain things which are liked by a large percentage of the 
population (never ever 100%). e.g. certain types of music strike harmonies 
which we react to instinctively without having to consciously try to 
appreciate the music. Ever thought about the background music which builds 
up gradually as the bug-eyed monster creeps up on the good guy? You don\'t 
need to see the monster to know that it\'s coming, you automatically 
interpret the music to indicate an approaching threat. Think of the classic 
Jaws music. Mix such things with some advanced social science and computer 
aids and you\'d be able to develop music appreciable by a wide range of 
cultures. Do the same with art, etc. and you have the basis for 
interstellar-famed artists.
Then remember the more important factors - s*d what you actually like, it\'s 
how much it cost and its rarity that matters. Wine from grapes grown on 
Earth would be priceless at the outer edges of the Solomani systems. It 
doesn\'t matter if the grapes grow elsewhere - punters will always believe 
the Earth grapes taste better, and will pay through the nose for them.

TL3 \'country bumpkins\' can become quite respectable and well paid if they 
can harvest the local opiate-equivalents more cheaply than producing the 
drug in a high-tech factory.

Look around you. We have quite a range of TLs (probably from 0 up to 8) 
around us on this planet. Just extrapolate a bit...

Time to stop gibbering...

Commander Lilly, PITS (Political Intelligence Team, Scout)
Nothing I say or do in any way reflects the views of my very kind and
generous employers.

