XO Racks.
                     Y=80, Z=100

Notes: This ships uses the usual technology--enhanced output m-drive, H-C
overdrive, NH3 fuel, anti-missile fire control, superconducting armour,
afterburning plant. Has two computers, and also two bridges and two frozen
watches. The ship uses modular construction, and can be built in two years.
The Manta Ray-class, due to its modular construction, has many components in
common with the Alliance-class escort carrier.

Has a 7500-ton missile magazine (2500 battery-rounds), 2 30-ton small craft,
12 parsecs jump fuel, a 1 tonne AM containment pod, and space for 5 90-ton
planetbusters. Has 600 battery-rounds of fire in XO racks.

The Manta Ray-class was designed as a firepower support ship. During a
battle, it stays well back at the edge of ER missile range, and fires on
targets designated by fighters or starships in close combat with the enemy.
To fulfill this mission, it has a very heavy missile armament for its size,
and 2.5 times the magazine capacity of the "close combat" ships.

Because it is so focused on fire support, the ship is somewhat vulnerable to
enemy battlecruisers getting in energy weapon range. The class\'s designers
compensated for that by providing a heavy XO salvo, which is normally kept in
reserve and fired only if an enemy ship tries to close the range--the salvo
is heavy enough that even the toughest battleship should lose its M-drive. In
case an enemy ship gets into energy range anyway, the Manta Ray\'s tough
shield can block 45 batteries of energy weapon fire per turn.

Because the class is a fleet support ship, it has seen little action as of
5650. Several ships did participate in the Battle of Quiver, though, and
performed adequately.

Unlike the designs I\'ve posted previously, which came from Neubayern designs,
the Manta Ray is a Sansterran design. The use of modular technology, heavy
redundancy, and reliance on missile weapons is typical of Sansterre\'s design
philosophy.

Ken
