    'topic' => 'Regional Stereotypes',
    'index' => 'aa294',
    'month' => '10',
    'body' => '
X::>>How do the "identities" of the different sectors differ? (If I recall
 ::>>correctly, Daibei worlds like tricolour flags, Verge people are
 ::>>rebellious, the Spinward Marches folk have a rough "Colonial" attitude
 ::>>and Core has entirely too much wealth and privelege)

X::>>(Anyone cares to add more "regional stereotypes"?)

X::>Antarean humans/Vargr work well with Vargr/humans.

X::>Corridor people are somewhat "paranoid" and military-minded (they are
 ::>very sensitive to TNS reports about defense cuts!).

X::>Vland citizens are very stuffy, and tend to go on at the drop of a hat
 ::>about "Ziru Sirka this" and "Vilani Main never lost jump drive" that
 ::>and "five thousand year empire" the other. They also can never do
 ::>anything in less than a group of three.

X::>Gushemegites and Dagudashaagites tend to get annoyed at the above,
 ::>and exhibit a noticeable "we\'re not Vland, dammit!" attitude, as they
 ::>go about their business in their asymmetrical clothes on worlds that
 ::>have been settled for thousands of years.

X::>Ilelish residents "buck the Imperial trend" more than most (but don\'t
 ::>stoop to outright revolt, like Vergers). Some of them are known to be
 ::>outright odd even in faraway places ("Mad as a Dlani"...).

X::>And don\'t forget that different regions of the Imperium have a
 ::>different "accent" based on their Galanglic dialect (Transform, Rim
 ::>Anglic, etc.). I would expect the Vilani-speaking worlds to have their
 ::>own "Vilani accent" as well, but a better linguist than I will have to
 ::>codify it. Basically I think it would involve breaking up consonant
 ::>clusters that don\'t occur in Vilani, and perhaps mutating "o" into
 ::>"au" because the former doesn\'t occur in Vilani either. That and
 ::>having trouble when people pronounce the same thing in different tones
 ::>of voice. (I once worked with a Thai student who said she had some
 ::>trouble understanding English because people kept pronouncing the same
 ::>word with different intonation and expecting it to mean the same
 ::>thing!)

 Solomani, even the Imperial ones, have a certain level of disdain 
 for centralized authority.  They\'re also more ready to go off the 
 beaten path to find their answers, or just to be "different".  
 There is an attitude of cultural/racial/ethnic superiority, 
 tracing back to "well, _we_ took on the Ziru Sirka when we first 
 developed Jump, and wiped the floor with them", despite the fact 
 that it wasn\'t exactly a floor-wiping.  Solomani are also more 
 likely to make snap judgements about other people (even Solomani) 
 based on physical appearances and stereotypes.
----
  QMPro 1.53  Chief Archivist, Regency Institute for Cultural Education
