    'date' => 'Sun, 30 Oct 1994 20:59:21  0500',
    'body' => 'Here\'s a new ship. This one is a close relative of the Manta Ray-class.

CVE-1 Alliance CV-P456(7)7J4-4(F0)0700-0000A-12 MCr59,034.4 67,500 tons
bearing                                    Y    Crew=1121.
batteries                                  Z    TL=15.
Low=1121. Cargo=1257. Fuel=10,655. EP=4914. Agility=6(7). Marines=156. 30,000
XO Racks.
                             Y=40, Z=50

Notes: This ships uses the usual technology--enhanced output m-drive, H-C
overdrive, NH3 fuel, anti-missile fire control, superconducting armour,
afterburning plant. Has two computers, and also two bridges and two frozen
watches. The ship uses modular construction, and can be built in two years.
The Alliance-class, due to its modular construction, has many components in
common with the Manta Ray-class battlecruiser.

Has 2 30-ton small craft, 12 parsecs jump fuel, a 1 tonne AM containment pod,
and space for 120 90-ton fighters (normally FA-5E Super Kraits). Has a
balcony and track launch system with balcony space for 80 fighters and a
track able to move up to 80 per turn. Has 600 battery-rounds of fire in XO
racks. Unlike nearly every other Alliance warship, this class does not have
an ER missile magazine.

The Alliance-class was conceived before the Serendip War as a "battle
carrier," a ship which would assist the Manta Ray-class in providing fire
support, and would also carry fighters to provide ER missile guidance. During
the Imperial Occupation, the Alliance Navy decided to use the ship for its
new escort carrier, since the requirements of a battle carrier were nearly
identical to those of an escort carrier.

The escort carrier is a fleet defense ship, similar in purpose (though very
different in design) to the 20th century Aegis ships. The carrier\'s fighters
are deployed ahead of a fleet to provide a first line of defense against
incoming missile fire. Although a fighter\'s antimissile capabilities are
nowhere near as good as a starship\'s, the fighter screen can thin an incoming
salvo enough for ship-mounted defenses to deal with it. In addition, the
carrier itself stays close to the more valuable units and uses its missile
bays for defensive fire--essentially acting like a giant destroyer. Like the
Manta Ray, the Alliance-class keeps its XO racks in reserve to deal with
anything that breaks through to threaten it (or the ships it\'s protecting).

The Alliance Navy developed the escort carrier idea as a way of defending
against the kind of massive missile salvoes that their own ships can throw.
However, for the first several years the class was in service nobody else had
the Alliance\'s missile technology. During that time, the class served more
often as an independent light carrier than an escort. In 5650, the class
still sees use in the light carrier role, but the spread of advanced missile
technology has returned many of them to escort duty.

Ken
