    'body' => 'The Alliance Navy began building a Mark II antimatter production facility as
soon as the Imperial Navy had been ejected from the Islands Cluster. The
facility would be operational in 5650. At the same time, the Navy prepared
plans for antimatter-powered versions of all its ships. These ships would be
built starting in 5647.

All Alliance Navy antimatter ships have several things in common. They all
use superconducting armour, and anti-missile fire control. They all have
antimatter jump drives, and antimatter power plants (called M/ARA in Alliance
terminology). They retain the enhanced output maneuver drives of the NH3
ships, and have a secondary power plant--always a Factor-1 afterburning power
plant. They carry enough fuel to run their M/ARA for one year, and their
afterburner for one month.

The second plant is used partially to provide auxiliary power, but more
importantly to provide additional thrust in combat to supplement the regular
maneuver drive. The idea of two plants used this way dates back to the 20th
century, when wet-navy warships often had a diesel engine for cruising and a
gas turbine for high-speed maneuvers.

The antimatter used by these ships is stored in a series of 1 tonne
containment pods. For simplicity, a ship\'s AM capacity will be totalled--for
instance, a ship described as having a 302 tonne containment pod really had
302 1 tonne pods. All of these pods can be ejected from the ship in an
emergency, as can the M/ARA.

Some Alliance worlds (most notably Browne) are concerned about the danger of
an antimatter containment failure aboard a visiting warship, and forbid AM
powered ships landing on them. The actual danger of an accidental failure is
almost nil, but it\'s more of a problem in battle. As a result, the Alliance
Navy forbids AM powered ships from getting too close to an inhabited planet
during battle.

Although ships are hardly ever destroyed outright in battle, it\'s much easier
to force them to crash in a battle near a planet--over one hundred fleet
escorts crashed on Neubayern during the Serendip War, for instance. Most AM
powered ships carry enough antimatter to reduce a planet to gravel if their
containment pods were to fail during a crash.

Ken
