    'from' => 'KenHagler@aol.com',
    'body' => 'Dave Smith asks:

> Uh, Ken,

> How do you handle the fact that one fuel hit destroys
> your entire ship, and maybe your entire *fleet*?

Well, every design has its flaws. :-)

Seriously, it\'s not as easy to blow up an AM ship as it might first appear.
First, you have to hit it--all Alliance ships have pretty high agilities.
Then, you\'ve got to get through its active defenses--dozens of missile
batteries firing defensively agaiinst incoming missiles. Finally, you\'ve got
to get through its passive defenses--thick shields blocking energy weapons,
and superconducting armour reducing the effect of lasers and nukes, not to
mention the old fashioned nuclear damper.

Then you\'ve got to get the right fuel. AM ships don\'t carry just AM
fuel--they generally carry about four times as much NH3 as AM, for
afterburner reaction mass and jump drive fuel. A fuel hit is more likely to
hit the NH3. If the AM is hit, KABOOM. Well, nobody said AM fuel was
flawless. The idea is that the merits outway the vulnerability to explosion.

As for taking other ships with it, I don\'t think that\'s a problem. Warships
don\'t exactly stay close to each other in battle. The nearest friendly ship
probably won\'t be close enough to go up in the secondary explosion--and the
nearest enemy ship is probably in just as much danger. Note that I say
_probably_. I don\'t really know for sure what the danger zone of an exploding
AM ship in space is, I don\'t have a clue how to figure this out. I\'m just
assuming that it\'s not a problem because I don\'t know how much of a problem
it would be (if any), and because it\'s an unnecessary complication. If you
know how to figure out the damage radius, by all means please tell me.

Of course, fighing in an atmosphere is a different story. Exploding AM ships
are a major danger there. Not only is an exploding AM ship likely to destroy
other ships in the atmosphere with it, it\'ll also blow off the atmosphere. In
fact, it\'s got a good chance of blowing up the planet. Needless to say, AM
ships do not fight too close to planets that they want to preserve.

For illustration, let\'s take a hypothetical engagement. Here\'s the scenario:

Alliance force: 1 Crazy Horse BCH, 1 Tisiphone DDF, 5 FA-6 Cobra fighters.
Total tonnage 85,450 tons.
Imperial force: 1 Kokirrak BB
No other ships are involved, all XO racks are empty. The Alliance uses AM
missiles, the Kokirrak has anti-missile fire control and is using KE missiles
(wouldn\'t want this to be a complete turkey shoot).
Action begins at short range, the DDF and fighters are deployed to provide
missile defense for the BCH. Again in the interests of fairness, the BCH is
forbidden to move beyond long range (for whatever reason). Fleet tactics DMs
are +1 Alliance, +2 Imperial. 

Turn 1: Alliance is the attacker, and opens the range to long. Combat:
BB fires at BCH, all weapons.
33 Beam Laser-6, 1 hit
23 Particle Accelerator-7, 2 hits
33 Missile-9, 6 hits
DDF fires 6 missile batteries defensively at 6 hits, stops all of them.
BCHs shield stops laser and PA hits.
BCH fires at BB, all weapons.
DDF fires at BB, all lasers and remaining 4 missile bays.
FA-6s fire at BB, 5 batteries total.
43 Beam Laser-D, 25 hits
1 APAWS-S, 1 hit
79 Missile-A, 57 hits
5 Missike-7, 3 hits
BB fires 13 repulsor batteries defensively at Missile-A hits, stops 13 of
them.
BB fires 33 sandcaster batteries at Missile-A hits, no effect (same story if
they\'d fired at the laser hits).
Damage:
Weapon-104
Fuel-32
Maneuver-6 (and then some)
Effects:
BB is dead in space; has 54,400 tons of fuel left
Loses 14 sandcasters, 15 repulsors, 15 lasers, 15 fusion, 15 pa, 15 meson
factors, 15 missiles

The BB captain has a choice. If he stays, he needs an 11 with his meson gun
to hit the BCH, but his ship will certainly be crippled and captured by the
Alliance. If he runs, he can go for repairs and fight on, but without
touching the Alliance fleet. The BB would pretty much always run, unless it
was defending Capital or something.

As an aside, I did simulate Turn 2 to satisfy my curiousity. The BB rolled
the 11, and blew up the BCH. In return, it was crippled. Still not a bad
tradeoff, losing a BCH and capturing a BB that cost almost three times as
much.

Ken
