    'body' => '
Neat idea to post some old stuff to the list alvin, I enjoyed
it, as I hadn\'t seen it before.

And before my comments, I called GDW themselves yesterday and
believe it or not, they still have a fair hunk of out-of-print
Traveller materials in stock. Aslan, Darrians, Beltstrike, Tarsus,
The Adventure and some misc. adventures. Good prices too -
Darrians $8. I\'m in no way affiliated with the company we hate to
love, but it is a good price on hard-to-find stuff. I don\'t 
have the phone # right here, but there\'s a price list on
ftp.mpgn.com and it has it, or mail me. I was impressed that they
still had as much stuff as they did, considering how long it\'s been
out of print.

Now...

>My point: this situation shouldn\'t happen. It goes not only
>against intuition and common sense, it goes against the principle
>of greed, the fundamental root of human nature (yes, I\'m down on
>humanity, but that\'s not the point here). The point is that this
>rule system is... flawed, no other way to put it. (I can see
>several people shaking their heads and saying "you mean you just
>figured this out?") Hey, I\'ve always been a big believer in
>classic traveller, and the spinward marches are about as classic
>as you can get. But the point stands, there\'s something rotten in
>the Lanth subsector, and it mostly likely extends from the whole
>set of rules on UWP generation.

And he goes on to describe a modified system of world generation,
with a lot of good ideas. (As well as moving Hamlet into the Third
Imperium - \'something\'s rotten in the subsector of Lanth\')

I think the idea behind the original rules is that the only
thing the players care about (on first glance) is the starport.
The rules are set up to give a certain distribution of starports
of different grades. This then needs a way to justify why there\'s
a type A starport there. It\'s is ass-backwards, I agree, but in
the Traveller universe, there\'s a lot of room for slightly 
illogical worlds.

Why are there 20 million people on a planet with a crappy atmosphere?
Maybe there was a population explosion during the long night
and the people have adjusted to that level of population without
amazing technology. Maybe locals have adapted to be a lot less
bothered by the conditions. Maybe the locals go on to become great 
endurance runners on other worlds with denser atmospheres.

Why are there only 20 people on the corporate-owned earth-like world?
Maybe no one wants people to go there. Maybe there\'s a disease
fatal to human life on the world. Maybe there\'s an ancients site.

I think even the stupidest UPP(UWP, whatever) can be justified by a 
good ref with a little imagination. For me, that\'s part of the 
appeal of Traveller.

What I\'d like someone to spout off about is sports in the 3rd
Imperium - a stable, civilized society would have a fairly
large focus on entertainment and lesiure, especially on worlds
nearer the core, but still, everywhere. Would there be an Imperial
Olympics? Would there be different classes for athetes coming from
high-g vs. low-g worlds? Would size-A thin-atmosphere planets
draw lots of athletes to train there? And of course, drugs, drugs,
drugs. Athletics is big business today, it\'d be even more so in
the 3rd Imperium. (Please note however, the 3rd Imperium isn\'t
Rome in space. Is it?)

Ethan
