I didn\'t look at all these old files, but James Vassailikos\'
old article from bundle 441 (5177) caught my eye.  To sum
up, he went over the Spinward Marches data and saw some
stuff that didnt make sense.  Sonthert/Lanth had tons of
people with only local tech of 3, while 5 parsecs away,
La\'Belle/Lanth looks ideal but has hardly anyone.  His
conclusion was that this shouldn\'t happen, and wen\'t about
changing world generation to fix it.

I\'m of the other school of thought.  I think the bizarre
situations are great opportunities to come up with some
local color.  For instance, take La\'Belle:

>La\'Belle      2416 C564112-4    Lo Ni              701 Im 

Corporate rule, 70 permanent residents...tech 4.  Hmmm.
Maybe this world has a nasty climate -- or nasty climate
shifts.  (Is it a two star system?  Would have to look.)
Or local life is too much of a problem to deal with.
But there might be something useful there because of this;
hence the corporate presence.  But since it\'s a source 
of some resource, local production need not be very 
sophisticated -- imports at the company store, or some
local entrepreneurs with scrounged equipment, but that\'s
it.  Or any number of other things.  Where is it in the
subsector?  Is it in the Abyss?  On the Main?  Maybe 
some explanation for the weirdness can be contrived.

Despite what people have said, post-virus, I think the
"blue-sky" Terra-norm worlds might in some cases be
more difficult to settle than a worse world -- there\'ll
be life down there, and who knows what all might be 
going on.  Vaccuum worlds are much more predictable,
and with proper planning might also be easier on the
equipment.  So more people might settle there, especially
if the colony is well established -- a vaccuum world
colony interior can be much more sophisticated and
spacious than, say, Moonbase Alpha.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
