>> Mark Clark
> 
> The Spinward Marches is a big place.  Where are your campaigns taking
place?

I use the Regina, Aramis, Lanth, and Rhylanor subsectors.  In a fit of
over-organization some time ago, I went through all the Classic Traveller
publications I own and wrote down every refernce to a Spinward Marches
location on a series of index cards.  Since I own everything GDW ever
published for Traveller (including every issue of JTAS), plus everything
Digest Group published, this gives me lots of reference material.  This
provides me with ready-reference background for many worlds without having
to develop it myself.  Since the vast majority of the adventures in
Classic Traveller are set in the four subsectors I mentioned, running
adventures there is easy. 

I also like these subsectors because of the wide range of planets present 
- everything from Tech 15 high pop worlds to isolated balls of rock with 
lots of stuff in between.  There are also three Imperial reseach 
stations, lots of scout and naval bases, and those naughty Zho are just 
across the border.  And who could forget the Ine Givar (I haven\'t)? 

> What kind of adventures do you find most suitable for PBeM games?

Non-combat, since one can\'t resolve combat in a way that\'s fair to player 
characters at the pace I run things.  I do a formal turn only once a 
week, though I encourage the players to interact with one another between 
times.  Those able to run turns more often or those with access to 
real-time forums might be able to handle combat.

My game does three things.  One, it allows the players to show off their 
character\'s personalities by interacting with one another.  Second, it 
allows contact with a succesion of different cultures on different planets 
(the starship is a plot device to move from one isolated location to 
another).  Finally, there is a mystery to be solved that will slowly suck 
the players in and then require solution so that they can live to tell 
the tale.  The first two elements serve as color to keep the game 
interesting, the mystery drives the plot.

> What procedures do you use for running a PBeM game?

See above.  The one other thing I think is important is to encourage the 
players to give their characters a fully developed past.  In other words, 
more than just a set of stats and skills.  All the folks who are playing 
have sent me at least two pages worth of description, and some 
considerably more, all about family, friends, lovers, enemies, places 
they\'ve visited, etc.  This allows me to develop the campaign in a way that 
links the players with their pasts - they act out of motivations, not for 
game reasons.

Frankly, I think I\'ve been very lucky so far - I have a great group who 
are really into Traveller and know the game well enough to play it under 
my not-so-experienced leadership (this is the first PBEM game I\'ve run).

> Sounds cool.  I\'m looking forward to your reply.  As others might be
interested > in the answers as well, I\'ve posted your message and this one
to the Xboat. 

Go right ahead, I don\'t mind, as long as you think it might interest 
others.  


Mark Clark
University of Delaware
