    'index' => 'aa346',
    'body' => 'From: erwin@fritz.cuug.ab.ca (Erwin Fritz)

>Mark Clark said that he likes the CT world-building system\'s occasionally
>weird results.  I have to agree.  I like the challenge of having to explain
>why a garden world has hardly anyone on it, or why people choose to live on
>a hellhole.

>What bugs me is why there must be exactly ONE starport per system!  That\'s
>like saying that New York\'s allowed only one international airport.  Where\'s
>the logic.

This was addressed in World Builder\'s Handbook, I think, and probably in 
the ancestor publication Grand Census as well.  I don\'t have a copy handy, 
but I believe there are provisions for additional landing points and 
extra starports depending on population and other factors.  In other 
words, the rating in the UWP tells you what is the "best" facility in the 
system.  If there is an A starport, there may also be several B and C 
facilities on the main planet or on other planets in the system, or even 
more than one A class facility.  

By the way, there is at least one reference in a Classic Traveller to a
planet with more than one starport.  In Adventure 3, Twilight\'s Peak, p. 
14, the planet Tureded/Lanth is said to have four C class facilities,
equally spaced around the equator. 

>Also, what exactly is the difference between a "Poor" quality spaceport and
>a class E starport?

>From Traveller Book 3 - Worlds and Adventures

D   Poor Quality Installation.  Only Unrefined fuel avalible.  No repair 
    or shipyards present.  Scout base (with refined fuel for Scouts only) 
    is present on a throw of 7+

E   Frontier instalation.  Essentially a bare spot of bedrock with no 
    facilities, fuel, or bases present.

X   No starport.  No provision is made for any starship landing.

