    'body' => 'Alvin Plummer objects to the use of aliens (more specifically, non-
humans, since people from Earth are aliens in Traveller) to explain odd 
UWPs.  His primary objection is that this adds complexity to a 
description of the overall working of the Imperium.  I find this no bad 
thing in itself, but his feeling that this leads to distortions of the 
population distribution of the Imperium is simply not true.

As other have pointed out before on this mailing list, the vast majority 
of the population of any Sector is concentrated on a few high population 
worlds.  One only has to assume that those worlds are populated primarily 
by humans and the balance Alvin wants is preserved.

As to aliens within the Empire operating on starships, they probably 
build and run their own as local reserve fleets or system defense boats, 
if they have the tech level, and leave the serious fighting to Humaniti.

Finally, the empire does not interest itself in the internal affairs of 
member worlds as long as they pay their taxes.  Aliens would fit right in 
with all those wacky human governments if they ran their planets in a 
hostile and odd fashion.

>P.S. Any word on who Plankwell is, and why he assassinated the Emperess
     Josephine

>From "Emperors of the Third Imperium," JTAS #4, p.10:

Olav: First of the Emperors of the Flag.  Olav hault-Plankwell, as Grand 
Admiral of the Marches, defeated the massive incursions of the Out-World 
Coalition* in the First Frontier War (589-604).  Upon return to the 
Imperial Core, Olav personally murdered the Empress Jaqueline I and 
procalimed himself emperor by right of fleet control.  Born 532, 
self-proclaimed emperor 606, killed in battle 609.

*Zhodani, Sword Worlds, and Vargr allies.

I seem to remember that this was expanded on later in a discussion in 
another publication, but I can\'t recall where.  This was not the first 
use of assasination for imperial succesion; that came with the killing of 
Cleon III in 245 (he was a homicidal maniac, so his staff killed him). 
