    'body' => '
erwin writes:
>What bugs me is why there must be exactly ONE starport per system!  That\'s
>like saying that New York\'s allowed only one international airport.  Where\'s
>the logic.

Several references (as well as my independent judgement 8-) say that
starport ratings refer to total capacity, not a single yard.  There are
lots of "Highport/Lowport" setups, with both orbital and ground installations.
There are also lots of published maps with more than one starport on
the surface (one per continent, often).

alwin writes:
>P.S. Any word on who Plankwell is, and why he assassinated the Emperess
>     Josephine?

Plankwell is (the late) Admiral of the Marches Olav haut-Plankwell (if I
remember exactly).  He was the naval commander in the Spinward Marches
when the first frontier war broke out (589?), and there was some problem
with lack of support from the rest of the Imperium during that war, which
led to the later events.

Following his successful defeat of the Zhodani, Plankwell took several
of his stronger fleets and took a trip to Capital.  Not realizing the
depth of his displeasure over the lack of support, Josephine agreed to
see them in person when they arrived.  During that meeting, the Admiral
shot the Emperess and then announced that he was assuming the throne
by right of assasination.  He ruled for about 2 years, then his former
chief of staff rebelled and became emperor due to luck in battle
(Plankwell\'s side won the battle, but Plankwell\'s command ship was
destroyed with all hands by a lucky shot).  There were a succession
of fleet-based emperors for around 20 years.

There\'s a good summary of this in the old Library Data books (classic Trav),
and in various places in subsequent materials.

-george

