    'topic' => ' E versus Poor Starports',
    'body' => 'In <Pine.3.89.9411062208.A17881-0100000@brahms.udel.edu> Mark Clark
<markc@brahms.udel.edu> writes:
>From: erwin@fritz.cuug.ab.ca (Erwin Fritz)
>>What bugs me is why there must be exactly ONE starport per system!  That\'s
>>like saying that New York\'s allowed only one international airport. Where\'s
>>the logic.

>This was addressed in World Builder\'s Handbook, I think, and probably in 
>the ancestor publication Grand Census as well.  I don\'t have a copy handy, 
>but I believe there are provisions for additional landing points and 
>extra starports depending on population and other factors.  In other 
>words, the rating in the UWP tells you what is the "best" facility in the 
>system.  If there is an A starport, there may also be several B and C 
>facilities on the main planet or on other planets in the system, or even 
>more than one A class facility.  

One can make the assumption that the starport/spaceport described in the rules
for a given planet is the best one for that world.  Given that, then it\'s
quite possible to have, say, a class C starport on the same planet as a class
A port (with the class A port being used for the UWP).

However, the rules for system generation described in MegaTraveller (and in
CT\'s Book 6 - Scouts) assign spaceports to worlds other than the main world.
If we assume that the spaceports given by the rules is the best one on the
world, then the only place in a solar system where there can be starports is
the main world.

So, your point about multiple starports on a given world is correct.  But,
only one planet per system can have a starport.  It is this rule I find
unrealistic.

>>Also, what exactly is the difference between a "Poor" quality spaceport and
>>a class E starport?

>>From Traveller Book 3 - Worlds and Adventures

>E   Frontier instalation.  Essentially a bare spot of bedrock with no 
>    facilities, fuel, or bases present.

Sorry, I was actually referring to the class H spaceport, not the G.  And, from
the rules, the H spaceport is a "primitive spaceport with no facilities". So,
what\'s the diff?

