    'index' => 'aa359',
    'topic' => 'XBOAT digest 83',
    'body' => 'I didn\'t get X-Boat 83. Could somebody forward it to me ?

Builder\'s Handbook, and you\'d be surprised how many "Terra-Normal" worlds end
up bloody uncomfortable. Too many moons, or not enough water surface, and the
temperature shoots up or down. By and large, if the sun\'s not G2 V, forget
it...

Now I\'m the first to admit that I tweak some worlds; for a start, I have more
faith in 56th century terraforming than DGP & GDW... But I feel that the stats
as they come tend to be an accurate indicator of what planets out there are
going to be like. There are millions of possibilities, and it\'s sheer racial
arrogance to assume that every system will have a "human-stop" built - a hab
world. 

The rider to that is that I make careful use of a composite table which
determines the miniumum TL to survive a planet\'s conditions. The average TL of a
region tends to creep up, but so what ? After all, _all_ these folk must have
been TL 10 or better, or they\'d never have got to the place (Ancient droppings
excluded). 

I store my Atlas data in a database (my own work, blush) and I\'v applied these
criteria to the whole damn lot. Interesting. Later published stuff tends to be
OK, but the Spinward! Oh dear. Still, only about 10 systems needed a TL hike,
and those not by much. 

I liked the alternate UWP generation system; it feels good and house rules keep
a game system alive. There are other ways, though.

	The War Dog',
