Jo Grant <Jo_Grant.LOTUSINT@crd.lotus.com> writes on UWP
Generation:

X::>Just my addition,
 ::> POP: I always assume that the pop figure does not
 ::>include transients. Thus where you have a naval base or
 ::>a large itinerant labour base this will not be accounted
 ::>for in the POP figures. (There are no aliens in my
 ::>universe. Humans are diverse and strange enough :-)

 An iffy assumption, IMO.  Depends very highly on the definition of 
 "transients".  Armed Forces bases are usually, as you indicate, 
 considered "transient" populations.  But people raise families 
 there, vote there in many cases, and when the government allocates 
 resources based on population, the base is figured into the 
 calculations - because the base is not self-contained, and has an 
 impact on local services.

 OTOH, it _does_ nicely account for the occasional world with a POP 
 of 1 or 2, but with a Naval base...

 ::> TECH: I always assume the Tech Level is the level
 ::>of technology that a particular planet can *produce*.
 ::>Obviously a Tech Level 3 society on an airless world
 ::>still needs to have domes/air-management systems. However
 ::>they may be incapable of producing them for themselves.
 ::>Thus they have to import them.
 ::> This is perfectly reasonable. I live in Ireland.
 ::>There are many "high-tech" things which our society
 ::>depends on (e.g. the busses of our public transport
 ::>system!) that are not, and can not, be made in this
 ::>country.

 But is this inability because of the (a) local level of technical 
 knowledge, (b) strict lack of physical infrastructure, or (c) 
 economic nonviability?  I\'d call (a) a case of "hard" tech level; 
 (b) and (c) different kinds of "soft" tech levels.  In the case of 
 Ireland, I\'d bet that the Irish inability to produce its own mass 
 transit busses is because of a "soft" limitation, rather than a 
 "hard" limitation.  Or are you suggesting that nobody in Ireland 
 knows how to construct a diesel engine?

 Practically, I suppose that it doesn\'t make a difference - but if 
 I were a TL 3 society on an airless world, you can bet I\'d be 
 directing economic development toward being able to supply the 
 bare minimums needed to keep the planet going - food, air and 
 water management, and dome construction and maintenance.  That 
 way, I have a bare chance of surviving another Long Night...
==========================================================================
Jeff Zeitlin                                      jeff.zeitlin@execnet.com
