    'from' => 'KenHagler@aol.com',
    'body' => 'Here\'s a first look at Alliance internal politics in 5650. This information
is subject to change and addition as I think of new things to cover...

Membership:
12 Full Members
5 Associate Members
27 Others (Only the members have a significant voice in policy.)

This does not include the GRA, which if it joins could add as many as 6 new
members. The GRA (Great Rift Administracy) is a six system country spinward
of the Islands Cluster within the Great Rift. It is inhabited by Vilani, who
are at TL12 but have developed jump-gate technology, and have a very strong
economy as a result.

Alliance Council:
12 Councilers representing Full Members
1 Counciler (from Falcon) representing Associate Members
Supreme Commander, Alliance Naval Forces (nonvoting)

Seven votes are needed for any motion to pass the Council. Of the present
Councilers, 12 are human and one (from Barstow) is fteirle. In addition, one
of the Assembly is of the unknown alien race on Garden.

There are no political parties in the Alliance yet, although it\'s likely that
they will develop when the Alliance gets big enough to support them. A
potential exception is the GRA. If the GRA has several worlds that would be
full members, and it joins, they\'d almost certainly vote as a block (and
might take over the Associate seat as well).

A hypothetical GRA party would advocate slow, careful expansion to be
undertaken only when it can be done without risk, economic development,
curtailment of R&D (they\'re Vilani, after all), and closer ties to the Vland
Domain (or Ziru Sirkaa, as the case may be). Later comments will include
(where appropriate) a mention of how a GRA Party would vote. The actual
impact of a GRA party is impossible to determine without a real idea of how
many votes it would have.

There is the possibility that some Imperial worlds in the Trojan Reach and
ajoining section of Reft might join the Alliance rather than be overrun by
Aslan. However, that is uncertain, and in any case will have to wait until I
have some idea of what Imperial worlds are likely to be overrun.

In addition to the GRA, there are several worlds which traditionally vote
together, but aren\'t powerful enough to be considered "parties." These are:

New Home/Neubayern/Barstow
These members were the original two allies from which the Alliance developed.
New Home has traditionally been the senior partner of the two, in large part
due to New Home\'s role as the author of the Alliance Charter. Since 5627,
Neubayern has typically followed New Home\'s lead in the Council, agreeing to
nearly everything New Home ever proposed. During the early years of the
Alliance, Neubayern didn\'t do much in the Council, but in the last two years
of President Krieg\'s administration Neubayern became more active while New
Home\'s power was lessened by a change in government. Today the two members
still vote together much of the time, but on the subject of expansion in the
Trojan Reach the agressive Delaz Administration tends to disagree with New
Home\'s more conservative position. Barstow started out as a colony of
Neubayern, and still votes with them fairly often out of loyalty.

Amondiage/Sansterre
These members were allies even before the Alliance existed, and they have
remained closely tied ever since. They are very cooperative, and always work
out their position in private before announcing it in the Council. Since
Amondiage joined the Alliance in 5633, the two members have always voted the
same way.

St. Hilaire/Browne
This is the newest but most powerful block. St. Hilaire had been the second
most powerful member since the Alliance was founded. It\'s power largely
disappeared during the Occupation, but when the Alliance began expanding into
the Trojan Reach following the CLW it returned. Browne saw that it\'s
interests matched St. Hilaire\'s almost perfectly, and began voting with the
St. Hilaire Counciler. Since Browne is the single richest, most populous, and
most industrialized member of the Alliance, this inevitably gives the two
considerable clout.

Note that much of St. Hilaire and Browne\'s power comes from the fact that
they\'re floating in credits. If the GRA joined, they might be replaced as
most wealthy faction, and much of their power would shift to the GRA as a
result.

Issues
Although there aren\'t any parties, there are groups of members who vote the
same way on certain issues. Some of the major issues being addressed in 5650
are:

1. Power of the Alliance government
Generally, the entire Council favors a strong central government--hardly
surprising, since they\'re the ones controlling it. However, several members
have considerable sentiment at home for limiting the power of the Council.
These members will generally vote to oppose anything they see as granting the
Council too much power. On the other hand, there are also some who favor
increasing the Council\'s power.

Anti-Federalists: Amondiage, Sansterre, Tisilli, Joyeuse
Federalists: Browne, St. Hilaire, Neubayern, New Home, Barstow
Swing Votes: Colchis, New Colchis, Falcon, Zuflucht
GRA: Would probably join the Federalist camp, but this might push the swing
voters into the Anti-Federalist camp.

2. Role of Psionics
Psionics became a part of the Alliance military by default during the
Occupation, and got lots of good press during the CLW. In addition, several
members have active psionics programs. There are also some members who oppose
Alliance use of psionics on the grounds of privacy.

Psi Backers: Neubayern, New Home, Barstow, New Colchis, Browne, St. Hilaire,
Joyeuse
Opposition: Amondiage, Sansterre, Tisilli, Falcon, Zuflucht
Nonaligned: Colchis
GRA: Would definitely join the Opposition.

3. Expansion in the Trojan Reach
The entire Alliance backs expansion, but there are a few more conservative
worlds which prefer to keep it to a slow and controlled pace. The strong
pro-expansion members are getting the most wealth from it, and believe that
the Alliance should dominate the sector.

Manifest Destiny: Browne, St. Hilaire, Falcon, Barstow
Slow Growth: New Home, Amondiage, Sansterre, Tisilli
Swing Votes: Neubayern, New Colchis, Joyeuse, Zuflucht, Colchis
GRA: Would probably join the Slow Growth Camp, but might instead favor No
Growth.

4. Support for the Zhodani
The Zhodani are fighting the Sixth Frontier War against the Imperium, and
they are slowly being worn down by the Imperium\'s material advantage. The
Alliance has so far aided them by supplying them with most of the Alliance\'s
new technology, and by ambushing a large Imperial force. In 5650, there are a
variety of opinions on what the Alliance should do to aid the Zhodani against
the Imperium. Some members favor strict neutrality, ending the aid that has
been given so far. Others prefer to continue the Alliance\'s policy of giving
covert support in the form of technology, intelligence, and occasional
well-timed strikes to divert Imperial resources. The third faction advocates
armed intervention, sending an Alliance Expeditionary Force to aid the
Zhodani directly, strikes at Imperial bases in the Domain of Deneb, and sales
of antimatter and antimatter technology to the Zhodani.

Armed Intervention: Barstow, Amondiage, Sansterre
Covert Support: Neubayern, New Home, Zuflucht, Joyeuse, Colchis, New Colchis
No Support: Browne, St. Hilaire, Falcon, Tisilli

That\'s all I\'ve come up with so far. More will be added as I think of it.

Ken
