    'subj' => 'AM and warships...',
    'from' => 'JSHiggin@aol.com',
    'body' => '    I\'ve been reading with some interest the discussion of the
pros and cons of using anti-matter as fuel for warships.

    The general concensus seems to be that AM is far too
explosive to be a "safe" fuel for any ship that gets shot at.

    Interesting theory, really.  However, it brings to mind the
HMS Hood.  Which ship was destroyed by a single hit to its
forward magazine (resulting in loud explosion, and total
destruction of said ship)...
    Note that there was NOT a great outcry to remove magazines
full of high explosives from warships.  They were OBVIOUSLY far
too dangerous to take into combat.  After all, a hit on a
magazine usually resulted in loss of the ship wrapped around
the magazine. Nonetheless, we kept on carrying large amounts of
high explosive in the magazines of our warships.  "Why?", you
ask.  Well, it seems that removing the high explosives from the
warship pretty much obviated the utility of the warship.  A war-
ship without guns/missiles/bombs/whatever is pretty much use-
less.  So we suffered through the dangers of the magazines full
of high explosives.  We continue to do so.
    I can see people saying now "That\'s not the same thing at
all, though!  A warship works just fine without antimatter on
board."  Certainly this is true.  Of course, once upon a time,
warships didn\'t carry explosives on board (pretty much through-
out history before the introduction of gunpowder, with the
exception of the period when greek fire was carried on Byzantine
ships).  They worked fine too.  But they couldn\'t compete with
the gun-armed ships.  Just as, later, the sailing ships couldn\'t
compete with the steam-powered warships (which, incidently,
added in flammable fuel oil , which greatly increased the
chances of destruction of the ship when a fuel bunker was hit,
and increased the loss of life even when the ship was NOT
destroyed by the hit on the fuel bunkers).

    I could not say absolutely for certain, but it seems to me
that the availability of VASTLY more power to an anti-matter
powered warship will increase the capability of the warship by
similar orders of magnitude.  Which means that the AM powered
warship will probably kick any non-AM-powered ship around the
block several times.  This is reason enough in itself to
justify the additional danger of the AM fuel.  After all,
winning is its own excuse, eh?

    On to more practical concerns, though:

    A 75000T warship may carry a few tons (say 100) of AM.  That
amounts to only 1/750th the target area of the ship, which makes
it a pretty unlikely hit.  I note that the magazine of an M1
tank (or a battleship) is MUCH larger in proportion to the size
of the vessel, though a magazine hit on a tank (or battleship)
produces pretty much the same effect as a hit on the AM supply
of a warship.
    However, some of you undoubtedly think that an AM hit (which
will destroy the ship) is MUCH, MUCH worse than a magazine hit
(which will destroy the ship).  Then, the obvious solution is to
do unto the AM storage facility some of the things done to
ammo magazines in history.
    How this would be done in HG rules would probably be as
simple as putting 15 points of armour around the AM storage
facility in addition to the 15 points of armour (more or less)
around the ship as a whole.  Under those conditions, the AM
facility would be essentially invulnerable to anything that any
weapon in HG could do.  Therefore safe enough that the ship is
likely to be vaporized BEFORE the AM blows.  And who really
cares whether the fuel tank blows up AFTER the plane crashes
into a mountain?  The guys on the plane aren\'t going to get
any deader...
    In TNE rules, you build a containment facility with around
6000 points of armour.  Sounds like a lot, but it is only about
3.2 meters thick, which amounts to a trivial load for a major
warship.  A weapon could be built to penetrate 6000 points of
armour, I\'m sure.  But such a weapon will destroy the ship
with or without antimatter on board, so who really cares?  How
much deader can you get?

    Which is my roundabout way of saying that the people arguing
that AM is much too unsafe to carry on a warship are a lot like
the people who said that the crossbow was so terrible a weapon
that it would make war obsolete (sound familiar?).  It\'s been
said about every new weapon that has been imagined, from the
crossbow to the thermonuclear warhead.  So far, it hasn\'t come
true, and I don\'t think it terribly likely to come true any
time soon...or late, for that matter...;-)
    So bet on AM being used as soon as it becomes plentiful
enough.  People will bitch and complain about how unsafe it is,
but they\'ll still use it, since NOT using it means that they lose
and lose and lose (sort of like the guys who tried to keep on
with the wooden sailing ships after the big boys switched to
steam-powered ironclads - it didn\'t work then, it won\'t work in
5650AD, either)....

                ----Steve H.
