    'body' => '
Re: antimatter fuels...

In addition to Steve\'s commentary about the necessities of having
dangerous stuff around sometimes, and the relative dangers,
I would like to correct the impression that released antimatter blows
up instantaneously with 100% conversion on exposure to matter.
It does not do so.  Extensive simulations run by people who
are considering practical antimatter applications today (the Military,
for one, who like Isp>10,000 8-) indicate that if you have a release
you get a very slow (order seconds) reaction, not an instant fireball.
The first contact turns both the AM and any M nearby into plasma, which
expands out some and has a much slower reaction rate.  You don\'t
get a detonation per se (well, you do, but a lot less than the
full energy content).  You get a prolonged flare.

This means, among other things, that properly designed starships
with AM fuel on board can survive leaks or failures or penetrations
of the AM supply.  You put the fuel on the outside somewhere (thoug
in a shielded container, obviously).  If anything happens, it will
turn the container and nearby parts of the ship into plasma, and you
will be sitting inside a matter/antimatter plasma ball, but that\'s
not necessarily lethal to those inside the ship.  Some of the hull
probably will get burned off, but it\'s not automatic turn-to-photons.

-george
