>A slight confusion.  When I a mean by "jump 2 cargo" is cargo that is going
>to a world that is jump 2 away, not being carried on a jump 2 ship.  Thus,
>while I got a bunch of useful stuff, but I still have a question.  Shouldn\'t it
>cost more to send something to a world that is jump 2 away than it costs to
>send it to world that is jump 1 away.  Or what if you are sending it to a world
>that takes multiple jumps (say jump 10), does that also cost the same as a
>world that can be gotten to in one jump?
>

        Time is, by and large, the limiting line in cargo carrying.  People
will pay for the haste they need....  If you need it there in 2 weeks,
you\'ll pay the premium required to get it there in 2 weeks.  If 10 weeks is
ok, then you aren\'t as concern nor going to pay as much to get it there.

>some specific questions...
>>  Jump 2 Ship :  2 * 2 parsecs per week / 2 parsecs = mult of 2
>>  Jump 1 Ship :  2 * 1 parsec per week / 2 parsecs = mult of 1
>
>>   Jump 4 Ship : 2 * 4 parsecs per week / 4 parsecs = 2
>>   Jump 2 Ship : 2 * 2 parsecs per week / 4 parsecs = 1
>>   Jump 1 Ship : 2 * 1 parsecs per week / 4 parsecs = 0.5
>
>So what you are saying is that a cargo being taken 4 parsecs costs the same
>as a cargo being taken one parsec, if you can get it there in a week, other
>wise you have to give a discount?
>

        That is what I am saying (in my campaign anyway).  It isn\'t a
discount, so much as the client will not be willing to pay the same amount
to have a cargo take *TWICE* as long to get there.  Very simple.  Think of
FedEx and UPS.  They charge substantially more for thier same-day service
than their "when ever" service.  If you really weren\'t concerned, you\'d
send it my regular mail.  Its not that the post office is giving you a
discount, it is just that most folks won\'t pay $10 to have a letter take 10
days if they can go elsewhere and pay $10 for next-day delievery.
        Same principle.

>This means that jump 1 ships can\'t compete on jump 2 lines.  However,
>the jump 1 lines will still be more profitiable (same income, less
>fuel and cheaper ships) and all the mega corps will be concentrating
>on them and leaving the longer routes for the independents.

        Exactly.  Which means as well that the "far trader" and "subsidized
merchant" now make sense...  The Gov\'t has to get regular frieghter runs
out to "Out-past-heck World", so it pays part of the operating expenses to
ensure you\'ll go there.  Same thing with the Sub Liner.
        The Far Trader is more likely to be hauling speculative cargo to
"Out-past-heck World" than just straight frieght, since the Mega-Corps
can\'t be bothered.
        It also means that the independants will have a fighting chance on
the long-haul routes, since they will not be dealing with the optimized
efficiency of a Mega-Corp.  The last thing it does, of course, is slows
economic development of colonies off of a Jp1 or Jp2 trade-route.  In my
campaign, I am using an "Island of stars" approach, where clusters of
systems wind up the higher tech areas, and the difficult to get to planets
remain frontier for some time.
