>    I\'ve been reading with some interest the discussion of the
>pros and cons of using anti-matter as fuel for warships.
>
>    The general concensus seems to be that AM is far too
>explosive to be a "safe" fuel for any ship that gets shot at.
>
>    Interesting theory, really.  However, it brings to mind the
>HMS Hood.  Which ship was destroyed by a single hit to its
>forward magazine (resulting in loud explosion, and total
>destruction of said ship)...
[lots of good points deleted for brevity]

        You are, of course, completely right.  The nature of warfare is
such that you have to keep up with the Jones\'.  The point I was trying to
evaluate, however, was the *collateral risk*.  I think it has been
adequately proven that my initial numbers were wrong, because of a couple
of logic flaws.  Essentially you are safe from a one ton of AM/M reaction
at one light second.
        However, lets look at look at a BR hex map.  A task force is
usually in adjacent hexes to each other or the same hex. While I haven\'t
mathed it out (which I want to do today), I suspect that at 20000km, a one
ton of AM/M reaction will obliterate a starship though.  So, in standard TF
ops, hitting an AM starship might well take out the entire TF;
particularly if any of the bystander ships are AM powered as well.
        Which is not a risk with the Hood scenario.  The Hood explosion
left human survivors, if I recall.  Some of whom were on the upper decks at
the time.

        My gut reaction is that the collateral risk is too high to include
AM warships in typical fleet operations.  I\'ll play with numbers and see if
I am right.  If I am, this doesn\'t mean AM warships don\'t have a role.
They do, but not in a convetional fleet operation.  High-speed raiders,
deep intruders and the like, who will be operating in a "lone-wolf"
capacity are suited to AM power.  Carriers and Dreadnaughts, who require
fleets to be clustered around them, might not be such a bright idea.
