    'body' => '
  There\'s been a bit of talk on interstellar shipping here; I just
  wanted to toss in my own 2cCr on the nature of this shipping, and
  some of its implications

  One ton displacement of anything isn\'t really all that much.
  Even at 1000Cr (the money-losing proposition for most ships),
  it\'s going to take a major chunk of any planet\'s economy to
  sustain it if it isn\'t self-sufficient (though self-sufficient
  may mean restricted rations, rather than what Traveller\'s
  audience would consider a "middle class" standard of living").
  Given this, it stands to reason that what you _can_ produce at
  home, you produce at home, and anything that\'s imported from
  off-planet becomes "luxury goods".  _This_ will be the mainstay
  of interstellar shipping.  Regardless of whether we\'re talking
  freight or spec cargo.

  Rarely, there will be "essential" goods that need to be imported
  from off planet; this will almost invariably be due to near-total
  unavailability of natural resources needed to produce the item
  domestically - for example, if there are no radioactives at all
  available in a system, all products that _require_ the use of
  fissionable materials will have to be imported.  Figure out for
  yourself how likely such a scenario is.  If you\'re playing in the
  New Era (not on this list, I know), it\'s likely that if the
  products in question were absolutely essential, the planet is
  dead, now; if the planet isn\'t dead or dying, the product wasn\'t
  essential, and probably could have been made locally at a
  competitive price.

  So, we assume that most interstellar trade is going to be
  luxuries - except for the small portion that represents the XBoat
  network (Gov\'t operated), the secret J6 couriers (also Gov\'t
  operated), and government officials.  Note that passenger
  traffic is going to be limited to the wealthy, for the most
  part (8,000Cr one-way), meaning that such travel is a luxury.
  What kind of traffic level does this suggest?  How can you
  justify the expense of A and B starports, unless there is a lot
  of in-system traffic - and how do you justify those levels of
  in-system traffic?  How do you justify the costs of servicing
  such a low level of trade?  How do you justify warfare on an
  interstellar scale, or even empire building not at the expense of
  neighboring empires?

  In short, while I thoroughly enjoy playing Traveller, is there
  any reason to believe that it really is possible, even from a
  theoretical standpoint?  Interstellar colonization is certainly
  not something to rule out; social and population pressures would
  provide a strong impetus toward colonization.  But once that
  colony is launched, what benefit can the mother planet
  reasonably expect from maintaining contact - and what benefit
  does the colony realize from maintaining contact?  I contend that
  there is none, and that therefore, there is nothing driving the
  colonies together into any sort of interstellar polity.

  Comments?
==========================================================================
Jeff Zeitlin                                      jeff.zeitlin@execnet.com
