> my initial numbers were wrong, because of a couple of logic
> flaws.  Essentially you are safe from a one ton of AM/M reaction
> at one light second.
>      However, lets look at look at a BR hex map.  A task force
> is usually in adjacent hexes to each other or the same hex.
> While I haven\'t mathed it out (which I want to do today), I
> suspect that at 20000km, a one ton of AM/M reaction will
> obliterate a starship though.  So, in standard TF ops, hitting
> an AM starship might well take out the entire TF; particularly
> if any of the bystander ships are AM powered as well.
>      Which is not a risk with the Hood scenario.  The Hood
> explosion left human survivors, if I recall.  Some of whom were
> on the upper decks at the time.

    The assumption that "standard TF ops" means that ships will
be close together (even comparatively) is fallacious.  "Standard
TF ops" will be developed by the individual nation-states
involved.  Included in the development process will be such
questions as "What kind of ships are we using?" and "What kind of
ships will the other fellow be using?"  If WE are using AM
powered ships, then WE won\'t park our ships that close together.
If HE is using AM powered ships, then we will assume he will not
park his ships that close together, though we will, of course,
pray to God Almighty that he be that stupid...;-)
    I should also point out that the Alliance Doctrine that Ken
is using (or should be using, if he\'s not ;-) ) assumes ships
with weapons that reach out several million Km.  There is very
little need for Alliance warships to be closer to one another
than about 3,000,000 Km, except for joint point defense
operations.  Certainly there is not a reason for any two Alliance
capital ships to be within that range of each other.  And not a
damn lot of reason for them to be within 30,000,000Km of each
other...


>   My gut reaction is that the collateral risk is too high to
> include AM warships in typical fleet operations.  I\'ll play
> with numbers and see if I am right.  If I am, this doesn\'t
> mean AM warships don\'t have a role.  They do, but not in a
> convetional fleet operation.  High-speed raiders, deep
> intruders and the like, who will be operating in a "lone-wolf"
> capacity are suited to AM power.  Carriers and Dreadnaughts,
> who require fleets to be clustered around them, might not be
> such a bright idea.

    Your gut reaction is wrong.  Just like the gut reaction of
people after the development of the A-bomb that aircraft-
carriers were now obsolete (they were vulnerable to being
destroyed by land-based planes, by nuclear attacks (surface, sub-
surface, aerial), and their air groups would always consist of
planes inferior to those based on land).  It doesn\'t work that
way because you design your Doctrine around your ships.  And you
design your ships to complement each other.
    Certainly a "conventional" fleet is not going to function
very well with AM power plants welded in place of the old fusion
plants.  But that\'s not what you should be building if you have
plentiful supplies of AM.  You should design ships to USE that
AM, to work with other ships so designed, and to defeat both
conventional fleets and fleets of AM equipped ships.  Anything
less is a waste of an enormous amount of time, money, and lives.


Les Howie:

> 1.  A question for the group: should this be a traveller list
> thread, or an xboat thread?  Opinions, please.

    Well, depends on whether you want me to shut up again, I suppose...;-)
    If so, then move it over to the TML, which I do not subscribe to...


> 3. If we say that the danger zone for a warship is within the 1
> MJ/cm^2 sphere (which would represent a pretty nasty attack on
> surface features if nothing else,   and ignores the very
> unpleasant heavy particle wave that the rest of the ship has
> been converted to) then a single 1 tonne AM pod has a danger
> zone of about 40km.

    Actually, I get considerably less than that.  As we were
taught in Nuke Power School, a considerable part (half?  more?)
of the energy released by pair-annihilation is in the form of
neutrinos, which couldn\'t hurt anything (except your neutrino
sensors, of course).  So a better estimate would be 25Km.


> 4.   The last alliance ship I recall seeing had 377 tonnes of
> AM on board.  That works out to about a 750 km danger zone.

    My guess is lower, but not much...Also, most warships need
much less than that amount of AM.  A tentative design I roughed
out over lunch required only 60T for a year\'s extended cruising
(including multiple J-6\'s)...


> 5.   SO if you have AM in your fleet, dispersion becomes VERY
> important to avoid a chain reaction.

    Certainly it does.  But I don\'t believe that spacegoing war-
ships will spend much time within that range of each other.  On
the contrary, I believe that if you find yourself keeping certain
ships very close to each other all the time, you should redesign
your fleet so that the collective missions of all those ships are
performed by a single ship.


    I should add a caveat about the danger space of an AM
reaction, though.  I think that GDW vastly overestimated the
energy density required for damage to be caused.  If, in fact,
it takes only a small fraction of 1MJ/cm^2 to mess up your whole
day, then the danger space is much larger than was estimated by
either of us above.
    A further caveat:  1MJ/cm^2 is only enough energy to get
a penetration of 1cm of hard steel (under TNE rules).  It is
nowhere NEAR enough to actually cause more than surface damage
(burn off unprotected antennae, and similar things) to a real
warship.  Even the featherweight ships I am currently playing
around with at home.


                                ----Steve H.
