    'body' => '
	Hawkings calculated that black holes, if small enough, give off 
a substantial amount of heat. They\'re still very heavy, but very dense. 
	A Mini-black hole has a temperature of:
		
		6 * 10^-8 * (Mo/M) kelvin

(where "Mo" is the mass of the sun, 2 * 10^30 Kilograms, and "M" is the 
mass of Mini.) NOTE: the smaller, the hotter! I know what your thinking, 
but black holes created by collapsing stars are too big ( at least as 
big as "Mo") to give off much heat. These mini\'s that I am talking about 
were created at the begining of the universe and may be floating around 
somewere (or created with GREAT difficulty.)
	All black hole have a "lifespan" equal to: 

		10^78 * ((M/Mo)^3) seconds

	As they age, they get hotter and smller, increasing they\'re 
temperature even more. When they reach 0 seconds, all of their remaining 
mass (~2*10^14 kg) is converted into energy.


