    'ts-index' => '1994-11-19.aa435',
    'body' => 'George Herbert writes:

> This means, among other things, that properly designed starships
> with AM fuel on board can survive leaks or failures or penetrations
> of the AM supply.

That\'s interesting. All Alliance AM ships (and presumably anybody else\'s AM
ships) are designed to jetison their AM pods and reaction assembly in seconds
in case of emergency. I hadn\'t realized that might help in battle. Perhaps
some sort of roll to see if the AM is ejected in time would be in order...

Steve Higginbotham writes:

> There is very
> little need for Alliance warships to be closer to one another
> than about 3,000,000 Km, except for joint point defense
> operations.  Certainly there is not a reason for any two Alliance
> capital ships to be within that range of each other.

Well, yes and no. The Alliance Navy ships can be grouped in two
categories--ships that fight at close range (i.e. normal High Guard ranges)
and those which fight from as far away as possible. The close ships provide
guidance for the missiles from the far ships, as well as firing their own
weapons. The close combatants would be the cruisers and battlecruisers I
posted (except for the Orca-class).

The Alliance Navy\'s idea of an ideal deployment would go something like this:

The close ships jump in englobing the enemy force, which has no idea they\'re
coming. The try to reach and maintain a range of about 300,000 km, so they\'ll
be dispersed over the surface of a globe 600,000 km across--that allows for a
pretty substantial dispersion between ships. The destroyers and their
fighters would form another globe at around 250,000km where they can
(hopefully) intercept passing missiles.

The far ships would come out farther away--around 3 million km. These are
mostly high-value units like battleships and fleet carriers, and are the most
likely targets for enemy missile salvoes. They would _not_ be especially
dispersed, because the closer they are together the easier it is for their
escort carriers and destroyers to cut down incoming missiles. They\'d keep as
close a dispersal as they could without being in danger from exploding ships.

He also writes:

>    A further caveat:  1MJ/cm^2 is only enough energy to get
> a penetration of 1cm of hard steel (under TNE rules).

Well, I\'m still unclear on what that means in High Guard terms, but it
doesn\'t sound very impressive. All Alliance ships are required to have a
minimum of Factor-4 superconducting armour, which ought to laugh at anything
that can only get through 1cm of steel. That sounds about like an assault
rifle round...

Don\'t forget the shields, though. All Alliance ships larger than a light
cruiser have them, and possibly that energy might be enough to affect them.
Or possibly not--it\'s worth considering, though...

Ken
