    'body' => 'Steve H. writes:

>> Also: apparently, Terra was part of the Imperium from 588 to ?.
>Quite so...

>> What were they before?
>They were the Old Earth Union, or perhaps the Terran
>Mercantile Community.  Or whatever they were calling the *OLD*
>Terran Confederation (the one that beat the Vilani in the
>Interstellar Wars) at that time.

The Rule of Man officially dissolved the Confederation. (I would
suspect that Hiroshi Estigarribia vies with Zhakirov Alkhalikoi for
the title of "#1 traitor to the Solomani people".) The Terran
Merchantile Community corporation formed at that time, cementing the
trading bonds among Terra and her first colonies. The TMC evolved into
a political entity, the Old Earth Union, "well into the Long Night",
and around the same time the Easter Concord and Dingir League formed.

>> And why did they seperate?

>Because the Impy policies were very annoying, and because
>they could get away with it.  

More specifically, the Solomani Movement was at its peak right after
the Civil War, as many of Arbellatra\'s buddies in the upper echelons
of the Navy were racially pure Solomani. However, her son Zhakirov
preferred to work toward alliances with the Vilani-dominated
industrial interests in the central-coreward regions, and eventually
married a Vilani noblewoman, alienating the Solomanists in court. 
The SAR was a sop given to these folks by Zhakirov\'s daughter
Margaret I; after declaring it, the Imperium generally channeled
development efforts coreward rather than rimward, further alienating
the Solomanists. The SAR\'s independence move was certainly helped by 
the diversion of the Third Frontier War.

>> [Luckily, I _do_ know why they were reconquered in the Solomani
>> Rim War of 990 to 1002... to deprive the Solomani racists from 
>> their rallying flag...]
>
>Sounds like a large pile of what you find in pastures around
>here.  Terra was reconquered as PART of a campaign aimed at the
>conquest of the entire so-called Solomani Confederation (more
>properly the Solomani Autonomous Region <of the Imperium>).

Well, the histories we have do generally state that the conquest of
Terra was mounted primarily for the reason of putting the "Solomani
superiority" issue to rest once and for all ... if they couldn\'t keep
control of their own homeworld, the reasoning went, how could their
claims of historically ordained rulership of all humaniti (at the very
least) be taken seriously?

>Unfortunately (or fortunately, depending on your point of
>view), the Imperium did not have the resources to conquer the
>Solomani separatists completely.  So after they took Terra (and
>exhausted their resources in the doing so), they declared Victory
>(Yay!), and went home.  Which was probably lucky for them, since
>they still had MOST of the Solomani Confederation left to
>conquer, and not nearly enough Fleet or Army to do the
>conquering with.  It is likely that the only thing that kept the
>the Solomani from continuing the war and reconquering Terra was
>that they were entirely too aware of how hard it is to conquer
>a world like that, and had no desire to burn themselves out (the
>Aslan were still out there on the Borders, after all) trying...

Well, the Terrans had just lost most of their "Grand Fleet" at the
debacle of the Battle of Dingir; the histories state that the
Confederation was glad for the chance to rebuild that the Imperium\'s
olive branch gave them. The Imperium realized, though, that the
Solomani would be fanatic in defending the rest of what they had
(remember that part of their undoing was inflexibly defending every
single border world in the Sphere) and that the Grand Fleet would
still be a threat on defense. 

In a way, Dingir was like Dunkirk; the Imperium could have pressed on
and crunched up the rest of the Solomani military, but it decided to
try for a Battle of Britain-style "quick victory", failing in a
similar way (even though they beat Hitler in terms of actual territory
conquered).

>And then began the Imperial Propaganda Campaign against the
>Solomani, which was designed to convince everyone (especially the
>racial Solomani outside the COnfederation, and their traditional
>allies (like the Darrians, for instance)) that the Solomani
>Confederation were EVIL EXPLOITERS of ALL GOOD PEOPLE in the
>UNIVERSE...or something like that.  I note that the Terrans plus
>the Dolphins plus various uplifted apes make for more diversity
>than the predominantly Vilani Imperium, even ignoring the "minor
>races" in the Solomani Confederation", which are probably as
>numerous (and as poorly treated) as minor races in the Imperium.

However, they don\'t make much use of this diversity; note that the
faction which is generous enough to accord all humans "Solomani" status
is still considered part of the _liberal_ wing of the Party. 
The HDV and Pan-Sophontists are considered liberal loonies by the 
majority of the Party.

I think it\'s a bit misleading to call the Imperium at the time of the
Rim War "predominantly Vilani" when all the sources we have state that
it really was a Solomani-Vilani mixture ... Solomani had been
spreading throughout the Imperial territory for 3000 years, after all.

>In other words, the "evil Solomani racists" are a figment of
>the Impy imagination, just as much as the "evil, mind-burning
>Zhodani" are...

Now this is probably the case. However, we all know that the K\'kree
are a race of inflexible, bigoted jerks and the Hivers really _are_
behind your excessive Imperial taxes...
-- 
Erich Schneider  erich@bush.cs.tamu.edu  http://tamsun.tamu.edu/~ers0925
