    'body' => '~~inner_header~~
To: UNIXML::"xboat @ MPGN.COM"
Subject: Analytical Approach to Cargo Costs

Yo,
	I did a article a few weeks back that doesn\'t
seem to have made it out on the net. Bugger.
	Anyhow, the centrepiece of it was that I had
created a spreadsheet for ship design. Or, more
specifically, cargo ship design. Take out all the
bells and whistles of weapons and other frills and
it isn\'t that difficult.
	On the end spreadsheet I could just say "I want
a J-3, M-2 ship that carries 400t of cargo and 20
passengers." It did the rest.
	Having done this I then calculated the cost of
making a J-1 ship that carred 100t, 1000t, and 10000t.
>From this you could derive your mortgage payment cost,
maintenance overhead, and crew costs. Basically all the
standard listed operating expenses for ships. With all
this data I could compute *the running cost per ton of
cargo*. I then did this for J2 to J6 ships.
	The result was a table of the *actual* cost of
supporting cargo per ton of cargo space. Unfortunately
this table is in the spreadsheet and I haven\'t got 123
loaded on my computer just now. (Eeek. I\'ve just checked
and I may have deleted the spreadsheet too! Damn!)
	From memory, Jump 1 freight made a small (10Cr)
loss. Larger cargos lost more, obviously. I was able to
construct a table, though, of "Arnelia Reccomended Prices"
assuming a constant profit percentage.
	I also expanded normal High Passage into 5 classes,
each with different room sizes, steward proportion, and
cargo allowance. Their costs were computed accordingly
taking the difference between the cost of standard class
and the price as the specifier for normal markup. Traveling
by Low Berth came just between 4th (Tourist) and 5th (Student/
Military) class.
	What I wanted to do next was come up with tables for
cargo and passengers divided up into classes and distance
traveled. I was going to wrap it all together and call it
"Merchanting Ships of the Shattered Imperium". However,
things have become a bit disorganised. I wanted to test out
the logic of the rules on the Sysgen universe and my software
was in the middle of a re-write.
	However, the new TTG tools are shaping up. They have reached
"level one" (mainworld generation). This is enough to compute
trade figures. If people are interested in the above data
I can try to re-create it. If anyone is interested in a
"Merchanting Ships" like project, lets discuss it.
	[On business *again* for the next two weeks. If any of
ye are in the Atlanta or Boston area, drop me a line and maybe
we can go out for a drink...]

			Jo
