    'body' => 'IMHO, the history of the Imperium is closely tied to the history of
the Solomani Movement.  The following is my take on all this:

The early Imperium was nearing the point where absorption of
the territories to rimward were feasible, when haut-Devroe
published his "Solomani Hypothesis" in 114.  What started as an
innocent statement that Terra was the homeworld of humanity was
rapidly appropriated and turned into the 47th century\'s version
of social Darwinism.  Cultural Solomani seem to like living on
HiPop worlds, and it\'s likely that the Second Empire and Long 
Night gave the Solomani the chance to solidify their hold over 
the rimward end of the old Vilani empire.  It seems likely that
more barons are made on higher population worlds, so sudden
absorption of the Solomani region could have seriously altered 
the political balance in the Moot.  (DGP made the population
density in Solomani regions higher than everywhere else.  For
game reasons, this makes sense -- it helps explain the heavy
duty Solomani cultural influences.)

Artemsus, intent on maintaining the character of the Imperium
and worried about the situation, declined to absorb Terra,
and stopped expansion at the line running from the thumb of the
Great Rift to Delphi Rift.  He wanted to put off absorption until 
the empire could take it.  There was no Sol Pacification Campaign.
(A parallel with the RC\'s problems.)

Later emperors expanded carefully into the region.  Porfiria
opened a trade corridor to the Easter Concord in 305, and Martin III
finally accepted its\' allegiance in 426.  Ambassadors, client-
states, and a growing Imperial presence became common.

Then Cleon IV overturned everything, by killing the last of the
Lentuli line.  When somebody finally got rid of him, it\'s likely
that the Moot was controlled by Solomani nobles.  With no Imperial 
line, the Moot came into its\' own politically.  It elected the
next two emperors.  Jerome ruled for less than a decade before
someone killed him.  The next, Jacqueline, aggressively expanded
to rimward, although it\'s likely that Jerome was of a similar
mind.  However, Jacqueline neglected the power of her admirals
and the discontent of the Spinward Marches (and perhaps the
established Vilani interests), and helped set off the Civil War.

Note that all the claimants to the throne during the Civil War 
were genetically pure Solomani.  If Solomani nobles controlled
the Moot and hence the acknowlegement process, being pure
Solomani may well have been a necessity to have even a chance of 
Moot recognition.

Arbellatra came along.  The end of the Civil War gave her
a chance to replace a lot of nobles, and no doubt this was an
opportunity to quietly lay the groundwork for the eventual
breaking of the power of the most powerful members of the
Solomani faction at Court.  The plan didn\'t come to fruition
until Zhakirov married Antiama and replaced many of the high
officials in his counsels.  (This is what Norris and Strephon
mean when they deride Dulinor\'s precipitous actions.  Think
long-range.)  The Solomani faction was caught unprepared and 
was broken.  (A concerted action by the rest of the Moot would
probably be enough.)

Then the Solomani managed to get Margaret I to give them an
autonomous region (that included some Aslan worlds she had no
right to give them, probably on purpose).  Zhakirov may have
defeated them, but they still had power in the government.
This worked out for about a century and a half, and then the 
independence movement, radical politics, and the build-up 
toward the Solomani Rim War started in the 860s, leading to
virtual secession in 871, and the Rim War in 990.

With the DGP data files, I did a real rough estimate of total
Confederation population once, and the total population of the
Solomani Confederation (without the post-Rim War divot)
may have been about three-quarters that of the rest of the 
Imperium in 990.  I think that by the Battle of Terra, they\'d
basically worn down each other\'s will to fight already,
and what Terra did was stalemate the war again, but with 
neither side willing to continue.  Before the Second Civil
War and Collapse, it was the worst war the Imperium fought.
This helps explain why the Imperium waited a century to act.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>


