    'body' => '~~inner_header~~
To: UNIXML::"xboat @ MPGN.COM"
Cc: UNIXML::"A.S.Lilly @ bnr.co.uk"
Subject: Casual Encounter

CASUAL ENCOUNTER

	The PCs should have a jump capable ship. Ideally they
should be on a short insystem haul near either a multi-mooned
gas giant or a planetoid belt. Their sensors will pick up a
short/haul vehicle (equivalent to pick up truck) coasting on
a vector near theirs. On a nearer pass or good sensor scan they
can determine that it has nearly exhausted its fuel supply and
probably doesn\'t have enough left to change its course to
get anywhere meaningful. Backtracking its course only reveals
that it may have come from any number of places. The vehicle
does not answer hails or attempts at communication.
	A close approach will reveal that the vehicle is
occupied by one woman who waves a bit anxiously. She has no
vacc suit and is dressed quite inappropriately. It is also
readily apparent that by the conventional norm of this system
she is also *devastatingly* beautiful. She has not answered
hails because she does not know how to operate the radio.
She will try to communicate with sign-language or any other
means the players can come up with.
	The short/haul does not have an integral airlock.
To gain entry the players must either rig a lock between
their ship and the short/haul or take it into their dock
or hold (8t craft). Alternatively they can talk the woman
into a rescue ball (which the vehicle does have) and
blow the seals.
	Once abroad she will thank the players profusely
but say she needs more help. If they ask her name she
says Mlny (the local system isn\'t that fond of vowels).
If pressed for a surname she panics slightly and picks
something obvious (like one of their names, if embroidered
on their suits). She says she is fleeing from her ex-husband
and wants to get out of the system. She has no ids, papers,
or really anything more than what she is dressed in. Any
system they say they are going to she says is fine.
	Any character attracted to her gender is extremely
distracted in her presence. It probably wouldn\'t occur to many 
to even think of asking money for doing a favour to someone
who looks like a supermodel. For those who do she will say
she can access funds in their destination system and will
agree to any price that the characters feel is reasonable.
She is also willing to work passage.
	While on their ship she seems to display an extreme
neivativity. Yet, at the same time she is also incredibly
quick on the uptake. She is extremely agile with very fast
reactions and, as any forward players might find, much
stronger that you would think a woman of her build would be.
Although she appears familiar with no task or skill she is
willing to try her hand at most things and generally does quite
will for someone who obviously knows nothing about it.
	If the PCs stop to take on passengers (since they
were only traversing insystem, possibly on special contract
to pick up extra passengers), they will be approached by
a man named Smth. He will ask after Mlny and wish to meet with
her. She absolutely does not want to meet with anyone other
than the players. Smth will not be too forthcoming of answers
but if refused contact he will attempt to buy a ticket on
the ship. If they refuse he will book passage in a different
name through a travel agent. If they refuse to let him board
he will go to the starport authorities. Depending on your interstellar
law they will probably have to take him as a ticketed passenger.
	If they have registered Mlny as crew then they can
try to keep her in crew sections. She is more than willing to
cooperate. She is not interested in mixing with anyone but
crew anyway. Smth will doggedly attempt to find her but not so
far as breaking Ship Law.
	After extended contact with Mlny the players will notice
a number of incongruities. What first appeared as neivativity
can be seen as very strange holes in her education. The idea of
a book will come as a surprise to her, yet she will be seen to
have a tremendous reading speed. She has no training in ballet
or stage art but after observing some can enact it perfectly.
	Her looks are naturally devastating and chemical analysis
does not reveal any illegal pheromones. She is perfect in form.
Very perfect. Her stats are FFFF2A.
	If she does win the hearts of the players and becomes
close with them she may eventually admit that she really doesn\'t
have any money. She just want desperately to get away from
the man who claimed he was her husband. She can\'t really remember
things that clearly but she knew she was being treated terribly.
She throws herself on their mercy.
	The referee can choose whatever solution bests suits them:

1) Mlny is a genetic creation, commissioned by Smth\'s employer to
	be his perfect wife. Legally she is his property. He is
	very rich and will continue to pursue her as long as she
	is within 6 parsecs of his system.
2) Mlny is a genetic creation, commissioned by the local government
	from GeneCorp as the perfect assassin. She escaped before
	her training/indoctrination could commence. Smth is a government
	agent sent to recover her.
3) As 2) but for the Imperial government. Smth must recover or destroy
	her.
4) Mlny is an android, a bio-robot. She escaped from her institute
	before her educational programming could be completed. She
	was halfway through domestic education and has a fixation
	that the institute is her "husband". Smth must recover her
	but really has little resources.
5) Mlny is an android, a bio-robot. She was created by the local
	system computer net which has grown to the complexity of
	a self-aware AI. It has placed a subset of itself in her
	to explore the human experience. Her husband is a fiction
	to give her drive and Smth is to observe, put pressure
	on her, and eventually repossess her for integrating her
	experience back into the AIs knowledge base.
6) As 5) except Smth is another biological peripheral. He has been
	given the compulsion to love and pursue her, she to hate
	a flee him. The computer seeks to observe and learn, and
	eventually reintegrate.

						Jo Jaquinta
						jaymin@maths.tcd.ie
						Jo Grant
						jo_grant@crd.lotus.com
'
