Allow me to quote from Stephen Hawking\'s "A Brief History of Time":

	There may be primordial black holes ... that were made by the collapse
   	of irregularities in the very early stages of the universe.  Such black
	holes would have a much higher temperatre and would be emitting radiation
	at a much greater rate [than normal black holes].  A primordial black
	hole with an initial mass of a thousand million tons would have a 
	lifetime roughly equal to the age of the universe.  Primordial black
	holes iwth initial masses less than this figure would already have 
	completely evaporated but those with slightly greater masses would still
	be emitting radiation in the form of X rays and gamma rays. (pg 108)

So, you see, the primordial black holes (a.k.a quantum black holes) may still
be
around.

