This message was originally addressed to TRAVELLER@MPGN.COM
and a carbon copy was sent to you.
                    ----
  325-1201

  The (no longer canonical) thrust plates always bothered me a 
  little on the basis of blatant violation of physical law - they 
  appeared to be a reactionless propulsion system that had the 
  effect of changing the momentum of a closed system.

  Last night (yes, I had been "drinking"; my family and I went to 
  the Crown Plaza for a champagne brunch) something occurred to me:  
  Thrust plates weren\'t reactionless - what they did was convert 
  grav energy into neutrinos, and toss the neutrinos in the 
  direction opposite the desired direction of travel, a la Newton, 
  II.  This would have the effect of _appearing_ reactionless, 
  because neutrinos are about as near to non-existent as you can 
  get without actually failing to exist - they ignore almost 
  anything smaller than a small sun.

  I didn\'t follow this up at all; I\'ve got a couple of other 
  Traveller-related projects already in the works (crashing Sol and 
  Dingir subsectors, and seeing if I can rebuild a Terra-centered 
  pocket empire - yes, I\'ll post my results on the Traveller list 
  when I finish).  But it at least seems plausible; my roommate, a 
  BS(Physics), says that neutrinos do indeed possess that quality 
  known as momentum - which quality (or lack thereof) was the 
  problem with the original thrust plates.

  Anyone have the urge to do some _real_ math and decide whether 
  I\'m still soused?
==========================================================================
Jeff Zeitlin                                      jeff.zeitlin@execnet.com

cc: XBOAT@MPGN.COM
----
  QMPro 1.53  Senior Researcher, Regina Institute of Space Technology
