    'body' => '
As much as I\'d like to see a lot of out-of-print Classic Traveller stuff
re-appear in electronic form for redistribution, it probably isn\'t going
to happen because people are for the most part nice enough not to go around
violating copyrights like they wern\'t there.

My question is, what\'s the limit on copyright protection? Patents are only
17 or 20 years (somthing close to that) and although I know copyrights hold
longer than that, eventually they too expire (which is why Great Classics Of
Literature goes for $5 and the latest Stephen King drek goes for $50 for
the same size/format).

So, anyone know when it would be passibly-legal to put stuff like
The Travellers Digest into electronic form? In our lifetime?

Ethan
