    'date' => 'Wed, 23 Nov 1994 18:58:26  0500',
    'body' => 'Glenn M. Goffin:

> I hope that this was in xboat, not tml; I\'ve forgotten where I
> read it.  Anyway, JSHiggin@aol.com wrote that Solomani-Vilani
> mixing was bull, because the trillions of Vilani would
> completely absorb the Solomani in a few thousand years.  Would
> someone please do the math and tell me what birthrates the
> Solomani and Vilani would require for the Solomani to equal the
> Vilani population in 3,000 years?  At least one reason for
> Solomani expansion in the first place was population pressure.
> It seems likely, especially if Vilani culture was stagnating,
> that the Solomani reproduced much faster than the Vilani.
> Moreover, the UN probably tried to boost Terran population
> through various incentive programs once contact was made with
> the Vilani.

    You heard it on Xboat, I don\'t do TML anymore.

    As to the growth rates required, they are not excessive in
either case.  The only problem is the assumption that the
Vilani will grow slowly enough for the Solomani to catch up.
    Note that both groups are still Homo Sapiens, therefore both
still have the same inherent birth rate (monthly fertility
cycles, nine month pregnancy, such like).
    Note also that the Vilani (more about this farther dwon the
page) also have a significantly longer lifespan than Solomani
humans do.
    All other things being equal (they won\'t be), the Vilani will
then have a higher growth rate than the Solomani do.  Their birth-
rate is the same, but their death-rate is lower, therefore more
net growth.

    Considerations that will effect either or both groups:

    1) local population density.  The more people living on the
world in question, the lower the birth rate is likely to be.  In
the early days of the 2nd Imperium, the Terrans (in minute numbers
on a myriad of worlds) would not be significantly impacted by
this.  Later, as Terran population rose (and the Long Night set
in), the Terrans would be as affected by this as the Vilani.  Note
that the effect on the Terrans would come long before the Terran
population rose to match the VIlani population, in all likelihood.
    Note also that Terrans moving to sparsely inhabited Vilani
worlds would not be affected at all.  As the world population
rose from a few million (or less) to billions, the two populations
would tend to equalize in numbers, or merge into a single
population.
    Note that if the Vilani were, in fact, stagnant, that there
would be very few "sparsely inhabited Vilani worlds" for this to
happen on.

    2) Social mores of either/both group.  If interbreeding were
encouraged, then the Terran population would disappear into the
Vilani genepool in only a few generations.  Note that the Vilani
will have a uniform attitude toward interbreeding with "lesser"
breeds of humanity.  What that attitude is, I have no idea, but
it should be uniform.  Terran attitudes will vary, but it is
reasonable to expect that they will be fairly open to such ideas,
given the assumption that the Terran Confederation is dominated
by the USA.  That is by no means certain, but it is the way to
bet given the very near future of the Interstellar Wars.

    3) Biological compatibility.  They are both the same species,
but that DOESN\'T mean interbreeding is a trivial exercise.  Note
that a pygmy and a Watusi are the same species, and casual
reproduction between two representatives of these groups would
be a non-trivial exercise, given the significant difference in
average size of a pygmy woman and a Watusi man.  Carrying a babe
to full term _might_ be difficult in the extreme for the little
lady...

    In any case, further note that Terran colonies were spread
far beyond the bounds of the First Imperium.  So, in those areas,
at least, the Terrans would be free to grow without restriction.
And the Spinward Marches certainly qualifies in as one of these
areas, so it is quite possible that the Marches/Trojan Reaches
area has significant Solomani populations.  Possibly even a
majority.  But in the main body of the old Imperium (in front of
the Claw?), the Vilani should have long since absorbed the Terran
immigrants into the general populace.

    Note that this thesis applies to ANY minor human race
encountered by the Vilani during the First Imperium.  Vilani and
Vargr notes that lots of Vilani blood implies a longer than
normal lifespan.  They also make this fraction of Vilani blood
unusual, even within Vland Sector.  This is inconsistent with the
assumption that the VIlani have absorbed all the other human
races into their own genepool.
   However, also mentioned is that several minor human races have
disappeared completely in the 10,000 years of Vilani space-faring
history.  This leads me to speculate that a minor human race
encountered very early in the Vilani expansion may have been very
long-lived.  When this race was abosrbed into the Vilani
population, it introduced a small set of long-life genes into
the Vilani pool.  In susequent millenia, this importation from
an early minor race has come to be identified with classic
"Vilani bloodlines".  Therefore it is rare, even in Vilani
dominated territory, and closely associated with the "racial
Vilani" since the otehr race would have been absorbed and
all but forgotten very early in Vilani history...

                               ----Steve




