Generally speaking there will be very little difference between a neutron or
anti-neautron stream at the energies which we are talking about. The
present-day
SPS accelerator at CERN produces 450GeV protons, which, on striking a target
are easily capable of producing 2-300GeV neutrons. The rest mass of these
neutron is around 1GeV and hence this accounts for less than 0.5% of the
energy
of typical high energy neutrons today and we already have plans for
accelerators
with 10 times this energy...

The only difference between the two is their interaction cross-section which
will be slightly greater for the anti-neutron beam rather than the neutron
one. Hence the neutron beam has a greater penetration (slightly) then its
antimatter couterpart and is probably preferable since its a lot easier to
make.

I believe that the best way of creating a neutral beam though is not to use
neutrons but to accelerate both protons and electrons and eject the beams 
together - using gravity would be extremely unlikely as you require such
enormous fields (its about 10E37 weaker than the EM field) and if they can do
this then why bother with anti-matter - you can create blackholes and use
those as your power source (matter in => energy out).

Roger
