    'body' => '> The rules say that a jump takes one week. Does this mean that it takes 
> one week to calculate the jump or that the time in hyperspace is one week? 

The intent is that one week is spent in hyperspace.  All calucations are done
in the trip out to 100 planetary diameters.  (I know this is Xboat, but
forgive
me) In TNE, they refined the jump description by saying that the average jump
is 6 days, some are shorter some our longer (by at most one day unless there
is a mishap).

> Also, what is hyperspace? 

J-space is another dimension where the laws of physics are different from
that
of N-Space or normal space.  A ship basically aims it self where it wants to
go, punches its way into J-Space and in about 1 week, the ship is
precipitated
out back to n-space.  How far one can travel while in j-space is a function
of the ships jump drives.

> What is its effects on the ship and the crew? 

Bascially inside the ship, things are normal.  Communications, combat, or
contact with the outside are impossible.  Many people suffer nausea, and
other
"sea-sick" ailments during transition to and from Jump.  Typically this is
taken care of with a drug (Space age Dramimene).  Interestingly enough in 
Challenge 75, there is an adventure that takes place based on Jump sickness.

> What would someone see if they looked outside a window when the ship 
> was in hyperspace?

In my universe, hyperpaces consists of a blur of colors: Fushica, Mauve, 
Turqouise, Teal, lavender and other generaly anoying colors, such that they
really don\'t want to look.  I also say that if they do look insanity is sure
to infect them for the rest of their lives.  So my goal is to get it so the
players dont want to look, so I don\'t have to deal with it.

Others have claimed that it is solid white, or a starfield moving real fast,
(ah la Star Trek or Star Wars).

I don\'t know if GDW has ever defined the effects of space, so make it up.

Rob

