    'topic' => 'Copyright expiry',
    'body' => '  Re: Copyright duration
Let me begin by reminding the reader that the
following is not legal advice, that I do not
specialize in intellectual property law, and that
I am not rendering any legal opinion on the
following matters.  Caveat lector, as the saying
is.
 
There was a question on this list regarding the
expiration of copyrights on Traveller products. 
As to Traveller itself, copyrighted in 1977 (if
memory serves), the rule is:
"Any copyright, the first term of which is
subsisting on January 1, 1978, shall endure for 28
years from the date it was originally secured." 
17 U.S.C.A. 304(a)(1)(A) (West Supp. 1994).  
 
In addition, 
"In the case of ... any work copyrighted by a
corporate body ... the proprietor of such
copyright shall be entitled to a renewal and
extension of the copyright in such work for the
further term of 47 years."  Id. 304(a)(1)(B)(ii).
 
So GDW, Inc., has the copyright for 75 years (until 2053).
 
The foregoing assumes that Traveller was
copyrighted in 1977.  Many products -- adventures,
modules, revisions, periodicals, etc. -- were
copyrighted on or after January 1, 1978, however. 
The rule applicable to these items is as follows:
 
"In the case of ... a work made for hire, the
copyright endures for a term of seventy-five years
from the year of its first publication, or a term
of one hundred years from the year of its
creation, whichever expires first."  17 U.S.C.A.
302(c) (West 1977).  
 
The copyrights on these items would accordingly
not begin to expire until 2053 (=1978+75).  
 
--Glenn
