    'body' => 'Steve (Higgenbothem?) <JSHiggin@aol.com> writes:

>     Note that both groups are still Homo Sapiens, therefore both
> still have the same inherent birth rate (monthly fertility
> cycles, nine month pregnancy, such like).
> [ ... ]
>     All other things being equal (they won\'t be), the Vilani will
> then have a higher growth rate than the Solomani do.  Their birth-
> rate is the same, but their death-rate is lower, therefore more
> net growth.

Just because both are Homo Sapiens does not mean their birth rates
will be equal.  Birth rates have traditionally been higher in the
poorer parts of the world, where lifespans tend to be shorter.  In
fact, the overall growth rate has been higher in those portions of
the world.

You can blame it on lack of birth control, religion, or whatever,
but I think birth rate has more to do with people\'s attitudes.
Those that are "secure" will tend to have lower birth rates, while
the "upstart" nations will tend to have higher birth rates.

--Jerry Williams
