>Date: Thu, 24 Nov 1994 20:58:48 -0800
>From: Nrunner@ix.netcom.com (Archie Tindell)
>
>	Anti-neutrons do NOT exist, because the negative of a neutral
>charge is a neutral charge.... the neuton is it\'s own anti-particle. It
>may be created through different means, but a neutron is a neutron. The

	Anti-neutrons do exist. A neutron is made of of one UP quark
(charge +2/3) and two DOWN quarks (charge -1/3). An anti-neutron is made
of 1 UP and 2 DOWN anti-quarks (charge -2/3 and +1/3 respectively).
	The neutron is a fermion. Like all fermions it has a distinct
anti-particle of opposite parity. (Neutrons have positive parity,
anti-neutrons have negative parity.) Only a boson (like, for instance a
photon or meson) can be its own anti-particle; and even then, only if
it\'s neutral.

>	(anti-protons can absorb and store neutrons, for that little
>extra FIZZ in fission material.........:^)

	An anti-proton cannot absorb a neutron and remain an
anti-proton. Both protons and neutrons are baryons, and baryon number is
strictly conserved. Protons and neutrons have a baryon number of +1,
anti-protons and anti-neutrons have a baryon number of -1. So the
reaction:

	anti-proton + neutron  -> anti-proton
	(-1)        + (+1)     -> (-1)
	           (0)         -> (-1)	!does not conserve baryon number

cannot occur.
