    'id' => '<9411291730.AA04220@internet1.lotus.com>',
    'ts-index' => '1994-11-29.aa494',
    'body' => 'Here\'s my personal theory on J-space.  I reckon I read this somewhere but can\'t 
remember where and I have almost certainly mutated it.  Anyone who recognises
it feel free to let me know.  This takes the form of an explanation given by an 
astrogator to an enquiring passenger on a liner.

It is a common misconception for people to think that Jump Space is one 
definite place that we go.  That\'s not so.  There are a large but finite number 
of dimensions, collectively know as jump space.  These are alternate dimensions 
which exist adjacent to ours and indeed in these the laws of physics that we 
are ruled by don\'t apply at all.  

These dimensions have the property of holding properly shielded matter and 
dropping it out into the \'real\' world a distance from the start point.  These
dimensions have levels of removal from our own space.  There are a number of 
discrete groupings of dimensions.  

The \'nearest\' ones are in group one and they are the easiest to enter.  
Dimensions in this group (called collectively the J1 space) move the ship about 
one parsec.  Any Jump drive has the power to force the ship into J1 space.  
Once in there, if the computers did their jobs, you cruise along for a week or 
so and come out at the right spot.  Some spaces allow quicker travel and some
are slower, some go slightly further and some slightly less.  Thats why a jump 
sometimes takes a day or so longer or shorter.  The computers can pick the 
right distance and direction but we still don\'t know how to select the faster
spaces, maybe someday we will.

The further out groups allow travel over longer distances.  There are J2, J3,
J4, J5 and J6 spaces for definite.  They get much harder to enter the \'further 
out\' they are and computing the distance and direction is much harder.  Thats
why J5 xboats need such big power plants and computers.  Theoretecists think 
that there are more J spaces out there but if they\'re there, they\'re so far out 
we can\'t even detect them.  All these groupings contain a large number of 
subgroup spaces which are \'longer\' or \'shorter\' and \'quicker\' or \'slower\'.

The scientific bigwigs are unsure what happens when a mis-jump occurs.  My 
favourite theory is that there are wild spaces which cross over from one group 
to the next.  If you are very, very unlucky your ship enters a wild space and
you are precipitated into a much higher space than you wanted.  You could end
up anywhere.

Some people say that  _things_  live in Jump Space and they prey on ships that 
enter.  If you enter an inhabited space then maybe all that arrives at the 
destination is a dead hulk with the bulkheads torn open from the outside and 
all the passengers and crew.......just gone

Another theory is that there is a race of warlike aliens which originated deep 
in the rifts above the galactic disk.  This ancient race learned how to stay in 
J Space jumping from space to space watching and waiting.  Every now and again 
they\'ll attack a ship and leave it\'s gutted shell to travel the spaces for ever.

Rumours aside we do know that an uncontrolled jump by a ship with a damaged 
grid or a bad computer will enter a space at random.  It\'s possible for the 
chaotic energy burst to push the ship into higher spaces than they could manage 
in a controlled jump.  Not recommended for the less than suicidal amonst us.

Dying of starvation or ashyxiation light years from the nearest star with a 
burnt out J Drive is not a fate I\'d want.

Of course I\'ve seen J Space with my own eyes.  Any Navigator worth his salt 
has.  If you can\'t even look at the spaces what good are you going to be to the 
ship if something goes wrong?  If you could beat the over-rides on the external 
viewers you\'d see it out there.  It\'s entirely grey and it moves over the ship 
like it was alive.  Like being imersed in the thick grey liquid that flows 
slowly all over the ship.  The longer you look at it the more you think you can 
see things in it.  Often you start to see colours in the shades of grey.  
Delicate patterns of blue and green and red.  Sometimes you find yourself 
thinking that the ripples writhing across the surface of the viewer is the 
inside of a giant throat and the ship is being devoured slowly by some ghastly 
thing.  People go mad easily watching it.  Sometimes it\'s like their mind just 
leaked away.  All thats left is an unthinking husk, incapable of doing anything 
except drool.  Often they rave.  More than one has claimed that there was 
something outside the ship.  A hand (or a claw) forcing its way through the J

Space material.  A face, seemingly of some lost traveller from a missing ship, 
pressed against the screen pleading for help.

One final thing.   If some mad fool opens a lock or there is a breach in the 
hull it oozes slowly inside the ship.  It acts like it is one enormous thing,
it seem very thick and viscous.  If the opening is small it just forms a small 
intrusion.  The bigger the opening the bigger the intrusion.

Back when I was in the navy I was aboard a ship that jumped with a hull 
breach.  We were trying to seal off the section with the intrusion when the 
second drive engineer stumbled.  He fell into the intrusion.  To my death I\'ll 
remember how he died.



 Eric_Nolan.lotusint@crd.lotus.com
    is
 Roleplaying in a world gone mad.
