    'body' => '
On Sun, 20 Nov 1994 STEVEN M BONNEVILLE said:
----start
quote----

Artemsus, intent on maintaining the character of the Imperium
and worried about the situation, declined to absorb Terra,
and stopped expansion at the line running from the thumb of the
Great Rift to Delphi Rift.  He wanted to put off absorption until 
the empire could take it.  There was no Sol Pacification Campaign.
(A parallel with the RC\'s problems.)

Later emperors expanded carefully into the region.  Porfiria
opened a trade corridor to the Easter Concord in 305, and Martin III
finally accepted its\' allegiance in 426.  Ambassadors, client-
states, and a growing Imperial presence became common.

----end
quote----

It\'s a little more complicated than that, but not a whole lot.
Specifically, I\'m referring to the spinward portion of that "rift line" 
in Reavers\' Deep.

In 260-something, the Imperium had enough "interests" in the Deep
to warrant siding with the Principality of Caledon (based in subsector G)
against the Empire of Drexilthar (based in subsector K).

Drexilthar was the last of what could (with some legitimacy) be called a
Reaver State, run by a fairly obnoxious human minor race.  The Imperium
sent in "the Imperial White Fleet," which was apparently off the scale of
what the Iltharans could deal with, crushed the entire empire, and bombed
the homeworld down to pre-stellar tech.

The Imperium didn\'t occupy the Iltharan worlds (except for a base at 
Drexilthar itself), so this wouldn\'t quite qualify  as a Pacification 
Campaign, but it may have served as a demonstration of what the
Imperium COULD do, if it really felt like it.

Of course, with this buffer state out of the way, the Imperium started to
become a major player in the Aslan Border Wars for another century
or so, until the Peace of Ftalhr (sp?). [not that Aslan hadn\'t been 
tricking through for quite a while.  Remember the Emporer\'s Aslan Guard?
Formed from Aslan settling in what became Imperial territory.]

Source for this _Pilots\' Guide to the Drexilthar Subsector_ by 
(J.A. or W. H.?) Keith published by Gamelords some years back.


John Bogan

