To: UNIXML::"xboat @ MPGN.COM"
Subject: My View of Jumpspace

Yo People,
	I don\'t quite follow the standard published
Traveller view of Jump Space but rather that of
some of its literary inspirations. However I thought
it might contribute to the discussion...
	Jump space is a superset of normal space.
When a jump-engine activates it hurls the ships into
this space, after which it follows a ballistic course.
This works best in flat space. Where there is a gravity
gradient (curved space) the ship has a tendency to be
precipitated back into normal space.
	The formulas for calculating a jump are horrendously
complex and take non-polynomial time to solve. However,
in theory, you can jump from any point in the universe to
any other. It would just take a near infinite amount of
time to calculate it. There are, though, derived sets of
simpiler equations that work most of the time (except on
your normal mishap) that can be calculated much faster,
or even pre-calcuated within certain parameters. They
result in a varied transit time (usually 6-8 days) and
exit point (usually 100 diameters from target).
	When a ship is build there is usually encoded into
its mainframe\'s BIOS several thousand precalcuated jump
routes. These cover the normal range of mass the ship should
be carrying, the normal distances, and gravity points.
They provide a baseline from which the computer can interpolate
specifics.
	The human body has difficulty dealing with jump-space.
This is particularly bad in a high gravity gradient. Eyes have
a tendency to see around corners, joints bend oddly, just
lieing with a sheet on top of you can become an interesting
topolocial experiment. Consequently most civilised spacefarers
take drugs upon entry and coming up to exit of jump. This
cuts about a day off of both end.
	[There is one primitive culture that has been accelerated
to spacefaring by unscrupulous agents. They consider Jump Space
"The Otherworld" and the home of their god. Thus jump is a
religious experience. The gods must be placated and think well
of the ship to safely enter jump-space. The crew must be in a
suitble frame of mind. Most commonly they all take hallucinigenics
before jumping!]
	If you try to vary the parameters outside of 100 diameters
the simple equations are no longer valid. Frequently they will
still get you there but often with a large varience in exit point
or duration. Sometimes if the target gradient is missed the ship
may continue on and on until another graident is hit. This is like
finding a needle in a haystack, though, and a ship is quite likely
to run out of life support before it precipitates.

				Jo Grant
				jo_grant@crd.lotus.com
