    'topic' => 'vilani & solomani',
    'body' => 'Glenn M. Goffin:

> Jerry Williams and Steve Higginbotham have briefly addressed
> birthrate competition between Solomani and Vilani, but neither
> answered my question, so I\'ll ask it again:  What birthrates
> would have to have been in place for the Solomani and Vilani
> for the Solomani to equal the Vilani in numbers by the date of
> the founding of the Third Imperium, assuming that the Solomani
> population was about 10 billion and the Vilani population
> about -- what? -- 10 trillion? 100 trillion in -2422?

> Let\'s also assume that the two races didn\'t interbreed during
> that time.  We\'ll factor that into the next analysis (because
> we know it happened).

    Let\'s see.  Assume Vilani birthrate is "normal" for a high-
tech society.  That would be in the range of 1.2% to 1.5% per
year.  Let\'s assume a population of 10 trillion for them.  And
a lifespan of 150 years.
    Let us also assume that Solomani lifespan is 90 years.
Realistically, it\'s probably more, but let\'s assume that (note
that GDW assumes around 70 year lifespan...).  And an initial
population of 10 billion.
    Under those conditions, Solomani birthrate would be about
2.16%.  Which is around the world average today, I believe.
    Note that these assumptions are insanely stupid, really.
This results in equal number of Solomani and Vilani, but the
"equal numbers" are 1,216,993,250,000,000,000,000.  Just a tad
higher than the "reality" of the Third Imperium, eh?

    Someone has suggested that longer lived species have slower
birthrates.  This is true, but the Vilani and Solomani are the
same species, last I checked, so that argument is irrelevant.
    It has also been suggested that birthrates vary quite a lot
by society.  This is also true, but note that the determining
factor seems to be the relative wealth of the society.  With
wealthier societies having lower birthrates.  By that definition,
the SOLOMANI should have the lower birthrate in the Second 
Imperium period, since they made up the aristocracy of the
2I.
    Note also that the Long Night implies a certain amount of
die-back in the space formerly controlled by the First Imperium.
There is not much reason to believe that the die-back was
restricted to the Vilani, though (being the larger fraction of
the population) they undoubtedly suffered the greater number
of deaths.  It is doubtful that their losses were out of
proportion to their numbers though.

    Which, I guess, means that I stand by my assumption that
the Imperium is predominantly (99%+) Vilani genetically....


                                        ----Steve



