in any way refer to electrical charge.  The proton is not an 
anti-electron, but would be based upon your presumption.  The key 
defining criterion is a quantum physics factor known as the Baryon 
number.  In \'real\' matter this is positive.  In anti-matter this is 
negative.  

There, hope that sorts out that argument.  Please look up any \'beginners 
guide to quantum physics\' style book, and look up Baryon Number.  How 
else do you think you get a molecule of anti-helium...with anti neutrons, 
anti-protons and anti electrons....of course!!!

