    'body' => 'Glenn Goffin writes:

> Jerry Williams and Steve Higginbotham have briefly addressed birthrate
> competition between Solomani and Vilani, but neither answered my question,
> so I\'ll ask it again:  What birthrates would have to have been in place for
> the Solomani and Vilani for the Solomani to equal the Vilani in numbers by
> the date of the founding of the Third Imperium [ ... ]

Sorry about that.

It\'s not a question of birthrates, but rather RELATIVE GROWTH rates.  It
doesn\'t take much difference in growth rates when you are talking over a
period of 2422 years.  Essentially, take the 2422th root of the relative
proportion of the two populations.  That gives you the relative growth
rate that the Solomani need to catch up.

If the initial Vilani population was 10,000 times as large, it is about
0.381% per year.  If the initial Vilani population was only 1,000 times
as large, it is less than 0.286% per year.  These seem like very small
numbers, but remember this is the RELATIVE growth rate and is yearly.

To find the Solomani birth rate, you must calculate the Vilani growth
rate (Vilani birth rate - Vilani death rate), then get the Solomani
growth rate (Vilani growth rate * 1.00381), then add the Solomani
death rate:

Solomani B.R. = (Vilani B.R. - Vilani D.R.) * 1.00381 + Solomani D.R.

You can calculate the death rates given average lifespans.  Simply
take the <lifespan>th root of 0.5 (and subtract from 1).  I don\'t
remember the average lifespan of a Vilani and a Solomani (and even if
I did, it needs to take into account wars and such), but lets take
a guess at a Solomani lifespan of 100 years and a Vilani lifespan of
250 years.  That leads to a Solomani death rate of 0.691% and a Vilani
death rate of 0.277%.  Overall, that means:

Solomani birth rate = Vilani birth rate * 1.00381 + 0.413%

(The way I did the calculations, specify all of the birth rates as
greater than 1.)

If the Vilani birth rate is 0.277% (1.00277), which would mean zero
population growth, the required Solomani birth rate would have to be
1.00277 * 1.00381 + 0.00413 = 1.01072, or 1.072% per year.  If you
raise that to the 100th power (lifespan) and subtract 1 for the
original (now dead) person, you will find that the average Solomani
will have 1.9 children (or 3.8 per couple) over their lifetime.
The average Vilani will have 1 child (2 per couple) in order to
maintain zero population growth, of course (which you also get if
you raise 1.00277 to the 250th power and subtract 1).

If there were only 1,000 times as many Vilani to start, the formula
would be:

Solomani birth rate = Vilani birth rate * 1.00286 + 0.413%

(the last term was only altered by 0.000263%)

Then, if the Vilani had zero population growth, the Solomani birth
rate would be 1.00277 * 1.00286 + 0.00413 = 1.00977, or 0.977% per
year.  The average Solomani would have 1.643 children (3.287 per
couple) over their lifetime.

You can play with the numbers to examine different scenarios.

A few things:

o The "average" lifespan I gave is probably way too high.  That
  might be the "average" lifespan for people to die of natural
  causes, but the real average might be much lower (especially
  for the Vilani who have more time to get killed).

o The Vilani would be more vulnerable to the effects of large-
  scale wars/plagues/etc. on their death rates, but then again
  the definition of large-scale would be different for them.

o I wouldn\'t even think about dealing with intermingling of the
  species.  It would be easier to define the higher birth rate
  as a "Solomani" trait and leave it at that.

-Jerry
