    'month' => '12',
    'index' => 'aa520',
    'body' => 'Just wanted to point out that one does not need to postulate differential
birth rates to catch the Solomani up to Vilani population levels.  In
recent years a period of plague among the Vilani has been added to explain
the rapid collapse of the First Imperium.  If one assumes die-back on the
order of the encounter between Europeans and the residents of the Americas
in the 100 years after 1492, one can get rid of 90% of the Vilani at a
stroke. 

In fact, the die-back would actually be much greater, unless we assume 
Solomani intervention with medical treatment.  First Imperium 
Vilani had primitive medical science, due to lack of animal models to 
work with - no genetically similar animals on the Vilani homeworld to 
experiment on.  Also, without animal vectors, many infectous diseases 
died out, so Vilani had no natural immunity.  I seem to remember some 
recent Traveller publications talking about the development of 
wide-spectrum anti-virals as the eventual solution by the Solomani, but I 
can\'t remember exactly where offhand.

Frankly, this one-time reduction of the Vilani population makes more sense
than some sort of long-term constant differential in birth rates, IMHO. 
Look at our own world, for example:  birth rates for Western Europe have
changed dramatically in the last two hundred years, first expanding and
then contracting.  Moreover, current rates vary from the high of some
African countries to the slightly negative rate of the former East
Germany.  Postulating a differential that persists over thousands, let 
alone hundreds of years, is a bit rash.

However, I could make an arguement that Vilani would have a birth rate 
that tended to replacement level.  Given the apprenticeship idea in 
Vilani society that you train to take over someone\'s job, even small 
positive or negative growth rates would soon throw the economy out of whack.

This whole discussion reminds me of how much Traveller reflects GDW\'s
origins in an academic environment and its early focus on wargames.  As a
professional historian, I enjoy seeing how Traveller has evolved over the
years from a one-dimensional space-opera background to a more
sophisticated product grounded in current historical (and other social
science) thinking.  The addition of the impact of disease I\'ve discussed
here is only one example; one can also point to the more sophisticated way
alien races are described and the expanded focus on economics.  One need
only compare the depictions of the Zhodani in early issues of the JTAS
(Evil Commie Mindsuckers with Turbans) to the Megatraveller version
(what do you mean, they\'re _happier_ than we are?) to see how much things
have changed.  


Mark "The Common Cold will always be with us" Clark

