    'index' => 'aa537',
    'topic' => 'Not birthrates again!',
    'body' => 'We may be looking at birthrates the wrong way.  Say both the Vilani and
the Solomani tend to have 3 children per couple in their lifetime.  That
would mean a population growth rate of 1.5 over the span of a generation.

Well, the definition of a generation changes between the Solomani and
the Vilani, so the Solomanis\' shorter lifespans work to their advantage.
If you guess at the Solomani generation span being 40 years and the Vilani
generation span as 80 years, then the Solomani population would increase
by 1.0188% per year, while the Vilani population would increase by 0.5081%
per year.  After 2422 years, the Solomani population would have grown
almost 46,000,000,000 times while the Vilani population would have grown
less than 215,000 times (warning: I calculated this on a Pentium :-).
It\'s probably even worse than that, since the span between generations is
probably smaller, which would work to the Solomani\'s advantage.

In this case, plagues, wars, and such might actually work to the Vilanis\'
ADVANTAGE, since it would encourage them to have children young (those
that were inclined to have them later in life wouldn\'t get the chance).
You could also raise the average number of children per Vilani couple
until you got the number you wanted (if they have 4 children per couple,
the Vilani population would have grown almost 1,300,000,000 times in the
same 2422 years).

I think this might be a more logical way to look at things, since people
with longer lifespans don\'t necessarily have more children in their
lifetime (actually the reverse tends to be true on good-old 20th century
Earth).

And yes, this also means that the Solomani trait of a shorter lifespan
will tend to dominate and displace the "longevity gene" (or whatever).
Natural selection favors breeding, not living longer.

-Jerry
