    'body' => '
Steve Higginbotham <JSHiggin@aol.com> writes:

>    All this is true.
>    I have a hard time believing in a 99+% die-back, though.  I
>can\'t imagine ANY situation other than deliberately encouraging
>the die-back with a death-rate that high...

Well, it can get pretty bad.  The usual historical example is the
Spanish contact with the Central American natives in the 16th cent.
The pandemics of 1519 to the early 1520s were estimated at the time
to have mortality as high as 50% in places.  I\'ve seen figures as
high as 90% for the first century after contact.  And if Duskir were
something that hits like one of the more horrifying filoviri, all
bets are off.  Remedy this to some degree by a more modern Solomani
understanding of medicine -- after the first few years, things
may get more under control.

>    Note that "a small Solomani settlers\' laboratory" will not be
>all that is present on a high-pop world.  And the high-pop worlds
>are where the die-back must occur to lower Vilani populations to
>be comparable to Solomani populations...

But Vilani microbiology was a bit backward, and the trained techs
and equipment needed might not be readily available.  Meanwhile,
the planet is dying....  The HiPop world might also be more densely
populated, making it harder to control spread of the plague.

>    As to dealing with diseases that were fatal to people without
>Solomani immunity, seems to me that a vaccine could be made from
>the Solomani that would allow the development of that immunity
>in the locals.

Not necessarily.  There\'s some historical evidence that some 
diseases have lessened in severity over the historical time
frame, judging by Roman records among others.  One theory is that
a pathogen and its target might co-evolve in such a way that
the pathogen stops killing so many hosts.  Evolutionarily speaking,
it\'s to the agent\'s advantage that the host not die, but live
longer so that it can reproduce more.  And of course, hosts that
survive to reproduce get a chance to spread genes which helped
the host to survive the attack of the pathogen.  And the Vilani
have been separated from the Solomani since the time of the
Neanderthals.

Then there\'s things like toxic shock, and possible Vilani 
allergies to specific antibiotics that normally would work
fine.  This could be a problem if one of the bacteria is 
vulnerable to only one antibiotic.  (This is a very serious
concern today.  For various reasons, some bacteria are becoming
resistant to antibiotics -- a couple of previously easily
treatable diseases have developed strains which are treatable
with only one antibiotic.  The medical nightmare is if they
next become immune to *that* antibiotic, too.)

TD #20 talks about the Plague of Duskir, claiming that it was
a complex infection of yeasts, staph, various common digestive
bacteria, and VD.  This is similar to the New World infections.
They had problems with multiple infections of smallpox, measles,
influenza or typhus, diptheria, various fevers, and possibly 
the Black Death.  The fevers would weaken the victims, and then
a respiratory sickness like pneumonia would get them, in many
cases.

However... 

>    I also don\'t believe that even the "official" history includes
>the assumption that somewhere around nine trillion people died
>during the Second Imperium.  If it _does_ make that assumption,
>then I WON\'T be talking the GDW universe any more...

TD #20 states clearly that the death toll was one billion, over
several thousand worlds.  Even with other plagues, this doesn\'t
seem to be in the order of magnitude necessary for the population
reduction folks.  Terran response was "swift".  Make your own
adjustments!

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
 
