[Good Guys & Vilani]
JSHiggin@aol.com writes...

X::>    All this is true.
 ::>    I have a hard time believing in a 99+% die-back, though.  I
 ::>can\'t imagine ANY situation other than deliberately encouraging
 ::>the die-back with a death-rate that high...

 Yes, 99+% is a bit high.  But I don\'t recall seeing anything that 
 presents even a strong implication that the dieback was in fact 
 this high, except perhaps in extremely localized areas.  Terra\'s 
 Black Death of the 1200s and 1300s (Solomani dating) _averaged_, 
 as I recall, about a 35% dieback in its area of effect, but 
 "locally", there were rates as high as 75%, and some towns were 
 wiped out completely.

 ::>    As to dealing with diseases that were fatal to people without
 ::>Solomani immunity, seems to me that a vaccine could be made from
 ::>the Solomani that would allow the development of that immunity
 ::>in the locals.

 Yes, but how quickly can such a vaccine be developed?  
 Furthermore, what specific diseases are we talking about?  
 Influenza has been with us for centuries, and even so, it mutates 
 so quickly that the vaccine for any given year\'s variety always 
 comes out a week or two after people start catching it, and it\'s 
 still pretty severe.  How is it going to affect a population that 
 hasn\'t been culled by related strains?  How would this year\'s 
 version of the flu affect a population from, say, 200 years ago?  
 What about diseases that we have lived with from our animals for 
 centuries, and diseases related to them - cowpox/smallpox/chicken 
 pox, syphilis, and so on - how are they going to affect a 
 population that has not needed to build up an immunity?

 There are also the things that are simple allergies to Terrans 
 which might provoke a fatal reaction in populations that have 
 never encountered those substances.  Remember, the Vilani were in 
 effect "The Race In The Plastic Bubble" for most of their 
 existance.

 The more compatible a planet\'s biochemistry is with human 
 biochemistry, the more likely it is to produce diseases that will 
 affect humans, and which humans can build up an immunity to.  
 Terra is at one extreme of the scale - it is, after all, where 
 that human biochemistry developed.  Vland was probably pretty darn 
 close to the limit at the other end, where human life is possible 
 without high technology, but where the biochemistry has so little 
 compatibility that Vilani humans and Vilani germs basically ignore 
 each other.

 ::>    Note that "a small Solomani settlers\' laboratory" will not be
 ::>all that is present on a high-pop world.  And the high-pop worlds
 ::>are where the die-back must occur to lower Vilani populations to
 ::>be comparable to Solomani populations...

 True; a Solomani settler\'s lab won\'t be there.  Probably, no 
 Solomani lab will be there at all until Solomani/Rule of Man 
 government officials notice that there\'s a bit of a problem with 
 disease.  Hell, for all I know, that might have been the proximate 
 cause of the collapse of the Rule of Man - the government was 
 overextended trying to combat plagues all over the place - plagues 
 that they brought themselves, and had no idea could have that kind 
 of effect.  Plagues like "the common cold", "chicken pox", 
 "mumps", "measles", etc. - anyone wanna include "Montezuma\'s 
 Revenge" in the list?

 ::>    I also don\'t believe that even the "official" history includes
 ::>the assumption that somewhere around nine trillion people died
 ::>during the Second Imperium.  If it _does_ make that assumption,
 ::>then I WON\'T be talking the GDW universe any more...

 I\'m not sure where this figure comes from.  Elucidate?
==========================================================================
Jeff Zeitlin                                      jeff.zeitlin@execnet.com
