    'date' => 'Thu, 8 Dec 1994 12:20:09 +0100 (MET)',
    'body' => 'Steven Bonneville makes most of the replies I would have made to Steve\'s
posting if I had been in yesterday, so I\'ll just add a few bits:

>Steve Higginbotham <JSHiggin@aol.com> writes:
>
>>    All this is true.
>>    I have a hard time believing in a 99+% die-back, though.  

Neither can I, but is 99% nessecary to explain how the Solomani caught up
with the Vilani? Do we need any single explanation? Couldn\'t it be a
combination of factors? Someone else proposed that the Solomani used
cloning to expand. I\'ve never seen any suggestion of that (as far as I
can recall) and certainly some Solomani groups wouldn\'t use it, but some
might. My genetics is pretty shaky, but what if the main Vilani 
characteristics (especially the long life) was recessive? Wouldn\'t that
make most of the descendents of a Solomani/Vilani offspring effectively
Solomani? Especially when combined with a tendency to ape the Solomani
culture.
 
>>I can\'t imagine ANY situation other than deliberately encouraging
>>the die-back with a death-rate that high...
> 
>Well, it can get pretty bad.  The usual historical example is the
>Spanish contact with the Central American natives in the 16th cent.
>The pandemics of 1519 to the early 1520s were estimated at the time
>to have mortality as high as 50% in places.  I\'ve seen figures as
>high as 90% for the first century after contact.  And if Duskir were
>something that hits like one of the more horrifying filoviri, all
>bets are off.  Remedy this to some degree by a more modern Solomani
>understanding of medicine -- after the first few years, things
>may get more under control.

There were no single plague but a lot of different ones. Duskir was the
researcher who came up with a broad-spectrum antibiotica that could
handle these plagues. This implies that such did not exist before,
regardless of what we think TL 12 meditech should be able to provide.
(Also, I think that such an antibiotica would only be able to handle
_most_ plagues).
 
>>    Note that "a small Solomani settlers\' laboratory" will not be
>>all that is present on a high-pop world.  And the high-pop worlds
>>are where the die-back must occur to lower Vilani populations to
>>be comparable to Solomani populations...

But that\'s exactly my point. It _will_ be all that is present. The Vilani
medical tech level would be far below what was needed, so you can\'t use
them. The Vilani doctors and med-techs would not know what to do either.

>But Vilani microbiology was a bit backward, and the trained techs
>and equipment needed might not be readily available.  Meanwhile,
>the planet is dying....  The HiPop world might also be more densely
>populated, making it harder to control spread of the plague.

Yup.

>>    As to dealing with diseases that were fatal to people without
>>Solomani immunity, seems to me that a vaccine could be made from
>>the Solomani that would allow the development of that immunity
>>in the locals.

How fast? How many Solomani donors do you have? How many doses of vacchine
can your laboratory make per day? How many Vilani gets infected per day?
How many _different_ plagues do you have to deal with simultaneously? How
do you split the manufacturing capacity (Oh, the doctors in those day
must have had a fun time).

>>    I also don\'t believe that even the "official" history includes
>>the assumption that somewhere around nine trillion people died
>>during the Second Imperium.  If it _does_ make that assumption,
>>then I WON\'T be talking the GDW universe any more...

