    'body' => '1) We all know that High Vilani sounds a lot like Sumerian. This
inspired me to look for books on Sumerian in my local
library. Unforutunately, there weren\'t that many, but I did find out a
few things - for example, "lugal" seems to mean "king" (which is
interesting considering the name of Vland\'s capital, "Enlugal") and
the Sumerian name for Babylon seems to be "ka-dingir-ra" (some of
those syllables are probably grammatical particles - I saw the word as
part of a continuous text).  I believe "Shuruppak" was also the name
of an actual place in the Fertile Crescent.

Has anyone out there done any closer looking for interesting
Vilani-Sumerian matches? (I had this zany idea that, after the
Solomani conquest, the very Vilani-sounding name of the Terran hero
"Gilgamesh" (changed to "Gilugamesh") might become popular for Vilani
boys. Remember that the next time you meet a dark-haired man who goes
by "Gil" - he might not be "Gilbert".)

2) I was also thinking about the status of shugilii in modern Vilani
society. One might think that after the Terran contact the Vilani
would get hold of things like Terran rice and wheat, which are much 
more palatable than their "traditional" crops, and start growing them
for food. (The Vilani values of traditionalism and
resource-consciousness come into conflict here.) I can see modern
residents of Vland eating bread and rice much like we do today, and
the gourmet cuisine being the traditional foods (cared for in small
plots at great expense) with their nasty toxins leached out in the
traditional way. Think of blowfish eaters. I imagine a restaurant in
the AAB museum complex where the ordinary citizen can experience their
glorious culinary heritage.

-- 
Erich Schneider  erich@bush.cs.tamu.edu  http://tamsun.tamu.edu/~ers0925
