    'subj' => 'Vilani, Solomani, & plagues',
    'from' => 'JSHiggin@aol.com',
    'body' => 'Jerry:

> I think this might be a more logical way to look at things,
> since people with longer lifespans don\'t necessarily have more
> children in their lifetime (actually the reverse tends to be
> true on good-old 20th century Earth).

        Actually, there is little evidence that long lifespan
has much to do with number of children.  There\'s a lot of
evidence that wealth has a lot to do with number of children.
        And, of course, wealth and long life are usually
related.  But not always...


> And yes, this also means that the Solomani trait of a shorter
> lifespan will tend to dominate and displace the "longevity
> gene" (or whatever).  Natural selection favors breeding, not
> living longer.

        It certainly does.  It also favours numbers.  And the
Vilani have the numbers.



Steve Bonneville:

>>    I have a hard time believing in a 99+% die-back, though.  I
>>can\'t imagine ANY situation other than deliberately encouraging
>>the die-back with a death-rate that high...

> Well, it can get pretty bad.  The usual historical example is
> the Spanish contact with the Central American natives in the
> 16th cent.  The pandemics of 1519 to the early 1520s were
> estimated at the time to have mortality as high as 50% in
> places.

        50% isn\'t really any worse than the black plague in
Europe.  And if you were to kill every other Vilani, then they
would outnumber the Solomani by only 500 to 1...


>>    Note that "a small Solomani settlers\' laboratory" will not be
>>all that is present on a high-pop world.  And the high-pop worlds
>>are where the die-back must occur to lower Vilani populations to
>>be comparable to Solomani populations...

> But Vilani microbiology was a bit backward, and the trained
> techs and equipment needed might not be readily available.
> Meanwhile, the planet is dying....  The HiPop world might
> also be more densely populated, making it harder to control
> spread of the plague.

        Vilani microbiology may be backward COMPARED to the
Terrans, but it isn\'t really very backward.  Keep in mind the
basic principles of vaccination was developed empirically.  Keep
in mind that the Vilani had thousands of ecologies to study in
the millenia before the Terrans even thought about space travel...

        And I would hope that the the HiPop worlds are more
densely populated...:-)
        But, by the same notion, the HiPop world have more
resources to deal with plagues, both scientific and industrial...



>>    As to dealing with diseases that were fatal to people without
>>Solomani immunity, seems to me that a vaccine could be made from
>>the Solomani that would allow the development of that immunity
>>in the locals.

> Not necessarily.  There\'s some historical evidence that some
> diseases have lessened in severity over the historical time
> frame, judging by Roman records among others.

        And new diseases appear all the time.  So?  The Vilani
took Terran microbiology (their intestinal bacteria, if nothing
else) along with them, just like every other subset of humanity
taken by the Ancients.
        The Vilani had 300,000 years for the evolution of new,
improved diseases, so they should have had some disease
resistance...


> And the Vilani have been separated from the Solomani since the
> time of the Neanderthals.

        <snicker!>  The Vilani, like every other official variant
of humanity transplanted by the Ancients, has been separated
since the time of Homo Erectus.  Neanderthal came along almost
200,000 years after the Vilani were separated...


>>    I also don\'t believe that even the "official" history includes
>>the assumption that somewhere around nine trillion people died
>>during the Second Imperium.  If it _does_ make that assumption,
>>then I WON\'T be talking the GDW universe any more...

> TD #20 states clearly that the death toll was one billion, over
> several thousand worlds.  Even with other plagues, this doesn\'t
> seem to be in the order of magnitude necessary for the population
> reduction folks.  Terran response was "swift".  Make your own
> adjustments!

        a billion!?!  Is THAT all?  A billion people dying of
plagues in the Vilani Imperium is roughly comparable (10 deaths per
100,000) to the losses on Terra during the Influenza epidemic of
1919...it\'s peanuts! :-)


Glenn:

> Solomani and Aslan does indeed describe GenAssist\'s solution to the
> problems of insufficient populations on colony worlds:

        Interesting, but not really applicable to the period AFTER
the conquest of the Vilani Imperium.  It does imply that the base
Terran population at the beginning of the Second Imperium may have
been considerably higher than 10 billion, though.
        On the other hand, colonization of resource worlds should
require millions of people, but not billions.  So it may not mean
that GenAssist built multi-billion person colonies.  They are more
likely to have built colonies in the 10 million range...
        On the other hand, it implies that the Terrans may be MUCH
more numerous out on the Rim than I expected.  I have long since
assumed a HUGE "Solomani" population rimward of the Solomani
Confederation.  It may be even huger than I thought...:-)



Hans:

>>>    All this is true.
>>>    I have a hard time believing in a 99+% die-back, though.

> Neither can I, but is 99% nessecary to explain how the Solomani
> caught up with the Vilani

        99% means that the Vilani outnumber the Terrans by a factor
of ten.  90% means that there are still 100 Vilani per Terran.  You
figure it out.


> Do we need any single explanation?

        No.  As long as the total of ALL the explanations adds up
to 99+%....;-)


> Couldn\'t it be a combination of factors?

        Sure.  But all of them will be disasters that make the
"Rebellion" look like a tea-party, frankly...



> My genetics is pretty shaky, but what if the main Vilani
> characteristics (especially the long life) was recessive?

        What a concept!  All their traits are recessive!  How likely
is it that if you sample a poppulation, that everyone in your
sample will have all recessive traits with respect to the general
population?


> Wouldn\'t that make most of the descendents of a Solomani/Vilani
> offspring effectively Solomani?

        Let\'s see.  If we assume that the Solomani make up 1% of
the general population, and assume that the VIlani long-life gene
is both representative and recessive.  Let us further assume that
interbreeding is purely random (race is not considered at all in
choosing mates).  Let us look at the population after, say, 12
(picked randommly, I assure you, I have no idea where the numbers
will end up as I type this) generations down the line...

        We will have essentially three groups then:

        "pureblood Vilani" (anyone with the long-life gene
reinforced);
        "mixed blood Solomani" (anyone with ONE (and ONLY one
sample of the long-life gene - effectively Solomani);
        "pureblood Terran" (anyone without any long-life genes
- effectively Solomani);

        The three groups will be represented in the following
percentages:

        Pureblood Vilani:     98.01%
        Mixed blood Solomani:  1.98%
        Pureblood Solomani:    0.01%

        Effectively 98% Vilani and 2% Solomani...

        Surprising.  I would have expected a drift away from the
2nd generation numbers...probably happened because there was not
an assigned "lethality rate", that is, no tendency for any of the
three groups to reproduce with any less frequency than any other.
        In any case, we seem to have a stable situation where,
for all intents and purposes, "Vilani" equals the percentage of
the original Vilani population squared.  So 90% Vilani means a
stable population that is 81% "Vilani", a 99.9% Vilani base
means a stable population of 99.8% "Vilani"...

        Now, this may mean that I have to re-evaluate my initial
position.  These numbers (assuming I did them right, anyway, and
assuming that simplification was not carried to an unnatural
extreme) imply that the "official" position could be reasonably
close to correct given a marginally higher Terran birthrate plus
an initial population no less than 10% of the Vilani population.
        Note that a 10% initial Terran population implies that
the Vilani must have had a stable population (over 10,000 worlds
and 10,000 years) no more than one trillion.  It also implies
that the Terrans used fairly extensive cloning to increase their
own base population.  Neither of these is really too far out to
lunch for me to buy into (and justify to myself) though...


> Especially when combined with a tendency to ape the Solomani
> culture.

        Unfortunately, I cannot buy into the assumption that the
culture has much to do with the genetic mix.  Though I concede
that this could produce a whole bunch of "Jones families" whose
name in the old country was unpronouncable...:-)

        HOWEVER.  Note that the assumption used here is rather
bizarre.  I can buy the idea that long-life is a recessive
trait, but not that EVERYTHING Vilani (or even MOST Vilani
traits) is recessive.  Note that the above conclusions change to

        Pureblood Vilani:     98.01%
        Mixed blood VILANI:    1.98%
        Pureblood Solomani:    0.01%

        which is 99.99% Vilani and 0.01% Solomani, if the Vilani
are no more likely than the Terrans were to have recessive genes.


        Given that we assume that MOST of the IMPORTANT differences
between Solomani and Vilani are recessive traits that confer
neither advantage nor disadvantage on reproductive/survival
probablility, then we can assume that the original GDW picture is
reasonably correct, IFF we can assume that there were very few
Vilani (compared to what would be expected given the number of
worlds occupied), and that there were rather more Terrans than one
might expect...
        Note, though, that almost all the "Solomani" will look
rather more Vilani than not.  Only a very small number of the
"Solomani" will actually look like pure-blooded Terrans.  Even
assuming we can speak meaningfully of "looking Terran", or
"looking Vilani".  Which I doubt...


Jeff Zeitlin:

> Yes, 99+% is a bit high.  But I don\'t recall seeing anything that
> presents even a strong implication that the dieback was in fact
> this high, except perhaps in extremely localized areas.

        But without 99+% dieback among the Vilani, the Vilani
genes will dominate the genepool of 1100 3I...


> ::>    As to dealing with diseases that were fatal to people without
> ::>Solomani immunity, seems to me that a vaccine could be made from
> ::>the Solomani that would allow the development of that immunity
> ::>in the locals.

> Yes, but how quickly can such a vaccine be developed?

        Well, if the disease were a simple one (smallpox, for
instance), then the vaccine could be made in about a week...


> Furthermore, what specific diseases are we talking about?

        Who knows?


> Influenza has been with us for centuries, and even so, it mutates
> so quickly that the vaccine for any given year\'s variety always
> comes out a week or two after people start catching it, and it\'s
> still pretty severe.  How is it going to affect a population that
> hasn\'t been culled by related strains?  How would this year\'s
> version of the flu affect a population from, say, 200 years ago?
> What about diseases that we have lived with from our animals for
> centuries, and diseases related to them - cowpox/smallpox/chicken
> pox, syphilis, and so on - how are they going to affect a
> population that has not needed to build up an immunity?

        Doesn\'t much matter.  99+% dieback is going to make the
Rebellion/Hard Times look tame.  And without it, one has a fairly
hard time explaining the Terrans as a dominant factor in the
Imperium...


> There are also the things that are simple allergies to Terrans
> which might provoke a fatal reaction in populations that have
> never encountered those substances.  Remember, the Vilani were in
> effect "The Race In The Plastic Bubble" for most of their
> existance.

        By the same token, the reverse is probably true.  Allergic
reactions by Terrans is as likely as allergic reactions by
Vilani.  And the assumption that the Vilani have never had to
deal with diseases before the arrival of the Terrans is ludicrous.
After all, there were 30-odd other worlds encountered with Human
populations.  SUrely SOME of those populations introduced unknown
diseases into the Vilani scene.  Just as the Vilani intestinal
bacteria must surely have mutated (at least ONCE) into something
unpleasant...


> Vland was probably pretty darn
> close to the limit at the other end, where human life is possible
> without high technology, but where the biochemistry has so little
> compatibility that Vilani humans and Vilani germs basically ignore
> each other.

        Which implies that MOST worlds colonized by the VIlani were
more terrestrial, and therefore likely to introduce unpleasant
diseases to the Vilani.  And this has been going on for 10,000
years, guys...


> ::>    Note that "a small Solomani settlers\' laboratory" will not be
> ::>all that is present on a high-pop world.  And the high-pop worlds
> ::>are where the die-back must occur to lower Vilani populations to
> ::>be comparable to Solomani populations...

> True; a Solomani settler\'s lab won\'t be there.  Probably, no
> Solomani lab will be there at all until Solomani/Rule of Man
> government officials notice that there\'s a bit of a problem with
> disease.

        Do they not have a hospital in your town?  Hell, we have
large, well-funded hospitals and associated labs on every other
street corner around here...;-)
        Why do you assume that the Terran colonists would go to
a world without taking along enough medical types to take care
of them.  Or did they trust the Vilani? <snicker>



> Hell, for all I know, that might have been the proximate
> cause of the collapse of the Rule of Man

        Well, no.


> ::>    I also don\'t believe that even the "official" history includes
> ::>the assumption that somewhere around nine trillion people died
> ::>during the Second Imperium.  If it _does_ make that assumption,
> ::>then I WON\'T be talking the GDW universe any more...

> I\'m not sure where this figure comes from.  Elucidate?

        Nine trillion is 90% of ten trillion, which is a not too
unreasonable estimate of the population of the Vilani Imperium.  If
a 99+% dieback is postulated, then the total deaths are on the
general order of nine trillion people.  Actually, ten trillion is
closer, but let\'s be nice and call it nine trillion, eh? :-)

        This looks like a good time to end this thread.  I concede
that with a little work, we can justify the GDW picture.  I don\'t
actually consider the required conditions very likely, but I don\'t
really have too much problem with "unlikely" things happening
now and then.  So, I guess this is my way of saying that no matter
what else is said on the subject, I am done now....:-)



                                ----Steve




