    'body' => '
Does anyone here have an idea on how Holiday (001-XXXX) is celebrated in 
the Imperium?  Besides the Holiday Honor\'s list, that is...

And about the Solomani Confederation\'s version of Holiday, Christmas 
(celebrated by nearly all Solomani - Christian or not - for the last 3000 
years)... does anyone here have an idea on how it would be celebrated?
Would it be - as always - an occasion to exchange gift\'s and wish for 
galatic peace?  What new twists on the non-Christian legends would be 
added? (Santa Claus lives in jumpspace?  Present\'s left in airlocks, 
rather than chimmey\'s?  Or something completely new?)

----

A lllong time ago, I posted something on the culture of the Imperium, and 
one fellow said that the only people/things known Imperium-wide would be 
rock stars and major political leaders.

Well, I wonder.  In aristocratic cultures, the \'tone\' of the society 
would tend to favour the nobility\'s interests, if only because they 
control the big money and act as patrons to the arts.  Art, therefore, 
would tend to be more elegant, stylized and subtle, rather than brash and 
vigourous (ie. 17th century Europe vs. 20th century America).  So I would 
suspect that forms of opera (live, VR, or televised) would be the most popular 
form of entertainment... moreover, that this opera would be layered with 
signals and signs that derive form the older Vilani civilization.  Think 
Chinese opera, or Noh (Japanese) opera, both from ancient civilizations.

So where would the rock music come from?  Well, interestingly, if you 
mean modern rock music, the examples that survive the Long Night would be 
as revered and lovingly protected (with _real_ Solomani singers of 
N.American desent in a _real_ LSD haze, made the same way as 4000 years 
ago!) 

If you mean the thumping beat, crash-bang, \'youth revolution\' attitude... 
well, such revolutions only go with the revolt of comparatively wealthy 
children (ie. white middle-class Americans) in democratic societies.  
Most societies in the Imperium are non-democratic, and the society as a 
whole is an aristocratic bureaucracy.  Moreover, with neo-fuedalism, 
wealth is centralized in the hands of a few truly powerful families (I 
suspect there are about 10,000 high-noble families in the Imperium, who 
together own 50% of all Imperial wealth... ), who value stability and 
continuity, not revolutions.  And remember that the basic gestalt of the 
Imperium is a Vilani society with a large minority of "Conquerors" in 
high positions, rather than a high-tech society settling in a rich but 
(largely) empty land.  (For the first 600 years of Imperial history, the 
Imperial Line was pure-blood Solomani, for crying out loud.)

If you believe that most of the Imperium is pure-blood Vilani with a 
sprinkling of Solomani, the best model may be the Ming Empire, where a 
small minority of invaders rule over a vast and ancient culture.  Both 
sides would place high value on ancient culture, but for different 
reasons. (The Solomani for prestige, propaganda, and to restore some 
pride verses the Vilani... the Vilani to underline their superior, 
civilized nature vs. the Solomani barbarians.)  Interesting, Solomani Rock 
Music would transmigify from a banner of the sexual revolution to a 
banner of Solomani warrior\'s!  An interesting development... 


If, in contrast, you believe in a near equal split between Vilani and 
Solomani, _and_ assume that the Solomani always love to press the 
boundary\'s (I thing that this is the offical GDW Imperium), there would 
be less formal, stylized music and cultures (though they would still 
dominate), and more openings for "rebellious youth" culture\'s, great sea 
changes in public attitudes, and the iron grip of Tradition would be 
weakened, though still greater than today.  Perhaps Europe between the 
discovery of the America\'s (1492) but before the French Revolution (1783) is 
the best model of this society.  

[I favour this viewpoint... it would allow for a Dulinor, who not only 
wanted the Throne, but to totally rebuild the Imperium.  It would also 
account for the continued allegance of many billions to the mad Lucan] 

Of course, in both instances these are rather general gudelines, with 
lots of flexibility when it comes to individual worlds.  


Alvin Plummer
(Among the Solomani Conquers!)

P.S. And about those 10,000 families who own 50% of Imperial wealth... 
     
With THAT kind of wealth, it\'s likely that they form the backbone of 
Imperial society, and have final say on what - or what doesn\'t - happen 
in it.  NOT the academic\'s, who serve them.  NOT the Megacorps, which are 
owned and controlled by these people.  The Imperial Navy may have a real say
on what happens, but is \'a step behind\', if you will, to the high nobility.
And there are no Imperium-wide religions to challange these pepole, 
although there _is_ an ideology that can fight them off... the 
"Rule-of-Man" belief.
