Hi,
I promised a while back I\'d post a short note on Zhodani combat armor
relating to the Zhodani NPC, Piebzhde-atl, that I\'d posted earlier.
(Xboat digest 107) This information comes almost totally from CT Aliens
Module 4, Zhodani. I won\'t post the whole thing which should keep me safe
on copyright grounds. If you can find a copy, it\'s interesting, but not
up to the quality of the MT Alien books, I\'m led to believe. As far
as I know though, it\'s the only big source of Zhodani information,
with Expedition to Zhodane containing only a subset of the info
therein (no news for you people who have all this stuff).

Anyway, to quote the opening paragraph on Zhodani combat armor,
"One of the most distinctive and characteristic pieces of Zhodani
equipment is the ever-present Zhodani-style combat armor.
Recognizable by its clamshell helmet (which splits down the center to
open), Zhodani combat armor is a standard issue piece of military
equipment found in nearly every Zhodani military unit."

The immediate implication of this is that Piebzhde is well advised
not to take it out of the well-locked box he keeps it in if he\'s in
the Marches and looking to keep his life. He avoids wearing it in
general and due to its difficulty to put on, only wears it knowing
he\'s going into combat and won\'t be seen by very many people. People
who are going to live, that is. If necessary, he can make a
telepathic assault to wipe the memory of anyone who sees him in it.

His set of armor is standard guards model armor. It provides
protection per the combat armor column in the combat tables and can
function as a vacc suit for short periods of time. To quote, "Guards
armor is a specially produced model which has been designed and
tested for its ability to enhance (or not hinder) psionic activity.
Its mass and bulk has been reduced to provide the least hindrance to
teleportation." The armor also contains psionic shielding which can
be de/activated psionically. The glove palms can be removed for
activities that require direct contact. It has a multi-channel
communicator capable of handling 5 channels with a 50km range.

The armor also has the following built-in capabilities:
 - Filter for tainted atmospheres
 - switchable IR/Image Enhancement faceplate.
    (Image Enhancement as per all those green nightime CNN shots)
 - Chameleon Surface (prevents IR detection)
 - Magnetic boot soles (for zero-g operations)
 - external sensors (temperature, atmosphere, pressure, etc)

The armor has a base weight of 6kg. (miracles of technology, eh?)

Piebzhde also carries several several attachments which can be
fitted quickly (< 5 minutes) if need be:
 - Oxygen tanks good for up to 6 hours (5kg)
 - grav pack (as per a grav belt) (10kg, when off)
   (the grav pack is good for about 2 hours without an extra
    powerpack)
 - holo display computer (allows computer generated heads-up display
    in the helmet; 2kg belt module)

If the referee is feeling especially over-zealous, the armour is also
available as battle dress, doubling the wearer\'s strength and giving
unlimited endurance (but not for combat hits). This raises the base
weight to 22kg.

You may think "This is sheer overkill munchkinism!", but it isn\'t
necessarily so. Piebzhde doesn\'t exactly wear the armor to do
everyday tasks like going to the bathroom. It takes 3 minutes under
the best conditions to put on (for him). Under adverse conditions (or
if someone else is trying to put it on) it can take 5 or more
minutes.  (This may not seem like long, but when you\'re under fire, I
figure 5 minutes is 4 minutes and 59 seconds too long). Piebzhde isn\'t
a mercenary, he is an intelligence officer. He won\'t wear the armor
anywhere he thinks there\'s Imperial troops who have been through more
than a day of basic training. Generally speaking, Solomani troops
aren\'t briefed on Zhodani soldiers and tactics - after all, why would
they be? Piebzhde isn\'t too cautious about showing friendly PCs his
armor, especially if he knows he will be with them a while to give
him an opportunity to wipe their memories.

The armor is Piebzdhe\'s insurance to make sure he doesn\'t get stuck
in any nasty situations. He will always try to make sure the trunk he
keeps it in is easily accessible (and locked). He will also go to
long lengths to recover it if lost. He most certainly not let a PC
borrow it.

That\'s, uh, it, in a rather large nutshell.


On an unrelated note, I got a copy of K\'kree and the cover is
unstapled on it, but even wierder, on the back, in the write up it
says "K\'kree, Traveller Alien Module 1", but on the front in a big
title, it says "TRAVELLER Alien Module 2". Whoops.

Ethan
