  {
    'body' => 'Alvin wrote this on the Traveller List. I am replying
to it on XBOAT because we are all such cool dudes and
TNE is just so crass...

>What is the place of languages in Traveller (Regency or Wilds),
>and how would I role-play it?
	When the characters don\'t know the language I usually
make them try to communicate with grunts and hand-waving. Where
they might have some knowledge or some commonality I restrict
them to the number of syllables they might use.
	For example, if they have started a language course
in Scout (Scout, Navy, Merchant, and Army are all seperate
languages in my universe) they might be able to communicate
in that in works of one syllable. When they have, say,
Scout-0, skill level I let them use two syllables, etc.

>TRANSLATORS: First off, living translators are 
>most valuable in _Written_ material (which regular
>TNE translators are useless, being angled for speech). 
>The more subtle and specialized the material, the
>more needful your living translator is.  
	I disagree totally. Automated translation is 
currently in its infancy (Guess what the branch of my
company that I work for does: translation! Guess something
we\'re very interested in: translation software!) however
it is improving and as the capacity for storage and
processing improves it will rise to an acceptable level.
But *only* for written matter! With current technology
we can barely interpret speech. Suppose we bridge that
gap, then we can pipe the output through our textual
translators.
	This, however, has many drawbacks. The amount of
information conveyed by tone is huge. Not only that but
in spoken language we use coloquialisms or shortcuts
*all* the time. Written language tends to be a bit more
formal. Believe me, I am very concious of this. I frequently
have to deal with people whose English skills are not that
of a native and I have to be very careful about the language
I use so that I can be understood.

	In my Traveller campaign the characters had a
read/write lead attached to their optic and aural nerves.
They could plug this into a hand computer. One of them
spent some time configuring their translation software
so that it would scan the incoming image/wave, identify
it by language, and then overlay the translation to the
brain. Pretty cool, but not always 100% accurate...

				Jo
