>   From my partial grip on history, my classification of
> \'good/bad\' wars can be cut down to this...

	Fascinating.  I\'d love to argue definitions here.  But
I won\'t...  Now...

> So much for preamble. 
> My question is: how can an interstellar society (or any
> society) tell the difference between a Pyrric War and either a
> Good War or a Political War?

    You can\'t.  You can\'t tell the difference between wars until
after the fact.


> Incidentally, at what point in the Final War should the
> combatants realized that victory is either unattainable or not
> worth the price, and organized a general ceasefire?

    What is "worth the price"?  Dulinor would probably have
considered any final victory over Lucan "a bargain, the best I
ever had".  Ditto for Strephon, I think.
    The rest of the Final War was a waste of time and effort for
pretty much everyone involved, of course.
    Or were you talking about the REAL "Final War"?  The one
between Yaskaydroy and the kids? ;-)


> B: Interstellar strategy

> In my own private universe, a largely TL C government (Gov1),
> about a sector in size, is planning to attack another gov\'t at
> TL E-F (Gov2).
> Assuming that the war is  - certain to happen in 10 years
>                           - unavoidable
>                           - basically Political, with
>                             Ideological (racial) overtones
> What advise would you give Gov1?

    Surrender, making the best peace possible.  I am a long way
from an expert on TNE rules (yet), but from what I have seen,
there has been no fundamental change in the relations between
TL\'s.  Sure, the technologies are different, but so what?  The
rate that capabilites change as TL goes up (or down) is pretty
close to where it always was.
    Which is a roundabout way of saying that the TL12 lads are
going to lose this war in a big way.  Note, if you haven\'t
already, that TL14 ships are, ton for ton, cheaper than TL12
ships by a factor of around 50%.  So the differences in the
industrial bases of the two powers will be cancelled out by the
differences in cost of ships.  And, ton for ton, the TL14 ships
(if well designed) will be about ten times as effective as the
TL12 ships...


> Statistics: 
> Gov1 has about 150% the people of Gov2

    Useless advantage, given the differences in ship costs.

> Gov1 is about a sector in size, but Gov2 is about a sector and a half
> Gov1\'s population is evenly spread out compared to Gov2, which
> have two \'high-pop areas\' and vast areas of low-pop and no-pop systems.

    Big advantage for Gov2.  They only have to defend a small
area (their high-pop areas), while Gov1 will be losing industrial
base in approximately direct proportion to their world losses.


> Both governments have existed for about 900 years; Gov1 was
> more powerful for the first 400 years, Gov2 since then. 

    Irrelevant to the issue.


> Gov1 is primarily TL C, but has high-pop systems from TL A to TL F.
> Gov2 is primarily TL E, with systems ranging from TL D to TL F.

    Here is where the equalizer can be fit in.  Depending on the
relative distributions of TL15 worlds/populations, of course. 
Note that, to all intents and purposes, the TL15 worlds will
dominate both polities, unless they are VERY small.  And
whichever side has the most TL15 people will probably win the
war.
    Note that a single high-pop TL15 world pretty much makes the
polity a TL15 polity, NOT a TL14 (or TL12) polity.


> There is a large buffer state between them, about 2 subsectors
> in size, at TL D-F.  An ally of Gov1, but more like U.S./Japan
> rather than U.S./Britain.  It has no love for Gov2, but does
> not wish to commit it\'s limited forces unless certain of
> victory.  Moreover, it does not fully trust Gov1.

    Probably irrelevant, but note that the war will not occur
without at least the tacit permission of the buffer state.  In
fact, I would expect that the attacked party (Gov2) will pretty
much automatically consider the buffer to be on the side of the
aggressor if the buffer allows the aggression to occur without
fighting back.  And if it DOES resist the passage of Gov1\'s
fleets, then Gov1 will never get around to fighting Gov2...;-)


> Gov1 is a unitary state, Gov2 is more like a federation of
> nations.

    Probably irrelevant to the issue.


> So far, the only thing that I have come up with is that Gov1
> should focus on maximising their (relatively recent) TL F
> capasity for electronic warfare, to provide an element of
> equality when it comes to sensors, decoys, etc.

    That is about the best you can do.  It probably will NOT be
enough.  Note that if the war is inevitable within ten years,
then Gov1 should spend the next nine years preparing for the war.


> Moreover, I want to leverage the numerical superority of Gov1\'s
> navy, but how?

    There is no numerical superiority.  Or very little.  The only
numerical superiority will be if Gov2 designs EXPENSIVE ships. 
In which case Gov2\'s ships will so badly outclass Gov1\'s ships
that mere numbers will be irrelevant (Note that New Home Wasp in
my late TCS game - one Wasp could defeat the entire fighter
complement of the Neubayern Fleet, all 20,000-odd of them).
Quality counts.  And in Trav (all incarnations to date), quality
usually means TL, and very little else.


> (Incidentally, I\'m using TNE stat\'s, not Trillion Credit
> Squadron)

    What does the one (TNE) have to do with the other (TCS)?  TCS
is basically system-independent.  All it provides is a campaign
system for interstellar wars.  It works equally well with
Classic, MT, and TNE.  And could be adapted to GURPS Space with
little difficulty...

> (Does anyone here read Dragon?)

    Yes.

                                         ----Steve H.

NOTE:  I am ignoring the possibility of genocidal war by either
power.  Based on earlier incarnations of Trav, a genocidal war is
virtually impossible to defend against.  That changes SLIGHTLY in
TNE, but I still would not bet too much on any government
surviving long against attacks meant to kill as many people as
possible, as quickly as possible.

