    'body' => '>A: Pyrric Wars
>   From my partial grip on history, my classification of \'good/bad\' wars
>can be cut down to this...

With the wise advice of someone else, I too won\'t argue your definitions
for the sake of bandwidth. Good War/Bad War is pretty subjective - History
is written by the victor. . . and subsequently rewritten by the grandkids
;)

>Assuming that the war is  - certain to happen in 10 years
>                          - unavoidable
>                          - basically Political, with Ideological (racial)
>                            overtones
>What advise would you give Gov1?

"Certain to happen" and "unavoidable" are synonomous, neh? Other than those
stipulations, my advise would be "don\'t do it".

Starting with the assumption that this will be a conventional war, I second
the notion that gov1 prepare extensively for war as much as it can. Hitler
spent 6 years between attaining office and attacking Poland, and practiced
by annexing countries that, unfortunately, no one cared about. Gov1 needs
to anticipate as many of gov2\'s stratagems, and have as advanced a military
as possible - which means tactics and discipline, not just toys.

How many of gov2\'s low/no-pop worlds are still uses? That is, do any of
them have vital resources? I would assume so, otherwise they wouldn\'t claim
them (nost of them, anyway). In attacking, I would advise gov1 to attack
small, undefended worlds that have vital resources - take the oil & wheat
fields, basically. If you do that, you may be able to squeeze the hi-pop
worlds that you won\'r be able to take.

BTW, in response to Merrick\'s comments on how the TL/econ superiority of
gov2 neutralizes gov1\'s numerical superiority. . .there are a number of
reasons that may not be as true as imagined. Gov2 is a federation - I
imagine that while there may be a "Grand Navy", a good number of the
vessels will be provided by the member-states, at whatever TL they have. If
Gov1 attacks the planets it out-classes tech-wise, they\'ll fair better than
attacking their tech-equals and superiors. Eat what you can first. Besides
which, they may not have devoted that much money to lots of high-tech
ships; Many nations facing less advanced opponents settled for fewer
numbers but more advanced weaponry. IMHO it\'s almost axiomatic that
high-tech means smaller numers.

>There is a large buffer state between them, about 2 subsectors in size,

Annex them.
This will put gov2 on alert, so don\'t wait too long before continuing the
attack. Hitler walked through Belgium to get to France; Gov1 can do the
same.

>So far, the only thing that I have come up with is that Gov1 should focus
>on maximising their (relatively recent) TL F capasity for electronic
>warfare, to provide an element of equality when it comes to sensors,

They should do more. Drill, drill, drill. Each soldier has to be so
well-trained that he is better than five enemy soldiers. Officers need to
know tactics in order to counter them better on the battlefield.

>Moreover, I want to leverage the numerical superority of Gov1\'s navy, but
>how?

Blitz. Pick some poor-defended but important world and throw everything you
can at it. Repeat as often as needed.

Of course, all of above assumes conventional war. If you just want to kill
people (which I doubt; the animosity is likely due to gov2\'s surpassing of
gov1\'s economy and technology, meaning gov1 would like to capture those
resources) then go cheap. Throw jump drives on missile launchers; have them
jump to system, launch a whole lot of missiles (nuclear or antimatter
tipped) and blow up the planet(s).

You could also simply practice an isiduous propaganda war - inciting riots,
social discord, and so on. . .maybe even locate nationals of gov1 in gov2
territory, and have them complain abot being ill-treated by gov2, giving
gov1 an excuse to invade. . .

